<H1>Today's Chemist at Work</h1>
<h2>January 1997</h2>
Today's Chemist at Work, <b>1997</b>, 6<i>(1)</i>, 13-15.
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1997 by the American Chemical Society.
<hr noshade></h5>

<center><h3><font color="red">THE EVOLUTION OF CHEMCENTER</font></h3>
</center>
ChemCenter may be the newest electronic
information service from ACS, but it is certainly not the first. In the
1960s, before the Internet existed, CAS had already computerized the
registration of new chemical substances, and this became one of the
first scientific databases available for remote online searching. In
the early 1980s, in cooperation with scientific organizations in Europe
and Japan, CAS developed the STN International Network to offer
searching through a graphically distributed network that to this day
remains unique in many respects.
</P>


<P>Of course, something as ambitious and complex as ChemCenter is
never really complete, and new material and contributors are being
added every day. Lorrin Garson, chief technology officer for ACS
Publications, has been involved in the development and use of computer technology at ACS since 1974. He says, "We've been working on the
delivery of electronic products for the whole time I've been here."
</P>


It all started by creating databases to store the information
in the ACS journals, and even though there was no viable technology to
deliver the information electronically at the time, he says, "It was
well understood that we would eventually do this." Great technology
like the Web, super PCs for the masses, HTML (hypertext markup
language), and all the other goodies that we take for granted today
were not even dreamed of in the early seventies. Although ChemCenter
was put together in record time, Garson points out that it was "the
culmination of over twenty years of work, and not something that
happened overnight."
</P><br><br>

<h3><a href="peel.html">Return to Article</a></h3>

</BODY>
