<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TCAW 1/97 Peeling the ACS Onion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H1>Today's Chemist at Work</h1>
<h2>January 1997</h2>
Today's Chemist at Work, <b>1997</b>, 6<i>(1)</i>, 13-15.
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1997 by the American Chemical Society.
<hr noshade></h5>
<font color="B22222"><center><h1><big>PEELING THE ACS ONION</big></h1>
</center></font>

<img src="onion.gif" align=left hspace=5> 
<font color="green"><h2><i>Until recently, there was no single source that 
could provide
information on the whole ACS (American Chemical Society) to its members
and to the world at large. Well, that's all over now - thanks to
ChemCenter! Surfing ChemCenter is something like peeling an onion layer
by layer . . . except it becomes bigger and bigger</i></h2></font>

<center><h3><a href="auth.html">Robert T. Martinott</h3></a></center>
<p>The American Chemical Society was founded
in 1876 and, like the science and industry it serves, ACS has been
growing ever since. Today, it is the largest scientific society in the
world devoted to a single discipline, offering an almost bewildering
array of resources, products, and services to the chemical community.
Technical databases and journals, books, magazines, advisories, career
guidance, and other resources are available to members and other
interested parties. However, it has always been difficult, for me at
least, to fully appreciate the scope of ACS and the myriad departments
and services it comprises. Of course, the information has always been
there - somewhere. 
</P>


<P>Every division and product area of the Society produces many brochures,
booklets, direct mailings, and other material to let you know what is
going on and what is available. Some divisions, notably the ACS
Publications Division and Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS), have had
Web home pages on the Internet for almost two years. Until recently,
however, there was no single source that could provide information on
the whole ACS to its members and to the world at large. Well, that's
all over now!
</P>

<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">OPEN SESAME</font></h3> 
Enter ChemCenter, an "open sesame," not only to ACS but to
the whole spectrum of chemistry, chemical-related data, education, and
products, and even to the Internet universe beyond. Simply punch in
<b><a href="http://www.chemcenter.org">http://www.chemcenter.org</a></b>  on your Web browser and be impressed - I know
that I was. Surfing ChemCenter is something like peeling an onion layer
by layer, with one major difference: Unlike the onion that gets
progressively smaller as you go, the more you peel ChemCenter, the
bigger it becomes. In fact, ChemCenter could become the one-stop
shopping URL (uniform resource locator) for all your professional and
personal needs. 
</P>


<P>ChemCenter is up and running largely thanks to the efforts of staff at
CAS in Columbus, OH, the ACS Publications Division, and the Information
Services group at ACS in Washington, DC. Last summer, they were faced
with the monumental task of having to create an umbrella home page for
all of ACS, and it was wanted yesterday. In a remarkably short time,
ChemCenter was completed and online in time for the ACS Fall National
Meeting in Orlando, FL. 
</P>


<P>During the initial implementation, staff in Columbus focused on
developing the overall technical infrastructure while staff in
Washington focused on scientific and technical content. CAS was able to
draw on decades of experience in electronic information retrieval <b>(see
sidebar)</b>. 
</P>

<hr noshade>
<h3>TO SIDEBAR: <a href="evol.html">The Evolution of ChemCenter</a></h3>
<hr noshade>


<P>A major problem has been the sheer size of a full-scale
production system. "It is one thing to put up an occasional article
from a magazine; it is quite another to provide access to the full
22,000 pages a year in the <I>Journal of Physical
Chemistry</i>, for example, or the 18,000 pages of
<I>Biochemistry</i>," says Lorrin Garson, chief
technology officer for ACS Publications. When you take into account the
twenty-nine magazines and journals, half a dozen newsletters, and who
knows how many other information booklets and releases that ACS
produces, you begin to get an idea of what such a project entails. As a
result, many ACS publications are not yet fully online, but they will
be soon. The same is true for dozens of other ACS offerings and
programs that appear in their own ChemCenter pages. The material is
descriptive and provides all the necessary information about contacts,
but it is not yet fully interactive. 
</P>


<P>Another problem has been the need to correct certain misconceptions in
the minds of the users. Many customers are members or librarians who
believe this is something that mimics print in terms of content,
usability, and pricing. However, the content, convenience, and
usability of online journals and other data exceed what is offered by
the print media. 
</P>


<P>"If you look, for example, at supporting information," says Garson,
"a lot of that material would be pretty hard to put in print." And,
he admits, "We're having a hard time trying to establish pricing and
access control for this stuff." Although electronic access to the
journals was free during the initial introduction period, as of January
1997, users must subscribe to them. Yet there is no doubt that the ACS
presence on the Web is being well received. When the Publications Web
site first went online in January 1995, the number of hits per month
was in the hundreds. Now, the number of hits is about a million a month
and growing. 
</P>


<P>To try to describe in any detail all of ChemCenter's features in a
short article like this would be futile. Besides, the only way to
really appreciate what ChemCenter can do for you is to spend some time
browsing through it. ChemCenter is still very much a work in progress
and will undoubtedly undergo many changes, improvements, and additions.
However, here is a sampling of the services and new features that are
attracting so many users.
</p>
<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">PUBLICATIONS</font></h3>
The <I>Journal of Physical Chemistry</i>, one
of science publishing's oldest journals, became ACS's first
interactive Internet journal on 1 June 1996. Articles are available for
searching and browsing, and the Web version has streamlined
capabilities to search for words in title, text, or abstract. You can
browse a cumulative table of contents, conduct author name searches, or
look up articles by manuscript or page number. 
</P>


<P><I>Biochemistry</i> and <I>Environmental
Science & Technology</i> have also debuted on the World Wide Web.
The user can access peer-reviewed research, and articles through 1996
are full-text searchable. In addition, a quarter-million pages of
supporting information have already been downloaded to the Web, and the
response to the site has been overwhelming. 
</P>


<P>The supporting information consists of scientific calculations, tables,
charts, and other supplementary sources that substantiate the
scientific research presented in ACS journals and allows readers to
review how authors of papers reach their conclusions. No other
publisher offers this service. 
</P>


<P>Three ACS journals available on CD-ROM are <I>The Journal
of Organic Chemistry</i>, the <I>Journal of the
American Chemical Society</i>, and
<I>Biochemistry</i>. Each CD-ROM contains every aspect
of the original journal page: chemical structures, equations, spectra,
schematic diagrams, tables, mathematical equations, and even
photographs and graphics. A powerful search engine makes finding what
you want a snap, and the high-resolution images (sharper and clearer
than on standard CDs) ensure crisp reproductions from your laser or
color printer. 
</P>


<P>If you can't wait to see what's in the upcoming issue of your
favorite ACS journals, you can view the tables of contents (TOCs) of
all ACS journals before you receive your copy in the mail. Journal
subscribers get the additional benefit of being able to search and
browse the full year's worth of TOCs of the journal to which they
subscribe. 
</P>


<P>The CAplus Table of Contents Service from CAS is an even more
ambitious system. The source material for the CAplus TOC is the more
than 1,350 key chemical journals from the CAplus database. Each time a
new journal issue is entered into the database, a TOC is created and
sent to you in the form requested: hard copy, fax, Internet mail, or
STNmail. CAplus is updated each business day, ensuring that you get the
most recent information as fast as possible. No other TOC service can
do it faster. 
</p>
<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">DIGGING DEEPER</font></h3>
There are so many other databases, information sources, and
search engines under the ChemCenter home page that I can just skim over
them. For example, the ACS Books Department is on the Net with a home
page that provides access to lists of recent titles and a Gopher
catalog of all the books available from ACS, searchable by author,
title, or subject. The site also provides guidelines and other services
for prospective authors. 
</P>


<P>CAS offers a link to its databases on STN using traditional STN Express
software for holders of regular STN accounts. In addition, it has a
special service for Internet users, called Chemical Patents Plus, which
allows anyone to search for and purchase copies of patents without
setting up an STN account. CAS plans more Internet-oriented access to
STN databases through ChemCenter in early 1997.
</p>
<p>
<img src="cc.gif" align=right hspace=6>
<h3><font color="00008B">ELECTRONIC SHOPPING</font></h3>
If you are looking for lab equipment, reagent chemicals,
or what-have-you, ChemCenter is on top of that, too. The Publications
Division has its Product Information Network (PIN) with online catalogs
of such things as audio/video products and science teaching resources. 
</P>


<P>A new offering is the online version of <I>Analytical
Chemistry's LabGuide</i>, which allows
you to browse through the alphabetical listings or search for a
specific product, service, or company. Web sites and e-mail addresses
provided by advertising companies can be reached simply by clicking on
the desired item. 
</P>


<P>If you are searching for chemicals, the place to look is in CHEMCATS.
Available from CAS on the STN International network, CHEMCATS includes
more than forty catalogs (with more to come) from chemical suppliers
worldwide. Simply enter the name of a chemical or chemical supplier, or
start with a chemical structure search to find the name or CAS Registry
Number. In minutes, or even seconds, CHEMCATS will find the product and
supplier information you need in a growing database of more than
200,000 catalog records and 138,000 CAS Registry Numbers. 
</P>


<P>As I write this article, work is ongoing to make
<I>Chemical & Engineering News's Chemcyclopedia</i>
available on ChemCenter as well. You will also be able to access this
respected source for the purchase of chemical products. 
</p>
<br clear="all">
<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">FINDING MORE</font></h3> 
A click on the Chemistry Resources icon brings up a large
selection of other point-and-click Web sites and directories that are
of interest to chemists. As I write this, there are links to sixty-two
sites under the general headings of Starting Materials, Other
Professional Societies & Scientific Organizations, and Science
Smorgasbord. That number is sure to grow rapidly, and the ChemCenter
group is actively seeking suggestions and URLs from users. 
</P>


<P>To go beyond purely chemical areas and enter the larger world of the
Internet, you can choose the Search icon. It is aptly named, because
some of the most powerful search engines on the Internet are
represented there. For starters, you can tap into the Library of
Congress; or, if you are looking for somebody's e-mail address
anywhere in the world, there are seven people-searching services,
including Bigfoot and Switchboard, that will find it for you. 
</P>


<P>To find company and business Web sites, there are ten "Yellow Page"
directories to choose from, including The Global Yellow Pages, World
Wide Yellow Pages, and the WWWeb Business Yellow Pages. 
</P>


<P>And finally, to really get out there and surf the Web, there is a long
list of the best-known and most powerful starting points available. You
can click onto WebCrawler, Magellan, Lycos, YAHOO Hotlist, and many
more - any one of which can get you started on a journey into
cyberspace.
</p>
<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">PROFESSIONAL SERVICES</font></h3>
ACS is a membership organization and, as such, provides unique
services to chemists. For example, ACS Career Services enhances the
professional and economic status of members by providing one-on-one
career assistance; direct contact with employers; and information on
employment data, trends, and issues. Programs are offered in Career
Assistance, Employment Services, Workshops and Presentations, Workforce
Analysis, Videos, and Publications. 
</P>


<P>Newly online is the ACS Job Bank, a joint effort of the Department of
Career Services and the Publications Division, which was the hottest
item on ACS Web sites in 1996. It allows ACS members to search for jobs
available to chemical professionals through classified and display ads
from <I>Chemical & Engineering News</i>. Updated
weekly, the ACS Job Bank provides links to other online job banks; the
Web home pages of major companies are also included.
</p>
<p>
<h3><font color="00008B">TRY IT, YOU'LL LIKE IT</font></h3>
If ever there was a case of a picture being worth a thousand
words, this is it. The only way to learn about ChemCenter is to go
there and see it for yourself. Bear in mind that it is a work in
progress. As you browse, you will find many requests for comments,
suggestions, and contributions. This is your ACS, and you are invited
to be a participant in the development and growth of ChemCenter.
</p>

<hr><br><br>

