<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TCAW 12/96 YOUR FEET ARE YOUR BOTTOM LINE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H1>Today's Chemist at Work</h1>
<h2>December 1996</h2>
Today's Chemist at Work, <b>1996</b>, 5<i>(11)</i>, 48-50.
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society.
<hr noshade></h5>
<P>
<center><h1><big><font color="00008B">YOUR FEET<br>
 ARE YOUR BOTTOM LINE</font>
</big></h1></center>

<img src="feet.gif" align=left hspace=6>
<h2><i><font color="green">Your feet are where the buck stops, and they deserve care and
attention before they put you out of business. A 1930s radio jingle for
shoe cream advised that "If you wore shoes upon your head, you'd
make sure they look neat." There's a lesson there for feet</font></i></h2>
<center><h3><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/tcaw/96/dec/authfeet.html">
Trevor Smith</a></h3></center>
</p>
<p>
It is hard to concentrate on work
if your feet hurt. Foot ailments vary from trivial to serious, so
let's look at avoidance, self-treatment, and when to seek help.
</p>
<p>
<h3><font color="maroon">PAMPER YOUR FEET</font></h3>
We live in a society that regards shoes as a fashion symbol;
looking good takes precedence over function. When you buy your next
pair of shoes, visit the store late in the day when your feet are
largest. "Our studies have shown that feet expand about one size
(one-third inch) in length and width after only about thirty minutes of
continuous activity," says Harry Hlavac, a podiatrist in Mill Hill,
CA. 
</P>


<P>Check shoes for quality of stitching and gluing. Put your hands in them
and feel for lumps and bumps. Try on both shoes of each pair you look
at, walk around, and climb stairs, if possible. Suitable shoes should
fit well and be comfortable in the store; don't buy them if they feel
marginally acceptable. You may believe they will be okay once you break
them in, but that may not happen. Shoes that you have been wearing for
a while should be kept in good repair. 
</P>


<P>If you have trouble finding a comfortable fit because of problems such
as bunions or hammertoes, find a store that has a pedorthist, a
specialist trained to match problem feet with appropriate shoes. In
extreme cases, you may be advised that the best solution is a
custom-made shoe. Although this option is more expensive than regular
shoes, it is less expensive and less traumatic than foot surgery. 
</P>


<P>Sock material is important. If you always have dry feet, you can wear
anything. If your feet are often damp or sweaty, wear polypropylene or
acrylic socks and avoid cotton. Cotton is hydrophilic and clings to
water like limpets on rock. It provides a permanently damp environment
for your feet that encourages fungal infections and blisters.
Polypropylene and acrylic are hydrophobic, wick sweat away from your
skin by capillarity, and carry it to the outside of the fabric surface
where it can evaporate. 
<h3><font color="maroon">SELF-TREAT SORE SPOTS</font></h3>
Corns and calluses are a thickening of the top layer of
skin. A callus tends only to spread outward, but a corn tends to grow
inward as well. Because they are in only the stratum corneum, which is
dead tissue, you can simply get rid of them. Soak your foot in warm
water to soften the tissue. Then pare away carefully with a sharp
blade, or smooth away with a pumice stone, callus file, or even
sandpaper. Corns and calluses are reactions to pressure and friction,
so look for the cause. If you find tight spots in your shoes, stretch
them or take them to a shoe repairer or a pedorthist to be stretched.
You can also try wearing thicker socks or loosening shoelaces, or apply
pads such as Moleskin, lamb's wool, or Second Skin to relieve
pressure. 
</P>


<P>Warts look similar to corns but are caused by viral infections and can
spread by contact. Warts tend to grow inward and can contain folds of
healthy tissue, so avoid cutting or abrading them. You can ignore small
warts that do not cause pain, and they will probably disappear within a
couple of years. A favorite site for a wart is the ball of your foot,
and the pressure can cause pain. You can treat a plantar wart with
salicylic acid preparations from the drugstore to kill infected tissue.
Apply the preparation for a couple of days, then scrub the area with a
small brush and soapy water for a minute, twice a day for two days.
Repeat the cycle for a couple of weeks and longer, or as long as it
continues to work. If the treatment does not seem to work, or the wart
grows rapidly and spreads, visit a podiatrist or a dermatologist. More
aggressive treatments include burning, freezing, or, as a last resort,
surgery. 
</P>


<P>Blisters are the end result of friction that causes an
inflammation in which the outer live skin layer, the epidermis,
separates and forms a fluid-filled sac. This usually contains watery
plasma-like fluid, but it sometimes fills with blood. You can puncture
a painful intact blister with a flame-sterilized needle. Pierce the
blister close to its border with healthy skin, squeeze out the fluid,
and cover with a sterile dressing. If the blister has already burst,
more friction can make it raw. Clean the area with your favorite
antiseptic. Avoid covering burst blisters with simple dressings,
because these do not absorb pressure. To protect the area from more
damage, cut doughnut-shaped pads of Moleskin or Molefoam, which will
transfer pressure to the surrounding area. Alternatively, use Second
Skin or Compeed. These excellent products have mechanical properties
similar to those of skin, and they cushion and protect your blister. 
</P>


<P>Always remember to use antiseptics on burst or punctured blisters to
guard against infection. Because blisters are caused by friction, you
need to check your shoes for tight spots. Check that your socks or hose
are not wrinkled; seams can be another trouble source. Damp skin has
higher friction than dry skin and is more likely to lead to blisters.
You can lower friction with a lubricant; the finest is petroleum jelly.
This sounds messy, but it works. 
</P>

<hr>
<h2><font color="00008B"><center>WE LIVE IN A SOCIETY THAT REGARDS SHOES AS A
FASHION SYMBOL; LOOKING GOOD TAKES PRECEDENCE OVER FUNCTION</center></font>
</h2>
<hr>


<P>Cut toenails straight across, not curved, so you do not leave little
spikes of nail against your skin that can grow inward. If you do
develop a painful ingrown nail, you need to have a small piece of nail
cut away from the edge. If you are very confident of your manual
skills, you can do this yourself, but you must use antiseptic
afterward. Unless you know what you are doing, let a podiatrist handle
ingrown nails. In some cases, after repeated unsuccessful treatments,
chronic ingrown nails may have to be removed surgically. 
</P>


<P>If you stub your toe, you can develop a black toenail. This often
happens to runners and devotees of jumping sports who have poorly
fitting shoes and jam their toes. The black appearance is caused by
bleeding under the nail. Open a paper clip and hold it in a pair of
pliers while you heat it to red heat in a flame. Touch the top of your
black nail with the hot paper clip. The nail will melt painlessly and
release the blood, which should save your nail. If the appearance does
not bother you and your black nail is painless, you may ignore it. A
new nail will grow and eventually push out the damaged one. 
</P>


<P>Among the many fungal infections that plague feet, the most common is
athlete's foot. You do not have to be an athlete to pick up athlete's
foot; all it takes is exposure to the fungus. This wretched organism
thrives in warm, moist areas, usually beginning between your toes. At
first, you experience redness and itching. If you do not take care of
it quickly, your symptoms will grow worse. You will develop scaling and
cracks and, as the infection increases, you may end up with blistery
sores. 
</P>


<P>At the first sign of athlete's foot, use an over-the-counter topical
antifungal ointment. You must be persistent with treatment because the
fungus is in your skin, not on the surface. Apply sufficient medication
to cover all the skin so the ingredient can penetrate, and continue
treatment until you have no symptoms at all. Be careful to avoid
reinfection; the fungus spreads enthusiastically in damp environments.
You can dry your feet more thoroughly after showers and baths by using
ethyl rubbing alcohol as a jet from a squeeze bottle. If self-treatment
doesn't work and your symptoms persist or worsen, a podiatrist or
dermatologist may recommend prescription medication.
</p>

<p>
<h3><font color="maroon">SEEK PROFESSIONAL CARE</font></h3>
You will not receive good help from most primary care
physicians for foot pain caused by anatomical or biomechanical defects.
Your best choices are a podiatrist or an orthopedist. 
</P>


<P>The five podiatric medical schools in the US provide training that
leads to the degree Doctor of Podiatric Medicine. Such doctors are
specialists at least equivalent to those who choose regular medical
schools and obtain an M.D., then go on to become orthopedic surgeons
who specialize in feet. Podiatrists tend to have better knowledge of
biomechanics and more experience in the advanced surgical procedures
required to correct foot problems than do orthopedic surgeons. However,
some orthopedic surgeons become foot specialists, and you can identify
these by their membership in the American Orthopedic Foot and Ankle
Society. There are far more podiatrists than orthopedic foot
specialists. 
</P>


<P>Here are the principal problems that need expert help. 
</P>


<P>Between foot strike and toe off, during walking or running, your ankle
rolls in slightly in a motion called pro<hp>nation. Low-arch feet
pronate excessively, and high-arch feet underpronate (or even rotate
outward, a tendency called supination). Repeated abnormal foot
rotations can cause pain in your feet and sometimes in your legs. The
more physical activities you enjoy, the more likely you are to develop
overuse symptoms. Abnormal rotations can be corrected by orthotic
inserts in your shoes. 
</P>


<P>Your big toe and second toe should be about the same length. Then the
load-bearing centers of your foot are behind your big toe, your fifth
toe, and the middle of your heel. Some people have an abnormally short
bone in their big toe, which makes their second toe look much longer
than their big toe. This is called Morton's Syndrome, or Morton's
Foot. A short big toe displaces load bearing from behind the big toe
toward the smaller toes. In very active people, this can cause pain in
feet and legs. This also can be countered by orthotic inserts in your
shoes. 
</P>


<P>In a bunion, the bone at the base of your big toe grows bigger and
moves away from the other bones. While this bone moves outward, the
bone at the end of the big toe moves toward the smaller toes. Your big
toe is then bent and often pushes the second toe up or down, out of its
way. The increased pressure causes blisters, calluses, and painful
inflammation. You can counter these symptoms by wearing shoes with
wider toe boxes and by not using the lowest eyelets for laces. Cutting
a hole in the top of the shoe makes more room for a swollen joint. You
can also have orthotic inserts made to rearrange the forces on your
foot, or you can have shoes custom made. As a last resort, you can have
the whole area surgically reduced, fractured, and reset to correct the
misalignment. 
</P>


<P>Hammertoes are bent where they join the rest of your foot. This
makes the middle joint of the toes rise, so it rubs on your shoes,
causing pain, calluses, or corns. Again, you need roomier shoes and
perhaps pads to absorb the pressure. If hammertoes become a problem you
no longer wish to endure, they can be surgically fractured, grooved,
and reset in correct alignment. It is often said that bunions and
hammertoes tend to be inherited. But these defects are not known in
barefoot populations, and 90 percent of the cases occur in women, who
often wear pointy, flimsy shoes. It seems more likely that the only
thing that is inherited is a tendency to wear inadequate shoes, and
over many years bad shoes realign the bones in your feet. 
</P>

<center><img src="foot.gif"></center>

<P>In addition to choosing well-fitting, comfortable shoes, you can also
exercise your feet for strength and flexibility. Here's a routine
recommended by Paul Taylor, a podiatrist in Silver Spring, MD:
<ul>
<li>Sit down and spread a towel in front of you. Grip an edge of
the towel by curling your toes around it and lift it a few inches off
the floor. Hold five seconds, then let go. Switch to the other foot,
and continue to alternate feet until they begin to feel tired. 
<li>Sit down and flex your foot up and down vertically to stretch
your ankle. Next, keep your heel still and turn your foot from side to
side to stretch your ankle. Repeat each move thirty to forty times for
each foot.
<li>Stand with your feet twelve to eighteen inches apart. Turn
your ankles until you are standing on the outside edges of your feet.
Slowly turn your ankles until you are standing on the inside edges of
your feet. Bend your knees a little if this feels better. Repeat twenty
to thirty times.
<li>Take a band of stretchable material. Loop the band over your
toes to join your feet. Sit down and raise your legs straight out in
front, ankles about five inches apart. Keep your heels still and turn
your feet outward against the resistance of the band, then turn your
feet inward. Repeat twenty to thirty times.
<li>Walk around on your toes for up to five minutes. Now walk on
your heels for up to five minutes. 
</ul>
</p>
<p>
If your feet are in good shape, you should be able to
perform these exercises without discomfort. Build slowly until you can
complete three sets of each two or three times a week. You can also
massage tired feet with your thumbs, and whirlpool treatments feel
good, too.
</p>

<hr><br><br>

