<HEAD>
<TITLE>NORTH AMERICA - MEXICO</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>December 16, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<h1><big><center><font color="red">NORTH AMERICA</font></big><br>
Mexico's Economic Recovery<br>
Spurs Chemical Trade</center></h1>
<h3><font color="00008B">George Peaff</font><br>
<i>C&EN Northeast News Bureau</i></h3>
<hr noshade>
<p>
<P>Strong domestic economic recovery 
and continuing expansion of trade
with its northern and southern
neighbors has brought an apparent end
to Mexico's recession.</P>
<P>But Mexico is still coping with the
fallout of political commotion even as it
strives to strengthen its role in the international community. Various incidents
during 1996 epitomized the nation's
growing pains.</P>
<P>One example is the collapse and restart of the
Mexican government's attempt to put its petrochemical industry
into the hands of private investors. After several months of studying legal
aspects, the government called off its
initial plan - which called for eventual
100% private ownership - because of
the political and public outcry against
it. In October, the government outlined
a new plan that will allow domestic and
foreign private investors to take up to a
49% ownership in the 61 petrochemical
plants operated by Petr&oacute;leos Mexicanos (Pemex).</P>
<P>However, some of the other economic actions taken
by the Mexican government have encouraged the nation's expansion. Those actions
include the December 1995 devaluation of the peso
and the promotion of political and free-market economic reforms.</P>
<P>In 1995, according to statistics reported by
Banco Nacional de M&eacute;xico (Banamex), Mexico's gross domestic product
(GDP) declined 6.2% from 1994 and the
annual inflation rate in 1995 was 52%.
That compared with a GDP growth of
4.5% in 1994 and an annual inflation rate of 7%.</P>
<P>For the first half of 1996, GDP grew
3%, compared with a 5.5% decline in the
same period in 1995. In August, the inflation rate stood at 30.6%, compared
with 41.6% in August 1995.</P>
<P>Overall export growth, a desired result
of the peso devaluation, continued into
1996. Through August of this year, Mexico's overall exports totaled $61.3
billion, up 19% from the same period in 1995. In
all of 1995, Mexico's exports topped
$79.5 billion, up 31% from 1994.</P>
<p>But Mexico's economic turnaround is
best portrayed by the return of import
growth in 1996. Through August, Mexico's overall imports were $56.5 billion,
a 20% rise from the same period in 1995.
For full-year 1995, imports declined 8.7%
from 1994 to $72.5 billion.</P>
<P>Banamex estimates that exports will
total $94.5 billion in 1996 and $108 billion in 1997. Imports, it says, will
reach $87.7 billion this year and $103 billion in 1997.</p>
<P>Banamex pegs Mexico's return to economic growth
to the recovery of the
country's manufacturing sector. "The rate
of growth of the manufacturing industry is
expected to surpass that of GDP, owing
both to the continuing impulse given by
exports and the consolidation of certain
domestically oriented sectors, particularly
those producing basic goods," according
to the statistics report.</P>
<center><img src="mextrade.gif"></center>
<P>Consolidation refers to industries or
companies that sustain strong export
levels and that increase total and domestically oriented output. This requires
capacity expansion and the penetration of new markets through product
diversification.</p>
<P>Mexico's chemical industry is participating in
the economy's recovery. According to statistics reported by the
Asociaci&oacute;n Nacional de la Industria Qu&acute;&inodot;mica (ANIQ),
Mexico's chemical industry association, in
1995 the industry's total exports grew
50% from 1994 to $3.71 billion. Chemical
imports declined 1.4% to $4.72 billion.
For the first six months of 1996, chemical exports reached $1.79 billion and
imports were $2.69 billion. ANIQ's statistics do not include pharmaceuticals.
</p>
<P>The U.S. remains Mexico's largest
chemical trade partner. More than 65% of
Mexico's chemical imports come from the
U.S., and more than 50% of its chemical
exports go to the U.S. The next largest
trading bloc for Mexico's chemical imports - at more than 16% - is the
European Union. And in terms of chemical exports, its next largest export
partner - at more than 18% - is South America.</P>
<img src="mexchem1.gif" align=left hspace=6>
<P>Reflecting the state of Mexico's economy in 1995,
U.S. exports of chemicals to
Mexico - including pharmaceutical products - declined almost 2% from
1994 to $4.27 billion. U.S. imports of chemicals
from Mexico, however, rose a whopping
27% to nearly $1.3 billion. U.S. exports
of chemicals to Mexico could reach
$5.15 billion in 1996, rebounding about
20% from the 1995 level. And Mexico's
exports of chemicals to the U.S. could
rise about 16% to reach $1.5 billion.</P>
<P>Based on data through July, U.S. exports to Mexico
are being led by inorganic chemicals, dyeing and coloring materials, medicinal
and pharmaceutical products, fertilizers, plastics, and other
miscellaneous chemical products, all
growing at double-digit rates over the
same period in 1995. Leading Mexico's
exports to the U.S. are inorganic chemicals, dyeing and coloring materials,
medicinal and pharmaceutical products,
essential oils, plastics, and other miscellaneous chemical products - again
growing at double-digit rates over the same period in 1995.</P>
<P>But the turmoil surrounding the attempts to privatize
Mexico's petrochemical industry has no doubt hurt the trade
of one product segment, organic chemicals. Through July, U.S. organic chemical
exports to Mexico were only 3.6% greater than in the 1995 period, and Mexico's
exports of organics to the U.S. grew less
than 0.5%.</P>
<P>Prospects for the chemical industry
look brighter as the Mexican economy
grows stronger, however. And the implementation of the North American Free
Trade Agreement has played a part in
both the recovery of the Mexican economy and growth of the Mexican chemical
industry.</P>
<P>"NAFTA will make Mexico and the
U.S. very, very strong trading partners as
we continue to build into the near future," says Thomas A. Smith, president of
Eastman Chemical's Latin American operations, based in Mexico City. The
continuing growth in trade promoted by
NAFTA, he explains, has softened the
peso devaluation's effect on imports and
Mexico's domestic market.</P>
<P>"When the peso was devalued, the
companies that did manufacture in Mexico had much more of a capability to export
[on a] lower cost-of-goods basis. The
domestic market contracted to the point
that people were forced to look to the export markets. And those that could
export - those with goods of [superior] quality - did pretty well."</p>
<P>Chemical trade between Mexico and
its other NAFTA partner, Canada, remains
small compared with trade between Mexico and the U.S., but it has grown
substantially on a percentage basis since the trade pact's passage.</P>
<P>Using statistics from ANIQ, Mexico's
chemical exports to Canada totaled
$32.3 million in 1995, up 151% from
1994, again a reflection of the drop in value of the peso. Canada's chemical
exports to Mexico totaled $57.3 million in 1995, up just 2% from 1994.</P>
<P>But in the first six months of 1996
alone, Canada's chemical exports to Mexico were $42.3 million, no doubt helped
by the recovery of Mexico's domestic economic situation. Mexico's chemical
exports to Canada were $15.4 million in the first six months of 1996.</P>
<P>Chemical industry consultant Kline &amp;
Co. of Fairfield, N.J., in a report on Mexico's chemical industry, says it "will
sustain outstanding growth during the next
10 years," now that the Mexican economy is back on track. Kline sees a
"continuing pattern that began with the decade of the 1980s, [when]
the nation's
chemical industry recorded an annual average growth rate in excess of 9%, while
its national GDP grew at only 1% during
the same period.</p>
<hr noshade><br>
<center><h1>Return to <br><br><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/cenear/96121
6/index.html"><img src="worldsm.gif"></center></h3></a>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B25-8</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA042-000778-B039-101</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://pubs.acs.org:80/hotartcl/cenear/961216/asi.html 134.243.215.53 19970303170508 text/html 15840
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Enterprise/2.01
Date: Mon, 03 Mar 1997 17:10:01 GMT
Accept-ranges: bytes
Last-modified: Wed, 18 Dec 1996 21:16:34 GMT
Content-length: 15634
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML SYSTEM "html.dtd">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ASIA-PACIFIC </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>December 16, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<h1><big><center><font color="green">ASIA-PACIFIC</font></big><br>  
Slowing Economies Mean Less<br>
Growth For Chemicals</center></h1>
<h3><font color="551A8B">Jean-Fran&#231;ois Tremblay</font><br>
<i>C&EN Hong Kong</i></h3>
<hr noshade>
<P>Petrochemical producers from Japan, North America,
and other areas have traditionally been able to
count on the countries of East and South
Asia to absorb their surplus production in
times of slack demand at home. Very
soon, however, as numerous new facilities
come on-line in this region, creating a supply near at hand, it will become
increasingly difficult to sell to Asia.</P>
<P>Demand still outpaces chemical production capacities
in the region - a situation that will continue to exist for many
products. However, demand from overseas suppliers for major petrochemicals
will tend to stabilize or diminish considerably, said petrochemical consulting
firm Chem Systems at its annual Asian
conference in Singapore in November.
An extreme example of this trend is the
key polyester intermediate purified terephthalic acid (PTA), for which East
Asia, particularly South Korea, could become an
exporter as early as 2000. Moreover, the
most important country that will carry
over a deficit in petrochemical production
is China, a notoriously unpredictable buyer. As a result, chemical exporters
from the U.S. and other countries will gradually
turn their attention to other parts of the world.</p>
<P>With the exception of Japan, in 1996
the economies of Asia have grown more
slowly than in previous years. China,
which seems to have been reasonably
successful in slowing down its overheating economy, has seen its gross domestic
product (GDP) grow about 8% this year,
down from nearly 10% last year.</P>
<P>Meanwhile, Singapore repeatedly has
been revising downward its growth forecasts to a current 7% for 1996, which
will be off from last year's 8.3% economic growth. Recent unofficial estimates
put Thailand's GDP growth at 7% in
1996, down from 8.6% last year; the
country's newly elected government has
pledged to make the economy its top
priority.</P>
<P>South Korea is getting worried because its economic
growth has slowed to
7.6%, which falls short of the 10% that it
had grown accustomed to in years prior
to 1995. In Taiwan, the growth in manufacturing appears to have leveled off
in the past two years, and GDP growth this
year will be a disappointing 5.7%. Many
in Asia are questioning the sustainability
of the fast growth rates of the past, and
there is talk of structural problems in
many of the economies.</P>
<P>But Asia is nonetheless expected to
remain the world's fastest growing region. Chem Systems, for instance, estimates
GDP growth to remain strong at
7.9% yearly in East Asia (minus Japan)
over the period 1995 to 2000, compared
with 2.4% for the U.S., 2.0% for Western
Europe, and 3.2% for Latin America. Consequently, most growth in supply and
demand of petrochemicals will originate
from Asia, excluding Japan. GDP growth
and the demand for petrochemicals are
closely related.</P>
<center><img src="asiaeast.gif"></center>
<P>Operating under a different set of dynamics than
its neighbors, Japan has
emerged from a long recession, with its
economy growing 3 to 4% this year. Several factors, including a weaker yen,
are breathing life into the country's industries. The manufacturing index is up, continuing a trend started last year. And car
production is taking a break from the
downward trend of the past few years:
Based on partial figures through October, about 7.7 million units will likely
be produced in Japan this year, slightly
more than last year. Consumer confidence is perking up, with housing starts
much higher than in 1995.</P>
<P>In contrast, Japan's chemical industry continues
to essentially stagnate. For
the first half of the year, the country's
12 leading chemical firms disclosed financial results that were little changed
from the previous year's first half, although results varied considerably among
producers.</P> <P>Mitsubishi Chemical has blamed rising
naphtha prices - essentially the result of
the weakening yen - for a disappointing
first half. Sumitomo Chemical, which sells
a lot of construction material, reported
that its profit in the first half was up sharply, although its return on sales
remains below 2%. Drug company Takeda Chemical, however, continued to improve
its performance, and its return on sales in
the first half approached 8%, which is
more than double any other firm among
the top 12. For the past few years, Japan's drug firms have indeed been doing
very well. But their performance is expected to decline as the government
reduces its health insurance coverage of
drug purchases by patients.</P>
<P>On the whole, Japan's results are
weaker than one would hope, given that
the industry has been on a restructuring
path for several years. It is particularly
worrisome that Mitsubishi Chemical has
downgraded its profit forecast for the
whole fiscal year by 87%. Mitsubishi
Chemical is one of the leading companies in cost-cutting and restructuring endea
vors.
More than half of its earnings
last year were from strong petrochemical
sales, something that won't occur again
for several years, given the environment
in Asia in 1997 and beyond.</P>
<P>The Asian market for petrochemicals
performed a few stunts in 1996. Polyolefin prices surged when China, which
buys 25 to 30% of polyolefins traded globally, renewed its buying, which it had
restricted in 1995. But prices soon came
back down, where they appear to be
comfortably settling. Meanwhile, says
Chem Systems consultant Danley B.
Wolfe, the start-up of additional <I>p</I>-xylene
production capacity, coupled with an
easing in demand growth for polyester,
has caused prices of the fiber intermediate to nosedive from $2,000 per ton a
year ago to about $400 now.</P>
<P>Indeed, 1996 is the first year of a cycle in
which the Asian market for petrochemicals is settling into a lengthy slack.
Prices of polyolefins will remain "lousy
until the end of the century," Chem Systems consultant Sam N. Angove predicts.
Slower economic growth in Asia, coupled with the rapid addition of new capacity
next year and until 2000, means
that the profit picture is unpromising. In
coming years, unscheduled plant outages
have become the best hope for those
who long for higher prices.</P>
<P>Major additions to polyolefins capacity in coming
years will be made in the
Philippines, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia, South Korea, Thailand, Taiwan,
and China. For polyethylene, overall, the
planned expansions worldwide between
1996 and 1999 represent 24% of global
capacity in 1995. About one-third of this
will be built in Asia (excluding China).
For polypropylene, the planned expansions represent 37% of 1995 existing
capacity, with more than one-third of it being built in Asia, Angove says.</P>
<center><img src="japcar.gif"></center>
<P>The profit outlook in the polyester
chain appears less promising than it isfor polyolefins, also because of capacity
expansions. By 1998, Wolfe believes, operating rates for PTA production
facilities will reach a low of 68%. It's a similar situation with
<I>p</I>-xylene, a product whose
market is closely related to demand for
PTA. By 2000, global capacity will reach
about 22 million metric tons, about double 1995 capacity.</P>
<P>With their large excess capacity and
their aggressive approach to exports,
South Koreans have become the price
setters in Asian petrochemicals. The
country will export about half of its annual polypropylene production of 2.2
million metric tons between 1997 and 1999.
It's the same situation for polyethylene,
for which Korea will export about 40%
of its annual output of 3 million metric
tons. Moreover, an enduring surplus of
ethylene over the absorption capability
of the country's derivative plants means
that South Korea will continue to export
unprocessed ethylene in coming years,
although shipments are likely to decrease, Chem Systems Vice President
Steve N. Rothman says.</P>
<P>Among the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, demand for imports will
essentially evaporate in the next three
years as a result of their increased domestic supply. Thus, the effect that
South 
Korea's ability to export will have on international prices will be determined
mostly by China's appetite for imports.
This combination of strong regional supply conditions and unreliable Chinese
demand means that those producing from
other continents will be increasingly
wary of Asia, Angove says. He believes
U.S. producers will look more and more
to Latin America for trade and investment opportunities.</P>
<center><img src="asiasales.gif"></center><br><br>
<img src="asialit.gif" align=left hspace=6><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<P>Other than capacity expansions, supply in Asia
will soon be affected by new
and still-experimental technologies for
producing polyolefins that are on the
verge of widespread implementation. For
instance, Mitsui Petrochemical Industries
and Sumitomo Chemical recently announced their intention to start up inspring 1998 a linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE) plant based on metallocene
catalyst technology developed
by Mitsui. In addition to metallocene
catalysts, new second-generation technologies include the use of octene in
gas-phase reactors for the production of
bimodal and broad molecular weight
distribution LLDPE and in situ generation of comonomers.
Between now and
2000, Angove believes, most growth in
capacity for low-density polyethylene
will be based on one or the other of the
second-generation technologies becoming available.</P>
<P>In all this, Japan finds itself in a precarious
situation. For the past few years, its
chemical industry had been able to make
up for weak domestic demand by exporting to nearby Asian countries, where demand
was strong. However, having the
highest costs not only in Asia but also in
the world means Japanese chemical firms
are finding it more and more difficult to
compete against the expanding chemical
industries of Asia, especially for commodity chemicals.</P>
<P>Over time, Chem Systems consultants expect Japan's
petrochemical industry to stagnate. Older facilities will
be shut down and few new ones will
take their place. For example, Japan's
benzene production will shrink at an
annual rate of 1.9% until 2000, says
Wolfe, in sharp contrast with annual
growth of 15.4% in the rest of Asia. As
for styrene, he expects Japan's capacity
to decrease by 400,000 metric tons by 2000.</p>
<P>Overall, expansions in new polyolefin
capacity in Japan will increase by 1.5 million metric tons over the next 10
years, compared with 20 million metric tons in
the rest of Asia. Japan's chemical firms
will continue to invest, but the proportion of overseas investment will increase
sharply. Dogged by high costs and a
shrinking domestic market, overseas investment is becoming increasingly critical
for the Japanese firms.</P>
<center><img src="asiasouth.gif"></center> 
<P>Although the profitability of petrochemicals
in Asia appears bleak for the
next few years, the outlook continues to
be promising for specialty and performance chemicals. "In this region,
demand is explosive," says Damon C. Warmack,
Eastman Chemical's general manager for
Hong Kong and China. "I know it may not
make much sense, but for some products,
GDP growth of 10% might translate into
demand growth of 30%."<br clear="all"></P><br>
<P>"There are examples of consumer
goods manufacturers from foreign countries that build plants in this region
only
to find out, once the facilities come on-line, that they need to import even
more into the region of the very products that the new facilities produce,"
Warmack says. "We are in a market
where new demand is being created
versus substituted from a very low position on the economic ladder. Small gains
in average disposable income can drive
market growth much faster than general average economic data would suggest based
on analysis in a developed
economy."</p>
<center><img src="korea.gif"></center>
<P>Other than growing demand resulting
many plants operating in Asia do not produce the higher quality that local
consumers are increasingly demanding.
Compared with some of the commodity
items that Eastman produces, Warmack
prefers performance chemicals that he
can sell at a higher price, with sales that
grow at a steadier rate, and for which the
competition is not so fierce.</P>
<P>Cycles are inherent to the chemical
industry, and Warmack does not completely trust predictions. Generally, he
finds that people become overly pessimistic in the low phase of the cycle, and
overly optimistic during the peaks. "It's
as if someone were lying in the sun in a
puddle of water. Looking at the sun, the
person feels great, suntanning and all, it's
paradise. But turning around on his stomach, suddenly, it's panic. He forgets
he is
just face down in a puddle and thinks he's drowning."</P>
<center><img src="asiatai.gif"></center>
<P>It's a point of view some consultants
find affinity with. Even after painting a depressing view of the overcapacity
picture in the polyester chain, Chem Systems'
Wolfe still sounds upbeat. "Low prices
will pass through and stimulate polyester
fiber and [polyethylene terephthalate] resin consumption," he
says. Demand forecasts for polyester consumption in Asia are
already robust, and drops in prices might
yield to even stronger consumption than expected.</P>
<P>Indeed, what should one make of predictions concerning
the chemical industry in Asia? And what do consultants
think of the predictions they themselves
make? On this score, Chem Systems is
refreshingly candid. Noting that many
events can occur after a prediction is
made, the company president, Marshall
E. Frank, jokingly announces: "In the 31
years we've been in this business, our
forecasts have ranged between 100% accurate to 100% inaccurate."</P>
<P>Bangkok-based Wolfe, who specializes in the polyester
chain, further relates:"
There is an amazing diversity in Asia. A
few months ago, I was on a flight from
Bangkok to Singapore. On my right side
was one of the [video jockeys] from the
TV music channel MTV (Asia). She was
all done up, excited, cosmopolitan, you
get the picture. On my left was a missionary from Belgium writing a thesis on
the peasant cultures of Hubei, basically
China's least developed province. He had
lived one year among them." Given the
diversity of lifestyles that these two individuals represented, Wolfe wonders
at times how reliable his Asian market predictions possibly can be.</P>
<P>Which is certainly not to say that the
forecasters are consistently wrong. Indeed, many people are willing to pay top
dollar to learn what some of them have to
say. What they have to offer is more
or less the best guess one can obtain
based on the information currently
available. Their bottom line? Polyolefins have entered a period of
oversupply, and demand won't
catch up for about five years. In the
case of <I>p</I>-xylene, PTA, and polyester, the oversupply is more serious
and the next surge won't occur before 2003. And for fine chemicals, a
sector that is not studied by Chem
Systems, the Asian outlook remains
excellent.
</p>
<hr noshade><br>
<center><h1>Return to <br><br><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/cenear/96121
6/index.html"><img src="worldsm.gif"></center></h3></a>

</BODY>
</HTML>









