<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NORTH AMERICA - CANADA</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>December 16, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<h1><big><center><font color="red">NORTH AMERICA</font></big><br>
Canada's Chemical Production<br>
Set To Build From 1996 Plateaus</center></h1>
<h3><font color="00008B">Elisabeth M. Kirschner</font><br>
<i>C&EN Northeast News Bureau</i></h3>
<hr noshade>
<P>After the heady gains of 1995, Canada's chemical
industry held its
ground in 1996. Production, prices, and shipments hovered near the lofty
levels of 1995 for much of the year but
are expected to strengthen in 1997.</P>
<P>"Shipments are maintaining the record
performance of 1995" for chemicals and
chemical products, says David J. Shearing,
project manager for business development
at the Canadian Chemical Producers' Association (CCPA). Shipments dipped from
the 1995 peak of $21.3 billion to an expected $20.8 billion for 1996. Organic
chemical shipments slipped to $4.1 billion
from $4.5 billion in 1995, and shipments
of inorganic chemicals edged down to
$2.1 billion from $2.3 billion.</P>
<P>"Prospects for next year are for increased
production volumes," Shearing
explains. "Sales could be up or down,
depending on prices. Capital expenditures are up in 1996 and are expected to
rise further in 1997."</P>
<P>Canada's chemicals business tends to
move in concert with the U.S. industry.
Despite a sluggishness in the
economy, U.S. demand is expected to
keep the chemicals sector humming."
There seems to be optimism about 1997.
Because of exports to the U.S., things are
looking positive," Shearing says. "We're
pretty near the peak of the cycle, and
we're optimistic that this could be holding pat."</P>
<P>"We expect continued modest growth,"
says a spokesman for Calgary, Alberta-based
Nova Chemicals, a subsidiary of Nova Corp."
We see continued strong numbers particularly for polyethylene and methanol.
But the current weakness in the styrene
and polystyrene marketplace is not expected to change significantly."</P>
<P>Prices plateaued in late 1995 through
much of 1996. After the highs of early
1995, prices lingered around 130% of
1986 values for chemicals and chemical
products and for overall manufacturing.
Although the subcategory of inorganic
chemicals held at that price level, organic
chemicals - at an estimated price index of
146 - fell from the 1995 level of 158.</P>
<P>Although prices have fluctuated, total
volumes have edged up. And "indications are that some prices firmed up
in the third quarter," says Shearing. "Operating profits were essentially
at a peak in 1995 and down in 1996. Whether those
numbers are confirmed when we get the
final results remains to be seen. As of
September, we were expecting a drop of 2% in sales."</P>
<P>For the Canadian chemical industry,"
exports have risen as a percentage of
our output to be a much more important
part" of the economy, says Shearing. Exports accounted for 44% of shipments
in 1996 compared with 36% of shipments
two years earlier. Exports were up 3% in
1996 over 1995, with imports up 7%.</P>
<P>These results "continue the trend in
specialization on both sides of the border," explains David Podruzny,
CCPA's senior project manager for business development. "We have more exports
and more imports on both sides of the border. That reflects specialized
production, with product shipped from one site,
rather than having a range of products at
many sites."</p>
<center><img src="caimport.gif"></center>
<P>Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan (PCS),
based in Saskatoon, which has been on an
expansion rampage, posted third-quarter
1996 net income of $46.8 million, up
103% from 1995. Third-quarter sales totaled $342.1 million, up 59% from 1995.
The growth benefited from the White
Springs Agricultural Chemicals phosphate
operation in Florida, purchased from Occidental Chemical in the fourth quarter
of 1995. PCS is awaiting the completion of
two more acquisitions, U.S. nitrogen fertilizer producer Arcadian Corp. and
a majority share of German potash holding company Kali &amp; Salz.</P>
<P>PCS's potash sales volume for the first
nine months of 1996 declined 6%, with
prices flat. Potash exports were down
21%, but those prices rose 8% year-to-year for January through September. PCS
anticipates increased prices in the non-North American diammonium phosphate
market, firm pricing in liquid phosphates,
and improved potash shipments.</P>
<P>Nova Chemicals had net income plummet in the
fourth quarter of 1995. Although business has improved every quarter since then,
net income for the first
nine months of 1996 totaled only $107 million compared with $310 million for
the same period in 1995. However, Nova started the fourth quarter with
a new acquisition - the plastics business of Arco Chemical, purchased for $163 million.</P>
<P>Nova blames lower styrene prices and
higher crude-oil feedstock costs for the declines in income. "This was
partially offset
in 1996 by higher sales volumes," according to the company. But styrene
nd polystyrene prices are expected to remain flat
because of capacity coming on-line in early 1997 and soft demand in Asia.</P>
<P>Polyethylene prices strengthened and
volumes rose in the third quarter from
the second quarter. Nova says polyethylene prices "appear to have reached a
plateau. Prices may decline moderately,
but strong market demand should provide stability into 1997."</P>
<center><img src="cachem.gif"></center>
<P>In August, CCPA updated its 1994
study of the competitiveness of Canada's
business climate for the chemical industry. The report is used in government
advocacy, says Shearing, to show the industry's competitiveness in North America
and urge legislators and regulators to foster growth.</P>
<center><img src="caoutput.gif"></center>
<P>The provinces of Ontario, Quebec,
and Alberta - home to much of the Canadian chemical industry - are particularly
competitive with U.S. production. "We
are competitive overall in our corporate
income taxes, payroll, and property taxes. Looking at salaries and payroll
taxes, we have an advantage over the U.S.," explains Shearing. "Benefits
cost less in Canada."</p>
<P>Historically, he says, "we have had
uncompetitive construction costs versus
the Gulf Coast." Now, he adds, the cost
of "building a plant in Alberta is just a
few percent higher than on the U.S. Gulf
Coast. If you were to build that [plant] in
Ontario or Sarnia, it might be 8% higher
than on the U.S. Gulf Coast. The higher
cost is primarily due to higher [labor]
costs. We're working with the government to get the construction costs on a
level playing field."</P>
<P>The Organization for Economic Cooperation &amp;
Development (OECD) found that
Canada's recent "growth pause" comes
from the concomitant effects of moderate
demand from the U.S. in a slowed economy, weakened domestic demand, and fiscal
consolidation. "At the same time, however, the recent period has seen
a considerable improvement in Canada's economic
fundamentals," a recent OECD report says."
Over the next 18 months, real gross domestic product should again grow by more
than [production] capacity, which is estimated to be expanding at
an annual rate of around 2.5%."</p>
<P>Shearing says CCPA's efforts now are in"
trying to ensure we maintain our competitive advantages, such as feedstocks
and transportation, and work on any areas
where there is a disadvantage."
</p>
<hr noshade><br>
<center><h1>Return to <br><br><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/cenear/96121
6/index.html"><img src="worldsm.gif"></center></h3></a>

