<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TCAW 2/97 PRIZES! FAME! PRESTIGE!</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H1>Today's Chemist at Work</h1>
<h2>February 1997</h2>
Today's Chemist at Work, <b>1997</b>, 6<i>(2)</i>, 112, 109.
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1997 by the American Chemical Society.
<hr noshade></h5>
<p>
<center><img src="anim1.gif"><br>
<img src="anim2.gif"><img src="anim3.gif"></center>
</p>
<p>
<center><h1><i><font color="green">What are the seven wonders of the chemical 
world?
</font></i></h1>
</p>
<p>
<h2><font color="551A8B">WE'D LIKE TO HEAR FROM YOU!</font></h2>
</p>
<p>
<h3>Send your ideas by <font color="red">24 March 1997</font> to:
</p>
<p>
<font color="blue">Seven Wonders<br>
Today's Chemist at Work<br>
American Chemical Society<br>
1155 Sixteenth St., N.W.<br>
Washington, DC 20036</font></h3></center>
</p>
<hr noshade>
<p>
Many years ago, when in grade school,
I read about the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World in my history book
(<I>Modern Times and the Living Past</i>, by Henry W.
Elson). They still fascinate me. To refresh your memory, according to
<I>The New Grolier Multimedia Encyclopedia</i>:
</p>
<p> 
<blockquote>
The Seven Wonders of the World comprise the greatest feats of ancient
technology, architecture, and art as seen by Greek and Roman authors. The list
has changed onlyh slightly since it first appeared (c. 130 BC) in a poem by
Antipater of Sidon in the Greek Anthology. He praises the Pyramids of Egypt,
the Walls and the Hanging Gardens of Babylon, the Temple of Artemis at  
Ephesus, the Statue of Zeus at Olympia, the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus, and the
Colossus of Rhodes.
</blockquote>
</p>
<p> 
This list was later amended; the Walls and Hanging Gardens
were consolidated into one Wonder, and the Pharos (lighthouse) of
Alexandria was added as the seventh. And so it has been handed down to
us over more than twenty-one centuries. Thus, list-making is not a new
habit and indeed has been contagious through the ages. In fact, it's
fun and, I submit, educational, as well as inspirational. 
</p>
<p>
<P>But why "seven?" Possibly because seven is a neat way to separate
the wheat from the chaff. Or maybe it was intended to be one wonder for
each day of the week. Anyway, the urge to list seven wonders of
<I>something</i> has continued over the years. And so
we now have the<I> Seven Wonders of the Middle
Ages (1)</i>, as well as the
<I>Seven Natural Wonders of the World
(2)</i>. It's a nice custom carried over the
centuries, one that raises respect for what our ancestors accomplished
with far fewer resources than we and at the same time lays down a
challenge for us. <I>The Seven Natural Wonders</i>, in
turn, put our man-made wonders in perspective. 
</p>
<p>
<P>There is no "official" list yet of the <I>Seven
Wonders of the Modern World</i> that I know of. But candidates
abound: canals (Panama, Suez) . . . bridges (Golden Gate, Verrazano,
Humber) . . . dams (Oroville, Hoover, Rogun) . . . tunnels (Seikan,
Channel) . . . buildings (World Trade Center, Empire State) . . .
trans-Atlantic liners (especially <I>Normandie,
Queen Mary, Queen
Elizabeth, United States</i>) . . . the
electric light . . . the automobile . . . aircraft . . . spacecraft and
space probes . . . radio/TV . . . information systems (printing press,
typewriter, telegraph, telephone, computer, Internet) . . . . Note the
transition in this list from civil and mechanical engineering works to
what, for a better term, I call "electronic works." Draw your own
conclusions. 
</p>
<p>
But which seven of these would <I>you</i> pick? Which
seven would still impress our successors 2,000 years from now, even as
the Pyramids still entrance us, even though (and maybe because) we
haven't quite figured out how they built them? Maybe we should start
thinking in terms of seven times seven? 
</P>


<P>Well, we're not asking you to make <I>that</i> pick.
What we are asking you is to propose none other than the
<i>Seven Wonders of the Chemical World</i>. For chemists and chemical
engineers like you, that should be an easy assignment, right? Well,
play our game and find out.
</p>
<p>
So what should they be? There are so many "invisible" wonders to
choose from, wonders that lie behind all those others, including even
the natural wonders. Surely we would all agree that the periodic table
should be on any such list, just as the Pyramids of Egypt made that
ancient list. Wouldn't we? In fact, it would top mine. But then what?
What are the other six? 
</p>

<P>What all the various wonders have in common is that they all inspire
awe in terms of their size, ingenuity, and/or beauty, or, in the case
of the natural wonders, their overwhelming beauty. They invite
superlatives. They make you proud to belong to the human race and make
you want to excel, even as they make you humble. 
</P>


<P>The<I> Seven Wonders of the Chemical World</i> are at
a disadvantage in one sense. Ordinary folks can't see them, at least
at their working level, certainly not with a chemist's eye. But if
those folks could transport themselves into the molecular and atomic
world, as subatomic Lilliputians, they would see a similar set of
awe-inspiring sights. This is at once the chemist's good fortune,
frustration, and challenge - to get others to see their (your) world as
they see it. 
</P>


<P>In any event, the<I> Seven Wonders of the Chemical
World</i>, in a very basic sense, as I have indicated, underlie
all of those other wonders. And unlike some of the other wonders, they
are not eroding with time. They are in place for
<I>all</i> time. 
</P>


<P>The candidates are many and listing them is relatively easy.
Here's a starter list (in no special order): the periodic table . . .
the atomic model . . . photography . . . synthetic polymers, as in
plastics, hybrids, fibers, and materials . . . pharmaceuticals . . .
nuclear (atomic) power . . . the scanning tunneling microscope . . .
exploration of the nanoworld . . . deciphering of the genetic code and
all that has followed, including gene therapy . . . the green
revolution in agriculture . . . transistor/semiconductors . . .
the laser . . . catalysis . . . . 
</P>


<P>Winnowing any such list down to just seven is a formidable task. And
that's where <I>you</i> come in. With this article,
we are asking for entries to a sort of contest to forge an
"official" list of the<I> Seven Wonders of the
Chemical World</i>. 
</P>


<P>
<h4><font color="red">Your entries should include the following
information:</font></h4>
<ol>
<li>Your list, together with short statements justifying each of
your candidates (e.g., "I think such and such is one of the seven
wonders because . . . ."). 
<li>A short summary statement tying it all together in some fashion. 
<li>Your name, address, title and area of expertise, phone/fax number
and, if you have one, e-mail address. 
</ol>
</p>
<p>
<h4><font color="red">Please mail your entries no later than <b>24 March 1997
</b> to:</font>
</P>


<P>
<center>Seven Wonders<br> 
<i>Today's Chemist at Work</i><br> 
American Chemical Society<br> 
1155 Sixteenth St., N.W.<br> 
Washington, DC 20036
</p>
<p>
or use our e-mail address: <b><a href="mailto:tcaw@acs.org">tcaw@acs.org</a>
</b><br>
or fax us at 202-872-4403.</center></h4> 
</p>
<p>Please note that this article
will also be carried on the Internet, timed to coincide approximately
with mail delivery of our February issue. See <b><a href="http://www.acs.org.">
http://www.acs.org</a></b>
</p>
<p> 
<P>Entries will be judged on the quality/significance of your
wonders and how you present them. And yes, if you feel the urge, you
may, like Antipater of Sidon, put your suggestions in the form of a
poem . . . or whatever . . . . Your wonders might include, as hinted at
in my list above: a chemical family . . . an instrument . . . a
chemical map, such as the periodic table . . . a model or concept
(tested and tried and true) . . . . But clearly, they should be
developments that have had a seminal influence on chemistry, science,
<I>and</i> society and are pathfinders for all of us
who follow. 
</P>


<P>Entries will be judged by Dr. Ned D. Heindel, a past-president of the
American Chemical Society and professor of chemistry, Lehigh
University, and a panel appointed by him. 
</P>


<P>The "top seven" entries so chosen will be included in an article
appearing in the June 1997 issue of <I>Today's Chemist at
Work</i> in connection with our fifth anniversary. In addition, we
will use <I>all</i> entries as "ballots" and
will compute from this an "average" that will become the
<I>Official Seven Wonders of the Chemical World</i>. 
</P>


<P>The first 1,000 entrants will receive an illustrated National Chemistry
Week periodic table (suitable for framing). Everybody wins. 
</P>


<P>As judged,
<ul>
<li>Each of the <I>top seven</i> will receive a
triple prize: a tie inscribed with the periodic table or a woman's
watch with the twelve hours denoted as the first twelve elements, a
customized T-shirt illustrating each winning entry, and a copy of
<I>Your Chemical World</i> (an ACS book describing how
chemistry relates to the well-being of everyone).
<li>Each of the <I>second seven</i> will receive
a double prize: an ACS coffee mug inscribed with the periodic table and
a copy of <I>Your Chemical World</i>.
<li>Each of the <I>third seven</i> will receive
an ACS coffee mug inscribed with the periodic table. 
</ul>
</p>
<p>
Note: The coffee mugs come in "caffeine" and
"decaf" models, with appropriate symbols - -your choice. 
</P>


<P>All of you who participate in this exercise will receive our
undying gratitude. 
</p>
<p>
<h3><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/tcaw/97/feb/source.html">Sources
</a></h3>
</P>
<p>
