<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>EUROPE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>December 16, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<h1><big><center><font color="blue">WESTERN EUROPE</font></big><br>
Mediocre Year Lays Ground <br>
For Hope In 1997</center></h1>
<h3><font color="red">Patricia L. Layman</font><br>
<i>C&EN London</i></h3>
<hr noshade>
<p>
Last year, there was a sense of surprise
in the European chemical industry
when a slowdown rippled through it.
In 1996, the surprise has been replaced by
disappointment as the hoped-for resumption in growth failed to materialize.</P>
<P>Now, the chemical industry is testing
its forecasters. They are being asked if
the industry's upturn in the latter part of
the third quarter and into the fourth will
continue into a rosier 1997. They are being asked if the strong exports during
1996 will continue to underpin chemical
growth. And they are being asked if the
industry can capitalize on the improving
general economic conditions in the region to support solid growth into the
coming year.</P>
<P>The cautious answer to those questions is a qualified
"yes." As Richard D.
Freeman, corporate chief economist
with the U.K.'s ICI, puts it, "We are looking for a better year next year.
This year
was not a 'bad' year, it was just marked
by slow growth."</P>
<P>Presenting the most recent conclusions of the
European Chemical Industry
Council's (CEFIC) Economic Outlook
Working Party, Freeman says 1997 is
likely to be "a relatively strong year for
chemical production."</P>
<P>Among the factors supporting that assessment
are exports and inventories. "Export demand from outside Europe appears
to be on the increase, and it is expected to
boost production next year," he notes."
Demand in Eastern Europe is reported by
panel members to be buoyant, and exports to Asia are strong."</P>
<P>Meanwhile, after several years of
chemical buyers running down inventories, "stock changes are forecast
to be positive for growth in 1997. Stock levels
are estimated by the panel to be low in
most countries. This is the case both upstream and downstream in the industry,"
says Freeman.</P>
<P>The upshot is that chemical production in 1997
likely will rise by more than
3% rather than the 2% first predicted by
the panel early in the year. This follows
an estimated increase of less than 2% for
1996.</P>
<P>For Western Europe as a whole, general economic
growth in 1996 "has been
disappointingly slow," Freeman says."
The latest estimate is that [gross domestic product] will rise by
a miserable 1.5%.
That is about half the potential rate of
growth and well below the rate needed
to reverse the rise in unemployment."</P>
<P>Theodore S. Semegran, senior vice
president for New York City-based Dean
Witter Reynolds security analysts, notes
that Europe's general economy "continues
to grow slowly. It appears to be maintaining its 2% plus-or-minus pace of 1996
into 1997," he said in recent comments on the
European chemical industry. As he sees it:"
Key positive engines in Europe are the
U.K., Spain, and, to some extent, the
Benelux region [Belgium, Luxembourg,
and the Netherlands]. Key negatives have
been Germany and France."</P>
<center><img src="euracrylic.gif"></center>
<P>He sees two possible scenarios for
1997 in the European economy. One, his"
worse than" current economic scenario,
would reflect attempts by France, Italy,
and others to reduce their government
spending, to enable them to enter the European Monetary Union (EMU) by the
prescribed date - Jan. 1, 1999. Among the
effects of such policy would be government personnel reductions, combined
with the continued personnel cutbacks in
large European companies throughout industry, and still-slow wage growth. These
would all hurt overall European consumer spending.</P>
<P>On the other hand, Semegran says, a"
better than" current economic scenario
might occur with further weakening of
Europe's currencies relative to the U.S.
dollar. For example, "a weakening of 10 to
15% in the German mark to 1.70 to 1.80
per U.S. dollar would almost certainly result in increased exports of chemicals
from Europe," because most chemicals in
the region are priced in German marks.</P>
<P>Tight economic policies have, of course,
been a fact of life for a number of years,
Freeman points out. In fact, he believes they
have been mainly responsible for "a marked
slowdown in the growth of Western Europe since the end of the 1980s."</P>
<P>"Indeed," he says, "Western
European real GDP has risen over the past six years
at an annual average rate of only 1.6%. If
allowance is made for the effects of German unification, the growth rate has
averaged only about 1.3% per year since
1990." This compares with an average annual growth rate of 2.3% in the
period 1979 to 1989, he says.</P>
<P>Recent general economic growth has
been so slow, he says, because fiscal policies in most countries have been
restrictive in an attempt to try to get close to
the Maastricht budget deficit criteria of
3% of GDP in 1997 - a forerunner of policy needed for the EMU entry mentioned
by Semegran.</P>
<P>Moreover, monetary policy - given the
restrictiveness of fiscal policy - has been
too tight in most European countries, Freeman
suggests. And, noting the impact of
inventory changes over the past several
years, he adds, "activity in our economies
has been depressed by the rundown of
the high levels of involuntary stocks which
built up in 1994 and early 1995."</P>
<center><img src="eurchem.gif"></center>
<P>However, he says - with the exception
of Italy - all the main countries are expecting a considerable improvement
in GDP
growth in 1997. As in 1996, these countries are projecting an improvement in
their budget positions next year. However, the CEFIC working party opted for a
cautious consideration for the economy
next year; hence its forecast of 2% growth,
compared with a consensus forecast of
2.3% by various official bodies.</P>
<P>As for industrial production, the CEFIC
group forecasts a stronger pickup than for
real GDP, Freeman says - but certainly,
there is room for growth. Following two
years of strong growth in 1994 and 1995,
all industrial production in Western Europe
is expected to rise only 0.6% this year, according to estimates by the CEFIC
panel. Industrial production was very weak from the
second quarter of 1995 to the second quarter of 1996, primarily because of the
influence of overbuilt inventories.</P>
<P>However, says Freeman, with stocks at
low levels and demand strengthening,
growth has resumed in the third quarter,
and this is expected to continue. The panel
expects industrial output to rise 2.5%.</P>
<P>A similar pattern is emerging for the
chemicals sector of Western European industry, according to Freeman, although
a major difficulty has developed that hinders
forecasting. "The quality of chemical industry statistics is not nearly
as good as those
for the whole economy," he says. "Over the
past 12 months, we have had numerous
large revisions to chemical production data.
The major problem has been in Germany - a significant part of the West European
industry. It is difficult even to get a firm fix
on what has been happening in the industry
this year, let alone get a good basis for forecasting next year's output."</P>
<center><img src="eurmajor.gif"></center>
<P>According to Freeman, the industry in
the region has seen "some important revisions to the data, and there also
has been
some new data. The first effect of the revisions and new data is to reduce the
estimated increase in chemical production
this year. The second is to increase the
growth rate forecast for next year."</P>
<P>The latest data analysis shows that chemical
production tumbled by more than 3%
in the second half of 1995 and recovered
by only about 1% in first-half 1996. Only
strong growth of roughly 5.5% in the second half of 1996 has kept the year from
looking bleak.</P>
<P>One indication of the pickup from lackluster
1995 was the tangential - but significant - increase in consumption
of platinum catalysts in the chemical industry in Europe
this year. Use in 1996 by the industry, particularly for nitric acid production,
 was expected to hit 65,000 troy ounces, up nearly
20% from 1995. That is a larger increase
than estimated for any other world region,
according to the annual interim review
compiled by British precious-metals company Johnson Matthey. The review
indicated that continued, steady growth in catalyst
consumption in the European chemical industry is expected over at least the
next two years.</P>
<P>Chemical industry growth will settle
down somewhat, to a level that is expected to sustain the 3% that the CEFIC
working party forecasts for chemical production for 1997. And if anything, 
Freeman says, "the balance of risks is for
stronger growth of
chemical production
in 1997 than has been
forecast."</P>
<P>CEFIC's observations about the turnaround in
the second half of this past year
are supported by comments from securities
analysts in Western
Europe. For example,
according to the London-based chemicals
analysts at Salomon
Brothers, "companies
are reporting a pickup in demand, with
quarterly volumes above previous-year
levels for the first time in many months."
In their latest report, "Periodic Tables,"
analysts Peter D. Blair and Leslie Chow
say, "This pickup is mirrored in the underlying economic indicators, which
since the first quarter in continental Europe and which have remained strong
in the U.K." Economists at Salomon Brothers now predict slightly above-trend
growth in Europe in 1997, with stable
inflation, they add.</P>
<center><img src="eurdol.gif"></center>
<center><img src="eurecon.gif"></center>
<center><img src="eurmatch.gif"></center>
<P>However, Blair and Chow caution that
although demand recovery in Europe"
should provide a sound basis for earnings
improvement across the board, in the
chemical industry, the supply side of the
equation normally dominates the demand
side. There are risks from increasing capacity in Europe for several products
in 1997, and ethylene should not face the abnormal production problems that
beset the industry in the first half of 1996, taking
out 5% of normal production levels. The
result may well be a polyolefins downturn
during 1997," they say.</P>
<P>That pickup in business has not been
seen universally. For example, when
Royal Dutch/Shell reported its third-quarter results last month, the company
grumbled that its chemicals operations"
show only limited signs of improvement in parts of the business, with trading
conditions remaining difficult. Along
with the industry, change can only come
when there is significant growth in the
industrial economies," the company's
statement says.</P>
<P>Petrochemical producers seem likely
to be among the major winners in 1997,
however, predicts Tony Church, chemicals analyst at London-based Schroders
Securities. According to his recently published comments on the European
chemical industry, "After a confused end to
1996, we expect early 1997 to see a very
sharp upturn in activity and prices, based
on a more confident customer base rebuilding inventories.</P>
<P>"We expect a sharp improvement in
the cyclical chemical businesses in early
1997. There is a better than even chance
that improved economic confidence in
Europe will lead to a disproportionately
positive effect on demand for, and prices
of, heavy chemicals. In total, we believe
that 1997 will see a sharp increase in the
activity levels of the European petrochemical industry, to be followed by a
downturn in the following year."</P>
<P>He added, "This view could be radically
altered by a number of uncertainties: At recent industry conferences, we
judged the mood as one of cautious optimism about 1997, rather than a
flag-waving enthusiasm."</p>
<P>One of the major factors causing the
industry to perk up during 1996 has
been exports, according to Freeman. "Exports of chemicals in the recent
period have been relatively buoyant, given the
weakness of domestic demand," he said."
Growth of imports, on the other hand,
has been fairly weak."</P>
<P>The CEFIC economic panel estimates
that exports rose about 3.5% this year,
and imports were up 2.8%. In 1997,
chemical exports are forecast to increase
4% and imports, 3.5%.</P>
<P>On the basis of the production and
trade forecasts, CEFIC concludes that demand for chemicals in Western Europe in
1997 will increase "at a considerably faster rate than it has done this
year" - a relatively healthy increase of more than 3%.</P>
<P>As the year comes to a close, it is clear
that - as the CEFIC working panel forecast
last year - the rate of growth in capital
spending in the chemical industry in 1996
was less than it was in 1995, which was a
particularly strong year following several
years of tight budget purse strings.</P>
<P>Tracking the chemical industry's capital spending
in Western Europe is complicated by lack of reporting of such figures by
Ireland, Portugal, Greece, and
Switzerland, all countries in the CEFIC
orbit. However, CEFIC's statistics for all
the other Western European countries
over the past decade show that capital
spending grew from about $16.7 billion
in 1986 to a high in 1990 - the height of
the industry's big-spending frenzy - of
approximately $27.2 billion. Subsequently, it has simmered down, decreasing
each year through 1994. In 1995, spending was up smartly from the previous
year to $23.1 billion.</P>
<P>CEFIC's panel estimates, however, that
the increase this year will be 6.7% over
most of the major countries suggests that the
rise in capital spending is likely to be
small - in the range of 2 to 3%. In a sense,
that may reflect lessons learned, suggests
Dean Witter's Semegran.</P>
<P>"Modest chemical and petrochemical
investments by Europeans in Europe are
expected to continue," he says. European producers, he points out, are
concentrating much more on "plant debottlenecking and swapping or buying
assetts of others," than on new plants.</P>
<center><img src="eurwest.gif"></center>
<P>"One of the most obvious new trends
is a rash of major new European projects
by U.S.-headquartered firms - including
Amoco, Exxon, Dow, Union Carbide, and
Eastman," he adds. "U.S. companies seem
to be even more optimistic about their
businesses in Europe than many Europeans. Apparently, Europeans have learned
from past recessions: The many recent
business sales and joint ventures, in lieu of
building new capacity, suggest that many
European companies have learned."</P>
<P>Another lesson the industry has learned
is the cost of overstaffing. Despite the difficulties - legal and cultural - of
cutting back, the industry is continuing what has
been a 15-year trend of trimming employees. CEFIC estimates that employment
in the chemical industry in Western Europe
has fallen nearly 2% this year. Since 1990,
employment in the industry has fallen
nearly 300,000, and it's still on a downward path. Although the CEFIC panel
has not made a precise forecast for 1997, Freeman notes that "the available
country forecasts point to a similar reduction in 1997
as in this year."</P>
<P>The CEFIC panel might not have an
official forecast on employment, but it is
willing to commit itself on the sexier
subject of prices. According to Freeman:"
Reflecting weak demand and excess capacity worldwide, producer prices in
Western Europe are estimated to have
fallen by 1.7% this year. Much of the fall
seems now to be behind us, and prices
have flattened out or are rising a little.</P>
<P>"For 1997, the panel has forecast a
rise in producer prices of 1%,"
he says, adding that the "panel
believes there is a strong probability that price increases will be
better than forecast." In fact,
Freeman adds, among the most
optimistic members of CEFIC's
working party were the German
representatives. "When the Germans begin to talk about rising
prices, you have to sit up and take
notice," he observes.</P>
<P>The disappointments of the
year that is ending have been localized more than in the past.
And continuing the trend that
has developed since the reunification of the country, the major"
sufferer" has been Germany.</P>
<P>For example, at Germany's
Bayer, 1996 will be a good year - no
thanks to its headquarters country. Says
Manfred Schneider, Bayer's chairman,
about 1996: "We have set ourselves the
goal of achieving a new record in 1996.
Although not all our expectations have
been met because the business climate in
Europe - our home market - has remained
cooler than forecast, we are holding fast to
our targets for the year."</P>
<center><img src="eurfix.gif"></center>
<P>Market trends, he says, varied from one
region to another. In Europe, sales grew in
the first nine months by just 2% over the
comparable period of 1995, and "actually
stagnated in local currencies. The chief
cause was weak demand in Germany," although sales volumes were also down in
Spain, Switzerland, Austria, and the Benelux countries.</P>
<P>Schneider may be able to take some
comfort from the experience of his
counterparts at D&uuml;sseldorf-based Henkel,
with its hefty proportion of sales coming
from downstream, consumer products
such as detergents, formulated adhesives, and personal care products.</P>
<P>According to Henkel executives, demand is still
sluggish in Germany, but the
company says it saw signs in the third
quarter of the year that consumer demand
in the country is beginning to pick up.</P>
<P>An increased demand for consumer
products in Germany - as in the rest of
the region - will feed back, eventually,
into increased demand for basic chemicals. And on such a hint, the Western
European chemical industry is founding
its hopes for serious improvements in 1997.
</p>
<hr noshade><br>
<center><h1>Return to <br><br><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/cenear/96121
6/index.html"><img src="worldsm.gif"></center></h3></a>

