<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NORTH AMERICA - USA</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>December 16, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<h1><big><center><font color="red">NORTH AMERICA</font></big><br>
U.S. Chemical Industry Faces<br>
Likelihood Of Slow Growth Next Year</center></h1>                         
<h3><font color="00008B">William J. Storck</font><br>
<i>C&EN Northeast News Bureau</i></h3>
<hr noshade>
<p>
This past year has been a trying one
for the U.S. chemical industry. Following big earnings gains last year,
major chemical companies have not fared
very well in 1996. This year, earnings are
off from 1995 levels and sales are going
nowhere. Through the first nine months
of this year, earnings from 30 major chemical companies regularly surveyed byC&amp;EN declined 7% from the same period
last year to about $6.0billion on a 1% sales
decline to $66.9billion. Profit margins remained high, however, averaging
9.0%
compared with profitability of 9.6%
through the first three quarters of 1995
(C&amp;EN, Nov. 18, page 12).</P>
<P>The question is: Will next year be any
better? The answer, according to a number of forecasters, is maybe, but only
a little.</p>
<P>This year, the general economy has
been growing, but relatively slowly. Estimates for gross domestic product (GDP)
growth this year hover around 2.5% -
spurred by an apparently anomalous
4.1% growth rate in the second quarter.
Thus, in a highly cyclical industry such as
chemicals, slow growth, if any, could be
expected.</p>
<P>In 1996, production and prices of
chemicals - particularly the big-volume industrial chemicals - have
been down from
levels of a year ago, especially in the latter
part of the year. Shipments of major chemicals have done very little. Raw
material costs have risen. Major end-use markets,
such as housing and automobiles, have
slowed. And lately, the chemical trade surplus, long a big contributor to
chemical company fortunes, has been shrinking.
The result for many chemical producers
has been lackluster sales growth and earnings declines.</P>
<P>In 1996, C&amp;EN estimates that production of
chemicals and allied products increased some 2.5% from last year to an
index of about 128.0 (1987=100). This
compares with almost 3.0% growth in
1995. And for large-volume industrial
chemicals, the production index should
verage about 122.8 in 1996, only a 0.4%
increase. This compares with growth of
2.0% in 1995.</P>
<p>The same picture holds with pricing.
The Labor Department's producer price
index for 1996 averages about 142.1
(1982=100) for chemicals and allied
products, down 0.4% from 1995. And the
index for the more cyclical industrial
chemicals averages about 126.9, a drop of
about 1.5% from last year.</P>
<P>Demand for chemicals, however, has
risen somewhat this year. The industry
shipped some $370 billion worth of
chemicals and allied products during the
year, up 3.2% from last year. But the value of industrial chemicals shipments
dipped somewhat, down almost 1% from
1995 to $185 billion.</P>
<P>This is not surprising because, as the
Chemical Manufacturers Association
points out, the industrial chemicals segment has become a mature industry.
CMA says constant-dollar demand for the
entire chemical industry will grow at a
rate of about 1.2 times GDP growth in
the 1990s. But this includes pharmaceuticals, which the association says will
grow at about 2.7 times GDP growth. Industrial chemicals, however, are averaging
about 0.7 times GDP growth. Thus, a
2.5% rise in GDP translates into less than
1.8% real growth in industrial chemicals.
Over the past four decades, this multiple
of GDP for industrial chemicals has
shrunk from 2.9% in the 1960s, 1.5% in
the 1970s, and 1.0% in the 1980s.</P>
<center><img src="uschem.gif"></center>
<p>Production of petrochemicals this
year has been a mixed picture, with essentially moderate growth to slight
declines, according to data from the National Petroleum Refiners Association.
Production of ethylene, the bellwether
olefin, for instance, through the first nine
months grew 2% over the same period in
1995 to 36.2billion lb. But for propylene, the other major olefin, output
declined 5.9% to 18.5billion lb during the
same period. And on the aromatic side,
production of the highly cyclical benzene fell 3.3% to 1.59 billion gal.</P>
<P>Further downstream, there have been
some mighty gains in plastics production
and demand. The Society of the Plastics
Industry estimates that this year output of
major thermoplastics increased 8.0% from
1995 to 65.7 billion lb, and that shipments grew almost 12% to 69.0 billion
lb. Production of thermosetting resins
grew a more modest 4% to 7.82 billion
lb, and demand also grew 4% to 7.79 billion lb.</P>
<P>Growth in thermoplastics is being
paced by linear low-density polyethylene, with output rising 22% to 6.4 billion
lb and demand growing 27% to almost
7.9 billion lb. Growth rates for other
thermoplastics are much more modest,
but for the most part still respectable.
The next highest in terms of output is
polypropylene, which gained 9.4% to
11.9 billion lb. High-density polyethylene
is the second highest in demand growth,
at 13.8% to 7.88 billion lb.</P>
<P>Fibers, however, continued their
modest ways during the year. According
to data from the Fiber Economics Bureau, shipments of synthetic fibers
through the first eight months of this
year totaled 7.05billion lb, down 0.5%
from the same period in 1995. Within
the group, nylon demand grew 3.1% to
2.11 billion lb, but polyester shipments
fell 3.2% to 2.82billion lb.</P>
<P>One of the big disappointments this
year has been the chemical trade balance. Exports of chemicals totaled about
$62.2 billion, up less than 1% from last
year. At the same time, imports totaled
about $45.0 billion, up more than 11.4%.
Thus, the chemical trade surplus fell
about 19% to about $17.2billion. However, it still will be the largest
surplus of any U.S. industry, according to CMA.</P>
<center><img src="ustrade.gif"></center>
<P>The big problem in foreign trade, as it
was for production, was industrial chemicals - particularly organic chemicals,
exports of which declined about 9% to less
than $15.0 billion. Industry sources say
this decline is largely because of petrochemical capacity coming onstream in
the Asia-Pacific region, thus cutting exports
from the U.S. and other countries to that
area. Exports of other commodities, although in the positive column, had only
moderate growth. Inorganic chemical exports rose only 0.6% to about $4.6 
billion; plastics exports increased about 3% to
$15.6 billion; but fertilizer exports declined about 1.8% to $3.2 billion.</P>
<P>Some specialty chemical categories
posted good growth. Pharmaceutical exports, for instance, finished the year
up 11.5% to $7.3billion. And exports of essential oils, which include
toiletries and cosmetics, grew 10% to a value of about $4.3 billion.</p>
<P>Imports of chemicals this year have been
buoyed by a strengthening dollar against
key currencies, and organic chemicals have
shown the largest dollar growth. Imports
of organics this year grew almost 14% to a
value of some $15.2 billion. This has caused a
$1.8 billion trade deficit
in organic chemicals compared with a surplus of
about the same amount in 1995.</p>
<p>The highest growth in imports was posted by pharmaceuticals,
rising 21% to a value of about $6.7 billion.
This is a category in which strong trade, in
both exports and imports, likely will continue because of the increased foreign
ownership of U.S. drug producers and the
accompanying intracompany trade.</P>
<P>Most other trade categories this year
have boosted imports between 2 and 6%,
with the exception of the "other" sector, for which imports grew
about 20% to $4.7 billion.</p>
<P>For next year, the outlook may be
more of the same. Projections of economic growth in the U.S. are falling below
the 1996 rate. For instance, a survey
of 37 forecasters by the Federal Reserve
Bank of Philadelphia puts growth of real
GDP at 2.3% next year, compared with
an estimated 2.5% this year.</p>
<center><img src="ustrend.gif"></center><br>
<center><img src="usexp1.gif"></center><br>
<center><img src="usexp2.gif"></center>
<P>In its year-end economic survey, however, CMA
is taking a much harder line,
predicting a 1.8% rise in GDP next year,
followed by 2.3% growth in 1998.</P>
<P>Nevertheless, CMA is almost in agreement with
the Philadelphia Federal Reserve Bank about inflation next year. The
chemical trade group projects 2.9% inflation; the Federal Reserve Bank's
forecasters, 3.0%.</p>
<P>CMA, which surveyed its members
to get a consensus forecast, projects a
5% increase in sales dollars next year,
compared with a 1% rise this year. However, CMA members predict a 10% rise
in net operating income. Interestingly,
for 1996, the consensus forecast was
for a 5.6% increase in net operating income, with producers that have sales
of more than $1 billion projecting only a
0.1% increase. Forecasters from companies with less than $1 billion in
sales, which tend to be more niche producers
or specialty chemical makers, see net
operating income rising a median of
10% this year.</P>
<P>The respondents to the CMA survey
see higher operating costs next year with
feedstock unit costs rising 2.5%, other
energy costs up 2.0%, and hourly wage
increases of 3.3%, so they may be hard-pressed to get the 10% earnings gain
without further cost cutting.</P>
<P>And there are concerns that cost cutting may
mean further cuts in employment. Since the first part of 1994 through
November of 1996, the U.S. chemical industry has lost 51,000 workers. About
8,000 of those cuts came just since January of this year. But the workforce
is apparently an easy place to cut expenses.
And this is confirmed by the CMA survey. Although a weighted average of the
under-$1 billion companies see a 2.3%
rise in employment in 1997, the over-$1 billion companies see a 1.1%
decline. This, however, is less than the 1.9% cut forecast
by the larger producers for 1996.</P>
<P>However, if there is just a 1% further
reduction in chemical industry employment, this would translate into more
than 10,000 additional jobs cut. Although
this may, at first glance, seem excessive,
the U.S. chemical industry is well on the
way there before 1997 even starts with
the announced 1,500 to 2,500 employees that will be let go in the Monsanto
spin-off of its chemical operation (see page 9).</p>
<P>In essence, 1997 may look a lot like
1996: low economic growth, low inflation. And the chemical industry will respond
with only slightly higher economics of its own in production, pricing,
sales, and earnings.</P>
<P>One thing is sure, though. Chemical
producers are going to continue to watch
costs - especially in discretionary areas
such as employment and inventories.
</p>
<hr noshade><br>
<center><h1>Return to <br><br><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/cenear/961216/index.html"><img src="worldsm.gif"></center></h3></a>

</BODY>
</HTML>











