<HEAD>
<TITLE>Employment Outlook: DOWNSIZING</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<h1>Chemical & Engineering News</h1>
<h2>October 28, 1996</h2>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society
<hr noshade></h5>
<center><img src="downsizhead.gif"><br><br>
<h2><font color="8B2252"><i>It has disrupted the lives of chemists and
changed the face of employment, but it
often can lead to new opportunities</I></font></h2></center>
<H3>Elisabeth Kirschner, C&ampEN Northeast News Bureau</H3>
<P>"It was a horrible time and it
was a
wonderful time," says Donald Upson, of his 1994 layoff from Sterling
Winthrop. Upson was one of hundreds
who lost jobs when Eastman Kodak
backed out of its fledgling pharmaceutical business, selling Sterling Winthrop
to
Elf Sanofi.</P>
<P>"Everybody panicked, but we pulled
together and supported each other. It
was the old story of synergies and efficiencies," Upson explains. When
the
sale was announced, everyone knew the
end was near, he says. Sanofi didn't want
the people or the buildings, but did want
the value of the existing products and
some of those in the pipeline. Upson
was one of the lucky ones. He's now
vice president of operations at Molecular
Probes, Eugene, Ore.</P>
<P>Over the past five years, downsizing
has wiped out hundreds of thousands of
jobs, disrupted the lives of employees,
and changed the face of employment.
Chemists have not been spared. Globalization, consolidation, computerization,
and divestment have resulted in dramatic
changes in employment.</P>
<P>Many of the chemical companies that
diversified in the 1980s to buffer their
cyclical businesses were not able to manage their new businesses effectively.
Now, after a rash of divestitures in the
early 1990s, many chemical companies
focus on core competencies, with fewer
employees. Pharmaceutical companies,
merging to weather the changes in the
health care system, make jobs redundant
during the consolidations. Computerization and reengineering have further supplanted
people. And some companies
look to job cuts to improve productivity
and stock prices.</P>
<P>DuPont cited "improvements in fundamental
business processes and practices" in its announcement earlier this year
that it would cut 1,500 jobs in its nylon
and polyester units, about 8% of the unit
workforce (C&amp;EN, March 4, page 9). The
cuts come on the heels of a multiyear,
$2 billion reorganization that cost at
least 5,800 jobs. Mobil Chemical planned
to eliminate 2,300 jobs in a 1994 restructuring, blaming lower earnings and
excess capacity. Not all of the cuts resulted
in layoffs, says a company spokesman,
since some of the employees shifted to
the new owners when businesses or
plants were sold.</P>
<P>The merger of Ciba-Geigy and Sandoz is
expected to result in a reduction of about
10,000 in the new company's worldwide
workforce (C&amp;EN, April 8, page 13). The
jobs eliminated are expected to be administrative positions and from overlapping
manufacturing operations, with few cuts
planned for R&amp;D. These are some of the
big restructurings, but many chemists
say their companies "keep under the radar" of publicity by cutting
small groups
at a time without fanfare.</P>
<center><img src="agegraph.gif"></center>
<P>Some consultants say the worst cuts
are over. A survey by Right Associates, a
career management consulting company
located in Philadelphia, found that nearly
half of the 78 companies it surveyed in the
chemicals and pharmaceuticals sector expect continuing - though smaller - layoffs
within the next 18 months. And at the
same time jobs are cut at large companies,
there has been growth in some smaller
companies and at consulting firms, and
even strategic hiring within companies announcing huge layoffs.</P>
<P>In preparing this article, C&amp;EN sought
out chemists who had lost their jobs to
talk about their experiences. Not surprisingly, few chemists who lost their
jobs
were willing to be identified in C&amp;EN,
even if they had landed new positions.
Some who spoke with C&amp;EN said former
colleagues who had been downsized
would rather not be interviewed at all.
They did not want to sound bitter or depressed, alienate old colleagues or new
or potential employers, or jeopardize ongoing litigation. Age discrimination
was
frequently suspected among chemists
who lost their jobs.</P>
<P>Many chemical companies contacted
by C&amp;EN were even less forthcoming.
Some refused to comment on downsizing
questions at all. Others did not respond to
repeated requests for information.</P>
<hr noshade>
<A HREF="sidedown.html"><h3>TO SIDEBAR: One chemists's story of downsizing</h3>
</A>
<hr noshade>
<P>Whether called downsizing, right sizing, or layoffs - whether
spurred by attempts to shore up stock prices, company mergers, plant closings,
or reengineering efficiencies - massive
job losses have shaken up
the chemical industry. Reengineering and downsizing have been creating a
new workplace, a new
workforce, and a new attitude toward employment.
While the cost cutting has
benefited the bottom line
of some companies, it has
wreaked havoc on job security, morale, and chemists' lives.</P>
<P>"The first day I was in a
fog," says one downsized
chemist who spoke on condition of anonymity. "The
next day I got angry. I was
thinking about suing." The
group downsized by his employer suspected the cuts
were based on age, but "there was nothing you could
sink your teeth into," he
says. "The third day, I realized I would
have to make job hunting a full-time occupation, and that I wanted a better
job."
Luckily, he says, the company provided
career counseling to get him through
those three days. "It was a catharsis," he
says. "We could get the venom out early."</P>
<P>Within a month, he found a new job
that had the atmosphere his previous job
had lost years ago. "Friends have told me
I look tranquil. Like a weight's been taken off my shoulders. Thank God [the
layoff] did happen. They did me a favor."</P>
<P>In the end, he says, "I don't know
whether it was better for the people who
were laid off or for the ones who remain
at the old job. They don't have enough
manpower. It's a hellhole." Some of his
fellow downsized colleagues are double-
dipping at the old company, he says. They
receive retirement benefits and are back
on the payroll as consultants. But there are
others he has lost track of, who may not
have fared as well.</P>
<P>Another chemist who moved up to a
better job after being downsized says
some former colleagues could only find
temporary or part-time work for a few
years before finding full-time employment. Coworkers who did not want to
move to a different part of the country
had a more difficult time finding new positions, he adds. Still others "panicked"
after a layoff, grabbing a job offer made
the very next day, but switching again
within the year.</P>
<P>Another chemist who was caught up
in a downsizing more than a decade ago
says the dramatic cuts have changed the
way people look at their work and its
loss. Back then, the downsized and the
public were shocked at the news, she
says. Now, with downsizing so common,
it takes something like the 40,000 cuts
announced by AT&amp;T in January to surprise the public.</P>
<P>Despite knowing that layoffs were
coming, most chemists say they were
shocked when told they were the ones to
lose their jobs. Years ago, workers knew
that "if they continued to work, kept their
noses clean, everything would be fine,"
says Valerie J. Kuck, American Chemical
Society councilor for the North Jersey Section and a scientist at Lucent Technologies'
Bell Laboratories. Now, "you can do
all the right things and you can be out."
When she and other members of the ACS
North Jersey Section met with laid-off
chemists a few years ago, says Kuck, a
group of about two dozen men showed
up. One had won a performance award
from his employer early in the year, only
to be dismissed in a layoff. "All of them
looked exhausted.</P>
<P>"The stigma is all gone because so
many people have been affected," says
Kuck. "A layoff is no reflection on what
you do or how you do your job. People
who thought they were doing well were
canned. Things have changed."</P>
<P>Indeed, says Nancy Blum, Right Associates career
management consultant,"
99% of the time [when people are laid
off] it has nothing to do with them, it's
just the slot they sat in." Ironically, sometimes the skills that an employee
has get
him or her transferred or promoted to a
less secure job that gets cut. Companies
are "cutting costs at the higher end, eliminating the most costly positions,"
says
Blum. "They're looking at numbers, not
particular employees."</P>
<center><img src="companies.gif"></center>
<P>But job loss, no matter what the
cause, remains a blow to self-esteem. The
time between jobs is so difficult "because of that uncertainty,"
says a downsized chemist who has moved on. "Before 
you get your next job, it's like jumping in a pool of ice water. You say to
yourself, 'Let's get it over. Let's just do
it.' Perhaps you have to jump in 15
times. Just get it over with. Sometimes it
takes 50 times."</P>
<P>"Everyone is likely to go through
downsizing. The job-for-life security is
gone," says Paul J. Forti of PJF Associates in East Hanover, N.J. Formerly
with
Right Associates, Forti works with people who have experienced downsizing."
Some go through shock, mourning, anger, and depression before they come to
terms with it."</P>
<P>The most important thing is to "get
out of their own way: They have the perception that the market is difficult.
They
have to get over their defeatist attitude,"
he says. If they have six to eight months'
severance pay to take care of the financial concerns, it's easier to deal with
the
other stresses of job loss and find a new
job, he says. Marriages that are already
strained can be pushed to the breaking
point, although some troubled couples
become closer when facing the crisis of
a downsizing.</P>
<P>If you have a good skills set, and network, you
will get a good job, says Forti.
Chemical engineers who don't have
good people skills, or whose research
skills are not honed, will have a harder
time. He says about 15 to 20% of his clients don't recoup the salary and position
they lost in the downsizing. "Forty percent do manage some level of success" - a
similar job, though perhaps with an unwanted move. "But 30 to 40% make
the
home run, get a better job, a promotion,
more money."</P>
<hr noshade>
<A HREF="side2down.html"><h3>TO SIDEBAR: Networks, counseling can help with job hunting after a downsizing</h3></A>
<hr noshade>
<P>After the Sterling Winthrop layoff, says
Upson, chemists with bachelor's and master's degrees were quickly snatched up
by
other companies. They're "always a hot
property, some with five, six, or seven job
offers to choose from. The young Ph.D.s
were from the finest schools; they did just
fine." Non-native-born chemists "needed
more help" and networking assistance, he
says. But "it was the middle-level group
leaders - the ones with three to six people
reporting to them - that were even more
of a challenge." The rest of industry was
already retrenching, often eliminating that
rung in the corporate ladder.</P>
<P>Suspicions of age discrimination in layoffs are
magnified by the greater difficulty
that older workers have in getting rehired.
Whether due to their more senior positions and greater financial needs in a
new
job, being set in their ways, or subtle or
not-so-subtle discrimination, older employees "have just one devil of
a time" landing
a new position, says Kuck. They often are
told they are overqualified.</P>
<P>"The vulnerability is down to 40
now," Kuck says. "I see more and more
people in their early 50s retiring." Most
of the older chemists she met had become consultants, where experience is a
benefit (see page 55).</P>
<P>Upson says Eastman Kodak "dealt with
us superbly well. From the announcement of the sale of Sterling Winthrop, we
knew we were about to lose jobs, but
we had five to six months of time in
which we were paid, and had access to
the library, phone, and fax." About 500
people lost their jobs during the merger,
he says, and many more have since then.
Only 10% of his former colleagues ended
up on the transition team and in successor companies.</P>
<P>The employees had just been relocated in the
spring of 1993 from Albany and
Rochester, N.Y., to new state-of-the-art
facilities in the Philadelphia area. Thirteen months later, the company was
up
for sale and the jobs were on the line. "A
move can be traumatic, and some spouses gave up their jobs on the faith that
Eastman's pharmaceuticals were a cornerstone of the corporation," says
Upson. "A lot of people really felt betrayed
and angry."</P>
<P>Upson says he and others realized that Eastman
had no choice
but to sell to Sanofi and that
Sanofi had no choice but to cut
the positions. "As a stockholder,
I applaud what [Eastman] did.
Selling off to Elf Sanofi was a
good business decision," Upson
says. Given the situation at the
company, he adds, "I might have
made the same decision. Eastman
was trapped in a pharmaceutical
operation that it had to shed."</P>
<P>Many chemists C&amp;EN spoke
with said they understood the
need for downsizing at their company and had mixed feelings
about the layoffs. But some didn't
see the need: The cuts "were just
to keep the stockholders happy,"
says one chemist, "but we're stockholders, too."</P>
<P>For many people, Forti says, a downsizing is
a turning point: They ask, "What
do I want to do until I die?" and realize
that their old job was not the answer
anyway.</P>
<P>David Liebeskind - who took an early
retirement from his Union Carbide post
as director of health, safety, and environmental affairs - found downsizing
a"
golden opportunity to move into teaching." He now teaches at New York
University's Stern School of Business and is a
principal with the management consulting firm Business Improvement Associates.
In those capacities, he studies reengineering and how it can go terribly
wrong.</P>
<P>"Reengineering is elimination of work,
not of people," he says, and many companies have eliminated people without
first
cutting out unnecessary work. "In the
long run, they put the work on other people. Then they have to bring in consultants
and temps. Many companies don't do it
right." He says Union Carbide succeeded,
because management had the "guts" to
change the way it did business.</P>
<P>Liebeskind maintains that 60 to 70%
of those companies that reengineered
aren't seeing good results. "A year, two
years down the road, they wake up and
find they solved nothing. Society is getting extremely ticked off with what's
happening to very talented people.
Unions, politicians make corporations rethink downsizing," says Liebeskind.
"A
number of companies that were planning to go down this road didn't."</P>
<center><img src="fell.gif"></center>
<P>Instead of downsizing, progressive
companies are looking for new customers,
says David L. Witte, chairman and chief
executive officer of Ward Howell International, a New York City-based executive
search firm. "They take people and reutilize them in other capacities,"
he says,
whether in expanding businesses around
the world or answering different needs.
Companies that downsized "perhaps
didn't look at their human resources as a
critical asset. They didn't know how to redeploy or retool. They used the 1950s'
approach and cut the head count. That's the
easy way out. Many cut back too far; they
don't have 38 to 46 year olds with global
management experience anymore. They
cut too deep. They don't have the high
level of talent they once had [to take advantage of the global growth]."</P>
<P>Growth is the name of the game now,
says Roger Kellett, vice president and
head of the North America chemicals
practice at Gemini Consulting, a management consulting firm in Morristown, N.J.
The U.S. chemicals industry has "finished the bulk of downsizing and restructuring,"
he says. "We're left with organizations that are highly focused on their
core businesses." Some of these companies are ready for new applications
and
new processes. And they are ready to
build.</P>
<P>In 1992, "80% of our business was in
reengineering," Kellett explains. "In
1995 and 1996, 70% of our business is in
growth-oriented strategies and people issues." He says many companies
are now
seeking help in cleaning up the mess of
a poor restructuring. "The good news is
they weren't our restructuring clients,"
Kellett adds.</P>
<P>"The best thing in the chemical industry
is that the up cycle has given
companies time to get creative
about how they focus people,"
says Kellett. "There's no urgency.
There's a lot of effort in 'reskilling.'</P>
<P>"In companies where restructuring was properly
done, [job
cuts] were based on needs. In another set of cases, jobs went
away, then came back in the form
of contractors, vendors, and consultants. In essence, the companies [made
their costs variable].
Then, those costs were cut as they
got smarter and better at taking
the work out. In the third case,
companies brought employees
back and didn't know what to do
with them.</P>
<P>"A whole lot of companies
made the mistake of taking people
out under the reengineering definition. That's okay as long as the work
goes away, but sometimes it ends up with
employees thinking 'My colleagues are
gone, but all the work is still here.' That
leads to low morale and stress."</P>
<P>Often, further cuts are expected, creating more
stress in the workplace and
lower productivity. Some downsized
chemists say cuts were made in small
groups, leaving the remaining employees"
in limbo."</P>
<P>"Some of the people who were left
feel guilty," says Kuck. "People they respected were axed."
Others have to deal
with threats: One chemist said his company evacuated its buildings multiple
times this summer in response to bomb
threats rumored to have come from a
former employee.</P>
<P>The "churn" in employment as restructuring
opens new jobs as others are
closed forces chemists to reassess their
skills and rethink their futures, while
companies reassess their needs. Indeed,
even DuPont, with its thousands of layoffs, has a "modest" hiring
program, and
is looking for Ph.D. and B.S. chemists."
We're reviewing our needs list," says a
spokesman.</P>
<P>When employees experience or witness downsizing,
they "keep their options open," says Forti. They look for
what they can get from the company."
Their morale, their trust of the corporation significantly decreases, sometimes
it's never the same and employees become 'optimistically pessimistic.'
They
remain loyal to an individual but never
trust the folks one level above the boss."</P>
<P>And the new employer is, for many
downsized employees, the old employer. After a wrenching blow to their morale,
they are offered positions in a different division, a different business, a
different location, or through a consulting
arrangement.</P>
<P>For one chemist rehired by his former
employer, resentment simmers despite
the reprieve from unemployment. After a
wrenching downsizing, he says, "you
just don't get those warm fuzzy feelings"
anymore.</P>
<P>"Worker backlash" might haunt downsized
companies that saw quick productivity improvements, warns Steven S. Roach,
chief economist for Morgan Stanley, a
New York City-based investment banking
firm. Workers who take up the slack are
not being paid more for their improved
productivity - the savings go to shareholders - but that may change
in union bargaining. And, he says, the apparent improvements may not last. "Breakthrough
technology platforms, process reengineering, and new outsourcing strategies
[were
seen as] crucial ingredients of the great
productivity turnaround of the 1990s,"
Roach advised clients in May in a research
report. But "managers may have simply focused on paring the largest chunk
of their
bloated cost structures - worker compensation, which represents 70% of corporate
production expenses."</P>
<P>Indeed, Roach says, "corporate America
may now be too lean. There is really
only one way out: upgrading the quality
of the workforce and recognizing the
need to rebuild."</P>
<P>The backlash already has become evident in politics.
On April 15, Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.) introduced the"
American Workers Economic Security
Act." Under the act, mergers and acquisitions, which already go through
antitrust
scrutiny, also would be examined for"
the impact on workers and communities." The proposal never made it to
hearings, but may be reintroduced in the
next session of Congress.</P>
<center><img src="stable.gif"></center>
<P>David B. Opton founded Exec-U-Net,
Norwalk, Conn., a membership organization for executives that provides meetings
for networking with other executives, information, and listings of executive-level
job openings. Opton saw his
own job disappear in the cloud of mergers and acquisitions. He had been vice
president of personnel at Sterling Drug
when Eastman Kodak took over in its ill-fated foray into pharmaceuticals.</P>
<P>While creating a database of potential
clients for a consulting business he was
planning to establish, Opton realized the
demand for helping other executives to
network. Opton says 60% of the members of his organization are currently employed,
but use their membership as an
insurance policy - a way to combat the
uncertainties of employment.</P>
<P>"The experience gave people a lot of
confidence they didn't have before it
happened," Upson says of the layoffs at
Sterling Winthrop. "And if it happens
again - 25% of the people downsized
have already changed jobs - they'll be
prepared. The tools that they acquired in
the first downsizing help in the next.
Those of us who have children have
probably benefited from the philosophical aspects: You tell them to build skills,
improve themselves, and be prepared for
their next job. Now they believe you."</P>
<P>Workers should rely on themselves
more, and not the company, says Upson."
Keep building your skills, keep them
current. Loyalty is a thing of the past.
Why be loyal to your company if your
company isn't loyal to you? Don't count
on that loyalty."</P>
<P>Over the years, says James D. Burke,
chairman of ACS's Committee on Economic &amp; Professional Affairs and Rohm
and Haas's manager for technical recruiting and university relations, there
were
layoffs followed by rehires for the ups
and downs of the economy. But in the
more recent restructuring, the lower
numbers are intended to be permanent.
There was rehiring in many companies,
but most companies want new types of
employees. "It's like playing cards,"
Burke explains. "You discard three and
pick up another three."</P>
<P>Many of those downsized are not getting the standard
full-time jobs they once
held, but want to stay in the profession.
Some 27,000 ACS members list themselves as consultants, Burke says, and
numbers are increasing. Employees laid
off in their 40s and 50s have a lot of expertise to offer in consulting services.
But, he warns, "consulting is more demanding than people recognize. They
need knowledge of processes and of
how to get things done. It's not clear that
many people have developed presentation skills and business skills."</P>
<P>Smaller companies are expected to
hire a greater percentage of chemists and
chemical engineers in the future. Lawrence J. Rosen, CEO of Pressure Chemical,
Pittsburgh, says downsizing of his
large customers has meant more business for his smaller company, and more
employment for chemical process operators. "We're trying to add people
as fast
as we can," says Rosen. But usually not
the people laid off from large companies."
We are getting lots of applications, but
there's a misfit. Companies aren't downsizing the people we need. They aren't
laying off the operators." Research
chemists, chemists in analytical labs, and
customer service personnel are rarely
suited to the jobs available at small chemical companies, he says.</P>
<P>"Chemists look at their jobs with less
complacency" than before, says Burke."
Job security has rapidly given way to skill
security. Those who have neglected their
skills or are relying on dated technologies
or products are at great risk. They must
evolve and not expect security from a degree or from past accomplishments. Employment
is changing and will never be
the same," says Burke. For some, "it's
more exciting than ever and they work
harder than ever to stay on top."
</P>
<A HREF="emp2.html"><center><img src="empbut.gif"></center></A><br><br><br><br>




