<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>CHAS Jan/Feb What to do when OSHA comes knocking</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1>Chemical Health &amp; Safety</H1>
<H2>January/February 1997</h2>
<H5>Chemical Health &amp; Safety, 1997, 4(1), 10-13. </H5>
<H5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1997 by the American Chemical Society.<hr
noshade></H5>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>CHAS 1-2/97  What to do when OHSA comes knocking</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<center><h1><big>What to 
do when <FONT COLOR=#0678B4>OSHA</FONT> 
comes knocking
</big></H1>
<a href="auth.html"><h3>By Anne Harding</h3></a>

<center><img src="osha.gif"></center>
<h2><font color="01A0C6"><i>An OSHA inspector and a 
CHO whose laboratory has been inspected share their 
experiences and advice
</i></font></H2></center>
<hr noshade>
<P>
Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations protect 100 million employees in the nation, while 6.5 million employers&#151;from small doctors' offices to huge corporations&#151;are required to comply with OSHA. The federal arm of OSHA inspected 24,024 employers in fiscal 1996, and state organizations inspected 57,199 places of employment.

<P>
You can't know for sure when your lab will be visited&#151;possibly never&#151;but you should be prepared. OSHA most often appears at the door in response to an employee complaint, as part of an enforcement program targeting industries prone to problems, or after an accident in which people were injured or killed. Sometimes another government agency inspecting a facility may suggest that OSHA take a look.

<P>
Because OSHA inspectors won't give you a warning, the best way to prepare for an inspection is to be in compliance. In the event that an inspector does come knocking, it helps to have a plan in place for how to manage the visit.

<P>
<h4><font color="8B4513">The Laboratory Standard</font></h4>
Laboratories of all sizes have a special requirement that governs how they deal with hazardous chemicals. The so-called Laboratory Standard (29 CFR 1910. 1450), which became effective in 1990 and fully enforceable in 1991, requires that employees be aware of the chemical hazards in their workplace and protected from excessive exposure to these chemicals. OSHA promulgated these regulations after almost a decade of discussing the differences between labs and other workplaces. Previously, all employers with laboratories that used chemicals defined as hazardous by the Federal Hazard Communication Standard (29 CFR 1910. 1200) had to comply with that standard, which people in laboratories found to be inappropriate and overly burdensome.

<P>
The four-page, 12-part Laboratory Standard, which covers the "laboratory use" of chemicals on a "laboratory scale," has relatively simple requirements: It limits permissible exposure limits (PELs) to chemicals specified in 29 CFR 1910, subpart Z, and requires labs to ensure that employee exposure is below those limits; it requires an employer to develop a Chemical Hygiene Plan (CHP) that's easily accessible to employees and covers eight specific areas; and it requires employees to be informed about and trained on the CHP. The standard also covers requirements for medical consultation and exams for employees exposed to hazardous levels of chemicals, proper labeling of hazardous chemicals and maintenance of MSDSs, the use of respirators, and record keeping.

<P>
On the federal level in fiscal year 1996, Laboratory Standard violations were cited 45 times in 25 inspections, for a total of $18,525 in initial penalties. Most of these citations were for problems with the CHP (1910.1450 (e)) and employee information and training (1910.1450 (f)). Although citations for PELs (1910.1450 (c)) were few, penalties were high. Employers cited included a clinic; hospitals; a paint manufacturer; several chemical and allied products, health services, testing, and research laboratories;  and a soap maker.

<P>
Although the Laboratory Standard isn't a big citation or penalty source nationwide, it can be a problem for particular industries. For example, 1910.1450 was the top source of citations (if not fines) for industries classified by the Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) codes as Research, Development, and Testing Services (8730), Commercial and Biological Research Facilities (8731), and Testing Laboratories (8734). 

<P>
Depending on the type of laboratory, other top problems include Access to Employee Exposure and Medical Records (1910.0020), General Materials Handling (1910.0176), Hazardous Waste Operations and Emergency Response (1910.0120), Flammable and Combustible Liquids (1910.0106), and Personal Protective Equipment, General Requirements (1910.0132). 

<P>
The Laboratory Standard requires a lab to define how it protects employees against hazardous chemicals, and if an employer's compliance with the standard is excellent, it's less likely that other problems will arise.

<p>
<hr>
<H2><center><font color="01A0C6"><i> 
If you're concerned about what a surprise inspection might 
uncover, invite OSHA for a consultative visit</i></font></center></h2>
<hr>
<P>
<h4><font color="8B4513">Diary of an OSHA inspection</font></h4>
Richard E. Fairfax, industrial hygienist at OSHA's Health Compliance Assistance Office, performed site inspections across the country for 15 years. "Most of our inspections in labs are associated with other inspections of facilities that happen to have a lab on site," he says. Fairfax described how a typical inspection works, although he notes that "every inspector probably does it a little differently." The general outline for an inspection is as follows. 

<P>
* &#009;&#009;The inspector arrives, asks to speak to the top management on the site, shows his or her credentials, and tells the employer the reason for the visit. If it is an employee complaint, a copy of the complaint is provided and the identity of the complainant is kept confidential.

<P>
* &#009;&#009;A standard opening conference is held, and the inspector will ask that an employee representative or union representative be present. In the conference, the inspector reviews employee and employer rights and responsibilities and talks about the scope of the inspection. 

<P>
* &#009;&#009;The inspector usually will begin by looking at paperwork: accident and injury records, written programs, and records of any sampling or monitoring (of air quality, for example). 

<P>
* &#009;&#009;Next is a walk-around of the facility. The employer has a right to accompany the inspector, who will look at processes, interview people, and verify training with employees. 

<P>
*  &#009;At the closeout conference, the inspector will announce any violations that have been found and give the employer suggestions on how to remedy these and any other problems. 

<P>
The decision as to whether a facility will be cited and fined is not made on site. The area director makes the final decision on whether to issue citations and levy fines. Citations are classified as "serious" or "other." A serious violation is anything that can cause death or a serious injury or illness&#151;for example, a piece of protruding equipment that could bruise someone who bumped against it would not be classed as a serious violation. Penalties for serious violations begin at $7000, but this fine can be adjusted on the basis of various considerations, including such factors as the size of the organization, demonstration of good faith, and absence of a history of OSHA violations. After adjustments are made, the average penalty assessed winds up being about $700 or $800.

<P>
OSHA's <I>Field Inspector's Reference Manual</I> offers a more detailed look at inspection procedures, gives information on how penalties are figured, and  describes post-inspection procedures, including how a settlement with OSHA is negotiated. The manual is available on OSHA's Web site at <a href="http://www.osha.gov"><b>(http://www.osha.gov)</b></a>, through a link to the agency's computerized information system (OCIS) arm in Salt Lake City.

<P>
<h4><font color="8B4513">What you can learn from OSHA</font></h4>
The <I>Field Inspector's Reference Manual</I> isn't the only helpful piece of information you can get from OSHA's Web site. Information on violations and fines can be searched by SIC code or standard number. You can also find the text of the Lab Standard and copies of letters of interpretation from OSHA on the standard on the Web.

<P>
If you're concerned about what a surprise visit from an inspector might turn up, you can always invite OSHA yourself. The agency offers free consultative services, geared to small to medium-sized employers with up to 250 workers, that can be tailored to your requirements&#151;with very few strings attached. If an employer asks for a consultative visit, it can be limited to a particular area. Inspectors will note any problems they see and will do basically anything requested&#151;conduct a training session for employees, review a CHP, and so on. No citations will be made. However, if the inspector does note any problems, the employer must make arrangements to correct them. If problems aren't addressed, the consultative service has the right to inform OSHA. 

<P>
Fairfax says the consultative service is extremely popular, with waiting lists in many states. At OSHA's Web site, you can find specific information on how the consultations work and who to call in your state to set one up.

<P>
"People should be much more relaxed about inviting OSHA to come in and give them the free, no-fines inspection service," says James A. Kaufman, president of James A. Kaufman &amp; Associates in Natick, MA. "You do earn the credit, the recognition for being proactive."

<P>
<h4><font color="8B4513">Up-front organization can impress</font></h4>
In demonstrating compliance to an inspector, "record keeping is really critical," says Tom Shelley, chemical hygiene officer (CHO) for Cornell University's Department of Environmental Health and Safety. At the university's main campus in Ithaca, NY, there are 5600 lab workers, 3800 lab rooms, and 1200 registered chemical fume hoods. Nearly half of the university's building space is devoted to labs. 

<P>
&#009;When Shelley came on board as CHO about two years ago, the CHP was adequate but in need of some revision. Faculty members were not as aware of the need for compliance as they are currently. Faculty and staff are now more attuned to regulatory requirements: Now there are one or more safety representatives in every university department, a written, university-wide health and safety policy approved by top management, and regular self-audits and self-inspections of labs in many departments.

<P>
In addition to revising the CHP, Shelley is helping to set up a central committee on laboratory and chemical safety. "You need to have 'buy-in' from faculty and staff on new and existing safety programs to facilitate compliance," he notes.

<p>
<hr>
<h2><center><B><I><FONT COLOR=#01A0C6>It's vital
to have a CHP that reflects 
the real world<br>--not an ideal one</FONT></I></B></center>
</H2>
<hr>
<P>
Last year, an OSHA inspector came to Cornell as part of an inspection of 20 colleges and universities in the region. The inspector spent an hour&#151;maybe less&#151;going over the university's CHP, training records, and respiratory protection policy. Apparently, the inspector thought this was evidence enough of Cornell's compliance with OSHA and did not feel it necessary to go further. "If your records are really comprehensive," Shelley says, "they may not even choose to go out on campus."

<P>
The key points of Cornell's protocol are that when OSHA arrives, Shelley and his director are called immediately to accompany the inspector on the rounds. "We would go with the OSHA inspector through the plant and document everything they did," says Shelley. Making sure that a knowledgeable person on the university staff is monitoring what an inspector notices and answering questions in an informed way can help avoid later misunderstandings.

<P>
<h4><font color="8B4513">Keeping in compliance</font></h4>
Shelley's role at Cornell demonstrates the importance of having a CHO to oversee compliance with the Lab Standard&#151;and of having top management demonstrate a commitment to compliance. OSHA requires that an employer covered by the Lab Standard have a CHO, and industry has recognized that such a person can be extremely helpful. In fact, the American Chemical Society is developing a certification program for CHOs. (See <a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/chas/97/janfeb/
surv.html"><b>Tell <i>CH&S</i></b></a>).

<P>
But compliance with the Lab Standard and a dedication to safety in general can't be just one person's responsibility&#151;no matter how skilled and persuasive he or she is, says Kaufman. "Inspecting your own labs isn't difficult to do. It's often left as the responsibility of a few people. But everyone in the lab should be involved in the inspection process, from lab workers to administrators. . . . It should be everyone looking out for each other."

<P>
Laboratory size may play a role in the economics of compliance, points out Lou DiBerardinis, an industrial hygiene officer in the Environmental Medical Department at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in Cambridge. Smaller colleges, universities, and research facilities may be falling through the cracks, he says, but financial constraints need not be a barrier if the commitment is there. "It's time-consuming, and it requires perhaps some change in people's habits and culture," he says. "There also has to be the emphasis from the right people&#151;upper management."

<P>
Finally, it's vital to have a CHP that reflects the real world&#151;not an ideal one. OSHA inspectors are not going to appreciate a plan that's perfect in its rigorousness; they want to see a plan that's followed. DiBerardinis advises, "Don't write something that you're not going to do. OSHA is going to enforce what you say your rules are."
<br><br>
<hr><br><br>
