<HEAD>
<TITLE>CHAS Reader Survey</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><H2>Chemical Health & Safety<br>
READER SURVEY</H2>
<H5>Copyright &#169; 1996 by the American Chemical Society.</H5></center>
<br>

<H3>How much do you know about safe laboratory hood practices?  Test your
knowledge and enter our drawing for a free ACS safety video. </H3></center>

<p>To enter the drawing, mark the correct response(s) to each question,
tell us about yourself, and send your entry to the <I>CH&S</I> editorial
office by Monday, April 15.  We'll report the results in an upcoming issue
and enter you in our drawing.  The winner will select one video from the new
ACS series of Laboratory Safety Video Courses.</p>

<p><B>Laboratory Chemical Hoods</B><br><br>

1.  How can you tell if your hood is working properly?
<blockquote>
A. By performing a smoke test
<br>
B. By keeping the sash at a preset position
<br>
C. By checking a properly functioning airflow monitor
<br>
D. By checking the test label
</blockquote>

2.  What could happen if your hood is not working properly or you are using it
incorrectly?
<blockquote>
A. Your reaction might be contaminated.
<br>
B.  You might be exposed to a toxic chemical without knowing it.
<br>
C. Nothing, as long as you are using it for only a short time.
<br>
D. You might damage the hood.
</blockquote>

3.  What should you do if you think your hood is not working properly?
<blockquote>
A. Lower the sash and continue working.
<br>
B. Raise the sash and continue working.
<br>
C. Stop work and ask your supervisor.
</blockquote>

4.  True or False: The higher the face velocity of the hood, the better it
will contain gases and vapors.
<blockquote>
TRUE      <br>
FALSE
</blockquote>

5.  Which of the following are incorrect practices for maintaining a properly
functioning laboratory chemical hood?
<blockquote>
A. Chemical containers sitting on the floor of the hood at the back
<br>
B. Reaction traps on experimental apparatus
<br>
C.  Paper towels laid neatly on the bottom of the hood to provide a clean
surface
<br>
D. A piece of equipment sitting on the base of the hood
</blockquote>

6.  When you place your apparatus in the hood, how far away from the sash
should it be?
<blockquote>
A. All reactions should be placed at the rear of the hood.
<br>
B. It doesn't matter.
<br>
C. At least 6 inches from the sash
<br>
D. At least 3 inches from the sash
</blockquote>

7.  Which of these situations is unsafe when working at a laboratory chemical
hood?
<blockquote>
A. The sash is opened above the chemist's nose.
<br>
B. The chemist is sticking his (or her) head into the hood while working.
<br>
C.  The chemist walks away from the reaction without closing the sash
completely.
<br>
D.  Another chemist walks in front of the hood while the first chemist is
working at it.
</blockquote>

8.  What should you do if your equipment is too large for the hood?
<blockquote>
A. Install a spot ventilation system or enclosure hood.
<br>
B. Ask your supervisor to install a larger hood.
<br>
C. Don't use equipment that's too large for the hood.
<br>
D.  If you expect harmful emissions, use an appropriate respirator.
</blockquote>

9.  What should you do if the power to your hood is interrupted?
<blockquote>
A.  Work as quickly as you can to finish up your experiment.
<br>
B. Raise the sash to dissipate vapor and gas buildup.
<br>
C. Stop the reaction if you can and lower the sash.
<br>
D.  Report the malfunction to the facilities office and continue work.
</blockquote>
<hr>
