<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What if you are defamed?</TITLE></HEAD>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<H1>CHEMTECH</H1>
<h2>January 1997</h2>
CHEMTECH <b>1997</b>, <i>27</i>(1), 47-49.<br><br>
<h5><hr noshade>Copyright &#169; 1996 by Phillip M. Perry.<br>
Published 1997 by the American Chemical Society.<hr noshade></h5>

<p><h3><center><i><font color="8B2252">What if you are defamed?</font></i>
</center></h3>
What should you do if your own business becomes the target of disparaging
remarks by a competitor? Let the matter go unaddressed, and your profits
may suffer as your competitor spreads false information about your
business practices. Do the wrong thing, and you may end up in a worse
situation.</P>

<p>"Resist the temptation to start a counter-campaign of rumors about your
competitor," says Jeff Kaplan, partner in the New York law firm of Arkin,
Schaffer & Kaplan, which has represented many defamed businesses. "Two wrongs
do not make a right in this business." The big risk here is that your campaign
will backfire and you will become the target of a lawsuit. Furthermore, you
may be mistaken about who is spreading the rumor. "It's often difficult to
determine the source of the defamation," says Kaplan. "Some businesses have
employed private investigators to either catch the defamer in the act, or
trace the rumor back to its source."</p>

<p>Getting solid evidence of the rumor's source is the biggest step. "Once you
have done that, you are most of the way there," says Kaplan. Your attorney's
first step is likely to send a letter to the competitor, citing violations of
the federal Lanham Act, says Paul Batista. "I point out what is inaccurate in
describing the client's business."</p>

<p>Businesses guilty of falsely representing competitors' services or products
are subject to what the courts call "compensatory damages," which is financial
compensation equal to the damages sustained by the target. What if you feel you
cannot accurately assess the damages you have sustained? Should you refrain
from serving a complaint on a company? Not at all, says Batista. The simple
act of serving a complaint can scare the competitor enough to halt the rumors
and may even result in an out-of-court financial settlement.</p>

<p>State laws protect your business against defamation. So does the federal
Lanham Act, as amended in 1988. "Congress has made a gift to you in the form
of the Lanham Act," says Batista. "If you can say a competitor is making
misleading statements--we can get into federal court. We can make the other
side stop it. That's a real sea change from the laws of the past."</p>

<br><br>

<h3><a href="http://pubs.acs.org/hotartcl/chemtech/97/jan/bad.html">Return to
article</a></h3>


</BODY>
