<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>

The Ireland Funds - The American Ireland Fund FAQ

</TITLE>

<META name="resource-type" content="document">
<META name="description" content="The Ireland-Funds are a non-profit, non-sectarian
organisation sponsoring projects of Peace, Culture and Charity in Ireland North and South. -
FAQ">
<META name="keywords" content="Irish, Ireland, Irish-American, American, fund, peace,
culture, charity, links, 
<META name="distribution" name="local">

</HEAD> <BODY
BACKGROUND="../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff0000">


<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3><I><STRONG>

The American Ireland Fund FAQ

</STRONG></I></FONT></CENTER>
<BR>



<A HREF="../welcome.html"><IMG WIDTH="70" HEIGHT="61" SRC="../gfx/logo4.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT"
BORDER="0"></A>

<A NAME="top">

<A HREF="../welcome.html"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41" SRC="../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A>

<IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41" SRC="../gfx/higryfw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE">

<BR>
<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR> 


<A HREF="#what">What does The American Ireland Fund do with 
the money it raises?</A><BR>

<A HREF="#how">How does The Fund raise money for peace, 
culture, and charity?</A><BR>

<A HREF="#when">How and when did the AIF get started?</A><BR>

<A HREF="#how much">How much money has The Fund directed to Ireland 
to date?</A><BR>

<A HREF="#difference">How do grants from The American Ireland Fund 
make a difference in Ireland?</A><BR>

<A HREF="#contribution">How can I help The American Ireland Fund - and 
what will my contribution bring?</A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR> 

<H3 ALIGN=left><A NAME="what">What does The American Ireland Fund do with 
the money it raises?</A></H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>The American Ireland Fund (AIF) seeks to fulfill a 
profound pledge made to the people of Ireland, North and South: that 
its support of Ireland-based programs will advance the causes of peace, 
culture, and charity. With $80 million already raised, AIF is the 
nation's largest private-sector foundation dedicated to helping the 
people of Ireland help themselves.
</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>Through grants from a few thousand dollars to $50,000, 
The American Ireland Fund supports hundreds of projects in every county 
of Ireland each year. For many projects, a seed grant from The Fund 
provides the leverage necessary to qualify for additional monies from 
government agencies and other organizations.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>The conflict in Northern Ireland and the need for peace 
and reconciliation in Ireland, North and South, attract a large measure 
of The American Ireland Fund's support. But its work goes much further 
to meet the challenges of building a new Ireland with competence and 
determination. American Ireland Fund grants attach widespread, endemic 
unemployment. They search out the root causes of inner-city deprivation 
and rural depopulation. The enhancement of Ireland's unparalleled cultural 
heritage is also a key element of the AIF.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="how">How does The Fund raise money for peace, culture,
and charity?</H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>The American Ireland Fund relies on the generosity of
thousands of Americans of Irish background as well as their friends
and business colleagues.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>In more than a dozen U.S. cities, American Ireland Fund
events range from elegant black-tie dinners to relaxing golf 
tournaments. Fund supporters are invited to attend special benefit 
performances by the very best in Irish theater and music. Contributions
of any size may also be made directly to The American Ireland Fund.
All gifts are tax-deductible to the full extent of the law.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>The American Ireland Fund is assisted by the Irish
Advisory Committee, based in Dublin. Qualified volunteers from all 
segments of Irish society assess grant applications and prepare them
for review by The Fund's Board of Directors. To ensure contributions
are used properly and that donors' intentions have been honored, the 
Irish Advisory Committee reviews the progress of all projects to 
which grants have been made.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>The Fund's efforts have already forged strong and
lasting links between Americans and the Irish people. Our achievements
are possible only through the generosity and concern of our thousands
of supporters.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>

<HR>

<H3><A NAME="when">How and when did the AIF get started?</A></H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>The American Ireland Fund traces its roots to 1963 
when President John F. Kennedy made his historic visit to Ireland and, 
with President of Ireland Eamon de Valera, helped found the American 
Irish Foundation. A group of business leaders including Anthony
J.F. O'Reilly, now Heinz Company Chairman, President, and CEO, and 
Daniel Rooney, President of the NFL's Pittsburgh Steelers, organized 
The Ireland Fund in 1976.</P

<P ALIGN=justify>The Ireland Fund and the American Irish Foundation, like
The American Ireland Fund today, were nonpolitical and nonsectarian and 
committed to raising funds in the United States for support of worthy 
causes in Ireland, North and South. In 1987, at a Washington, D.C., 
ceremony attended by President Reagan the two foundations merged 
to become the American Ireland Fund.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>Today, partner Ireland Funds in Australia, Canada, 
Great Britain, France, Germany, New Zealand, Japan and South 
Africa make up a Confederation of Concern that helps unite
the more than 70 million people of Irish ancestry worldwide.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="how much">How much money has The Fund directed to Ireland 
to date?</H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>In the last six years, The American Ireland Fund
and its affiliated Funds have raised more than $27 million. In the same
period, grants of more than $19 million have been made to projects in
the areas of community development, education, reconciliation, and 
culture. The American Ireland Fund's General Endowment Fund exceeds
$6 million.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="difference">How do grants from The American Ireland Fund 
make a difference in Ireland?</H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>In every sense, The American Ireland Fund is
entrepreneurial and willing to take risks when the potential for human
dividends is high. It is often the first group to show a project in
Ireland that someone else believes in what their people can do and is
willing to stake something on that. In many cases, American Ireland Fund
grants come long before other foundations and government agencies are
willing to commit their money.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>Among the most successful grants were those made in 
the early 1980s to Derry's Inner City Trust and the North-West Centre
for Learning and Development. Anyone who has visited Derry recently
can't help but notice the changes that have taken place. Ruins have 
become restaurants, bombed-out buildings are libraries and shops.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>In North Belfast, The Fund has assisted the Flax Trust
in rebuilding an abandoned linen mill into a bustling small business
center that attracts ambitious, hardworking men and women from the 
city's Catholic and Protestant communities. In Dublin, The Fund has
helped revive a once-dying cultural landmark, Marsh's Library, the 
city's oldest library. In Limerick, the city's historic center now 
welcomes residents and visitors with attractive shops and museums,
thanks to a $50,000 flagship grant.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>Taking risks for the cause of peace and reconciliation,
The American Ireland Fund began its support of integration when the first
such school, Lagan College (the equivalent of an American high school)
opened in 1981 with just 30 pupils. Lagan now has an enrollment exceeding
700. It is one of 20 integrated schools in Northern Ireland teaching peace
along with math, science, and literature.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="contribution">How can I help The American Ireland Fund - 
and what will my contribution bring?</H3>

<P ALIGN=justify>Our thousands of supporters contribute in myriad ways,
from attending fund-raising events, to making donations by mail, to 
visiting projects in Ireland to witness results firsthand. A gift of any
size has a significant impact.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>Supporting The American Ireland Fund also puts you in
contact with thousands of other Americans who are inspired by a love of
Ireland. On the AIF Board of Directors are many of the nation's corporate
leaders.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>We have already raised $80 million, but the need remains,
as President of Ireland Mary Robinson has testified.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>"Many of you in your involvement with The Ireland Funds
will know that there is a quiet, friendly revolution going on. The hands
of friendship are being extended all around the place," President
Robinson has said.</P>

<P ALIGN=justify>"So I'll make a pact with The Ireland Funds," she 
continued. "I'll go on witnessing, if you go on doing the hard work
of making it happen, by raising the funds all over the world, and
knowing that the President of Ireland is a witness to what you're doing
and is very proud of you."</P>

<A HREF="#top">Return to top of Page</A>




</BODY>
