<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"><BR>

<H2>Strokestown Famine Museum</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<H3>
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="325" HEIGHT="210" SRC="famine1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
<FONT SIZE=+3>R</FONT>egarded by historians as the single worst catastrophe of the 19th century, the
Irish Famine now has its own museum in Co. Roscommon. Opened by Irish President Mary
Robinson in 1994, the Strokestown Famine Museum tells the story of the Famine, and life in 19th century Ireland.
Over 50,000 people have now visited the Museum to learn about the historical aspects of this 
important chapter of the Irish experience.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
This year is the 150th anniversary of the Famine and currently, the Ireland Funds are helping 
Strokestown and the National Library of Ireland undertake the proper cataloguing of all
materials relating to the Strokestown Estate (approx. 50,000 items) dating from the 1840's
in order to preserve the materials for study by students and scholars.

</H3>

<A HREF="famine2.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="famine2s.gif" BORDER=0></A>


</B>
<CENTER>
Photos courtesy of Derek Szabo

<IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>  A <B><A
HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. 
</BODY>
