<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>ULYSSES - The Ireland Funds - Connections</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/higryfw4.gif" ALT="Can't go forward" ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>


<H2>U.S. President Clinton Visits Derry</H2>

NORTHERN IRELAND
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="221" HEIGHT="250" SRC="clinton.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" VSPACE=5 HSPACE=5>
Derry on Thursday, November 30th will long live in the minds of us who were
privileged to be there. It was the day that President Bill Clinton came saw and
conquered the people of Northern Ireland before moving to Dublin to repeat the
exercise the following day. But Derry was special, really special and never in
its history can this wonderful vibrant town have experienced anything quite like it.
That the President of the greatest nation on earth should be in Derry to inaugurate an
American Ireland Fund project was indeed an extraordinary tribute to the work of
the Fund and the effect that the Fund has had over the last 20 years in this city. It
was also a great tribute to the former Speaker of the House Thomas "Tip" O'Neill and
the O'Neill family, 25 of whom made the journey to Derry for the event.
<P>
In words, it is hard to put across the sheer excitement, sense of pride and
emotion of the day. It was nearly surreal - the most powerful man in the world coming to a
small Irish town so renowned for conflict and violence, for burned out cars and
buses, for fights and funerals. But what a day of unbridled joy November 30th turned out
to be! From early in the morning the people of Derry streamed into the Guildhall
square. The climatic Gods were with us. Though cold, the skies were blue and
there was brilliant winter sunshine. By three o'clock in the afternoon the atmosphere
in the packed Guildhall Square was electric. Suddenly the President and Hilliary were
there, on the podium, and the crowd went wild. They could hardly believe their eyes.
This Square, site of so much protest in the past, reverberated to the rooftops with
the sounds of a genuine and an emotional welcome to a President who clearly wanted to
be there. It really sent a shiver down ones back. The President chose his words
carefully. He paid tribute to the historic role of Derry as the departure port of
so many emigrants to America and to the welcome Derry gave to U.S. troops stationed
there in 2nd World War. The President paid tribute to John Hume and made a
special reference to Paddy Doherty and the Inner City Trust with whom the AIF has been
involved so much over the years. He appealed for all party talks and he clearly
told the men of violence that their days were over. As he succinctly put it "Peace
means Peace".
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
And then it was into the Guildhall for the American Ireland Fund event. The main
event was preceded by a private reception with the President and Mrs. Clinton for
the O'Neill family and friends and Directors of the American Ireland Fund the
highlight of which was the presentation by nine year old Tom O'Neill of his grandfather,
Speaker Tip O'Neill's golf putter to the President. In the main Guildhall the
ceremony was simple and emotional. With great style and pride the President of
the American Ireland Fund, Loretta Brennan Glucksman spoke eloquently of the AIF's
involvement with Derry over the last 20 years. Tom O'Neill, the late Speaker's
son and a Director of the American Ireland Fund made a superb address in which he
invoked the memory of his late father, and his passion and concern for a part of
the world he had grown to love.
<P>
And then it was the President. His words were simple, heartfelt and poignant. He
paid special tribute to the work of the Fund and particularly Speaker O'Neill. He
referred to him as a man of the people, a bricklayer's son who became the most
powerful man in Congress and the nation's most prominent loyal champion of
working people in the United States. The President continued, "Speaker O'Neill loved
politics because he knew it could make a difference in people's lives. And he loved people
most of all - his neighbors, his constituents, his close colleagues and his
friends both back home and in Ireland. He was a good friend of the cause of peace in Northern
Ireland. He was among the first Irish American political leaders to oppose
violence in Northern Ireland. Though sorely missed he will be long remembered and the O'Neill
Chair in Peace Studies at the University of Ulster sponsored by the American
Ireland Fund will be a fitting tribute to his long life and legacy. For Tip O'Neill knew
that peace must be nurtured by a deeper understanding among people and greater
economic opportunity for all. Of all the voices I've heard along this trip, the most
inspiring were those of the two children I met this morning at the Mackie Plant in Belfast,
and -all those children, including some from Derry, who wrote to me in recent weeks
about aspirations for peace in heartfelt terms. I know they don't want to go back to
the way things used to be. They want a better future. They deserve it. And I know you, in
the American Ireland Fund, can make it happen. When I return to Washington, I
will be thinking of this wonderful city as all of us work to keep the momentous of
this eventful week moving forward."
<P>
And then they were gone, whisked backed to Belfast and we all trooped off to a
pub and a party that Paddy Doherty had arranged so we could reminisce and ruminate
about a truly great day. I, for one, look forward to the time when I can bounce
my grandchildren on my knee and tell them of the day President William Jefferson
Clinton went to Derry for the American Ireland Fund.


</B>
<P>
