<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0">

<A HREF="page1.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46"
HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page3.htm"><IMG
WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward"
BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT"> <HR SIZE="4"> <B> <P>


<H2>The Northern Ireland Initiative</H2>
<CENTER>
Peace - Culture - Charity - Community
Development - Education - Enterprise - Women - Youth
</CENTER>
A SPECIAL MESSAGE FROM MAURICE HAYES, CHAIRMAN, IRELAND FUNDS ADVISORY COMMITTEE

<P>
<IMG WIDTH="92" HEIGHT="118" SRC="graphics/p2a.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" VSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT">
For the American Ireland Fund and its partner Ireland Funds around the world, the
current cessation of violence in
Northern Ireland presents both a challenge and an opportunity, writes Dr. Maurice
Hayes, Chairman of the Ireland Funds Advisory Committee.<BR>
More than ever, it is important that the Ireland Funds now support the efforts of
those on both sides in
Northern Ireland who are trying to stabilize the situation and who are working to keep
lines of communication open between the two communities.<BR>
In Belfast recently, a special meeting of the Ireland Funds Advisory Committee
examined how the Funds can continue to
make a difference in Northern Ireland. Our group heard submissions from various key
figures in Northern Ireland, including past recipients of American Ireland Fund
grants.
Together, we strove to identify those projects and individuals where grants played a
crucial role in bringing peace.<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
These areas include:
<UL>
<LI>Initiatives in "interface areas" of Northern Ireland where people from both
communities work to bridge the
sectarian divide;<BR>
<LI>Explorations of cultural diversity in Northern Ireland and on a North/South
basis;<BR>
<LI>Human and social rights and<BR>
<LI>Projects especially for women and young people.<BR>
</UL>
<P>
Accordingly, the Advisory Committee has forged an exciting "Northern Ireland
Initiative" that focuses on Belfast, Armagh, Mid-Ulster, and Derry as
critical areas. Projects nominated will receive grants totaling over $500,000. I
firmly
believe the work of the American Ireland Fund can continue to do much to maintain the
momentum of the peace process. As we approach a summer of peace and hope, I urge you
to
renew your connection with this vital work.
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>
 
<A HREF="graphics/p2b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="65" HEIGHT="62" SRC="graphics/p2b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> "Peace doesn't flow easily. It cannot be
bought. It must be built. I believe that the Ireland Funds are contributing to that
process." -Jackie Redpath, Shankill Development
Agency, Belfast.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<P> 
<A HREF="graphics/p2d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="81" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p2d-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> "When people get support in their
communities, they can help themselves." -Joyce McCartan, Women's Information Drop-In
Centre, Belfast.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<H2>$3.2 million in grants. How do we do it?</H2>

Fundamental social and political change has deeply affected all of Ireland in the last
twelve months.<BR>
Thanks to you, this remarkable transformation has received substantial assistance from
the American Ireland
Fund.<BR>
<IMG WIDTH="100" HEIGHT="122" SRC="graphics/p2c.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" VSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">
At fundraising events across the U.S.-and around the world-I have witnessed a
tremendous commitment by people of all backgrounds to supporting projects that promote
economic renewal and community reconciliation.<BR>
American Ireland Fund grants give hope and confidence in the future for Irish people.
The bottom line is that fundraising
events make this work possible. Here in the United States, the AIF was delighted to be
a major sponsor of the White House Conference on Trade and Investment in Ireland held
in Washington in May. We in the AIF are conscious of how critical job creation is in
cementing a lasting peace.<BR>
In this special edition of "Connections," we bring you the news from an exciting
calendar of nearly two dozen highly successful fundraising events
held in the first half of 1995.<BR>
Last year, the AIF distributed $3.2 million in grants to more than 100 projects. From
1988 to 1994, AIF grants to hundreds of Irish
organizations totaled over $22 million.<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
I plan to visit with a number of AIF grant recipients throughout the summer and I look
forward to reporting to you what I find in
the next issue of "Connections."<BR>
Have a wonderful summer.
<P>
-Kingsley Aikins,<BR>
Executive Director


</B> <P> <CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR> A <B><A
HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. </BODY> </HTML>
