<H2>Wholeys honored for "Outstanding Contributions"</H2>

PITTSBURGH
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="167" HEIGHT="254" SRC="graphics/p4b.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT">
On March 25, supporters gathered for the city's eleventh annual AIF dinner. Robert and
Lois Wholey received the 1995 Chairman's Award for Outstanding Contributions-the first
such award ever to be bestowed on a couple. For Pittsburghers today, the Wholey name
is
synonymous with fine seafood and generous philanthropy. Through the years, Bob and
Lois
have given many hours and contributed most generously to the American Ireland Fund
where Bob serves on the Board of Directors.
The evening's special guest was actor and humanitarian Paul Newman who founded
Ireland's Barretstown Gang Camp for children with serious illnesses. (<A
HREF="page1.htm">see page 1</A>) AIF Chairman Tony O'Reilly presented Newman, who is
also a professional
racing driver, with a Waterford Crystal car as screen colleague Melanie Griffith and
others cheered him on.
Over the last ten years, American Ireland Fund events held in Pittsburgh have netted
more than $3 million to support innovative and progressive programs throughout
Ireland,
North and South. Pittsburgh businessmen Tony O'Reilly and Dan Rooney organized the
first such fundraising dinner in 1976.
"As a member of the American Ireland Fund from the beginning, I am proud to have
witnessed fundamental changes in the living conditions for Irish people," Rooney, AIF
Vice Chairman and President of the Pittsburgh Steelers, said.


<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="68" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4a-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>Paul Newman with fellow race car
driver Chip Ganassi. AIF's John O'Sullivan (center) looks on.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="69" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Melanie Griffith.

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="43" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4d-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Chryss O'Reilly is a major force for
Pittsburgh's success.



<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="62" SRC="graphics/grant.gif" ALIGN="LEFT"> CORRYMEELA YOUTH
RECONCILIATION.<BR>
One of Northern Ireland's oldest and most respected reconciliation groups, Corrymeela
has created leadership development programs for young people.<BR>
AIF grant: $6,000.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
</B>
