<H2>"Red Fay" is honored with Distinguished Leadership Award</H2>

SAN FRANCISCO
<P>
In 1946, Navy mates Paul Burgess "Red" Fay, Jr., and John F. Kennedy returned from war
duty and shared a room in Boston where Fay helped his friend win a seat in Congress.
Years later, Fay served as Under Secretary of the Navy in JFK's Administration and
after the President's death wrote "The Pleasure of His Company" about their
friendship.
On March 10, "Red" Fay received the 1995 AIF Distinguished Leadership Award from a
hometown San Francisco crowd led by Eamonn Keegan, AIF President West Coast Region.
"Red Fay is an original," noted Peter Folger, the event's General Chairman. "Above all
else, his friendship, his willingness to always lend a helping hand and his strong
sense of loyalty set him apart."
Also that evening, several special friends of Ireland in San Francisco established
"Endowed Funds" with their gifts of $25,000 or more. The American Ireland Fund is
grateful to the Jon K. Folan Family Trust; Eamonn and Louise Keegan; the Odell
Foundation; Thomas and 
Erma Jean Tracy; and Alfred and Dede Wilsey for their generosity.

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p5a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="88" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5a-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>A proud moment for the Tracys.<BR>
(from left): Cynthia, Tom and Erma Jean. An AIF Endowed Fund in their name was
announced. Over 25 AIF supporters have Endowment Funds in their name.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p5b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="69" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>San Francisco honoree.<BR>
Paul "Red" Fay (left) receives congratulations from Eamonn Keegan, AIF West Coast
Region President. In foreground, the Distinguished Leadership Award Waterford Crystal
Bowl.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">




<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>

<H2>Fabulous Femmes of Philanthropy</H2>

PALM BEACH
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="211" HEIGHT="176" SRC="graphics/p5d.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" HSPACE="10">
At the Breakers, Tina Harvey Flaherty, Felice Mark Lippert, and Chryss Goulandris
O'Reilly, were event co-chairs for a very special AIF evening honoring Carolyn Buckley
Dreyfoos, Gay Hart Gaines, Elesabeth Ingalls Gillet, and Rosemarie Stack, the Fabulous
Femmes of Philanthropy.
The AIF dinner and several related events attracted what Palm Beach Today called, "a
small army of noteworthy guests." On that list were former Presidential Chief of Staff
John Sununu and his wife, Nancy Sununu, as well as Eileen and Joseph Cornacchia,
owners
of two Kentucky Derby winners. Joining them were brothers Tim and Pat Rooney and
Eileen
and Brian Burns.

<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p5c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="47" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>In Palm Beach.<BR>
Majorie and Sam Meek.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
</B>
