<H2>St. Patrick's Day Celebration for Ireland's Children</H2>

BOSTON
<P>
For over 15 years, "Ireland's Children" has helped hundreds of children in Northern
Ireland who live in the shadow of violence by placing them in recreation and
reconciliation programs in their own communities.
On St. Patrick's Day 1995 in Boston, Jack Connors and AIF Treasurer Peter Lynch were
honorary co-chairs for an evening benefiting Meanscoil Feirste, Northern Ireland's
only
Irish language high school, and the Black Mountain Group, a Shankill Community
Development Organization.
In attendance were many youthful supporters of the AIF like Tim Corcoran, who carries
on the family's longstanding tradition of support for Peace, Culture and Charity in
Ireland established by his father Leo and his uncles Joe and John. Lawyer Corcoran is
proud to support not only the AIF's black tie galas but also less formal fundraisers
such as Boston's annual St. Patrick's Day party to benefit Ireland's Children, a
special AIF committee.
"I can't think of a better thing to do on St. Patrick's Day than lend my personal
support to a better future for all of Ireland's people, especially the children,"
Corcoran says.

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p6a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p6a-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>Building peace.<BR>
In Boston, Jackie Redpath (left) from Belfast was  happy to see Kingsley Aikins, AIF 
Executive Director, and Jack Connors, AIF National Board Member.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">


<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>

<H2>A night for a "Circle of Friends"</H2>

LOS ANGELES
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH="351" HEIGHT="171" SRC="graphics/p6b.gif" HSPACE="10">
</CENTER>
The reviews were enthusiastic for a "filum" premiere at Jimmy's Restaurant to benefit
the AIF. On the screen and in the audience were Minnie Driver and Chris O'Donnell, who
co-starred in "Circle of Friends," based on the novel by Maeve Binchy who also
attended.
Like the AIF, "Circle of Friends" brought America and Ireland closer together. From
America, there was Frank Price, who serves on the AIF's Board and is the film's
producer, and from Ireland, director 
Pat O'Connor. Also there to applaud Peace, Culture and Charity were Michael and
Gretchen Wayne.







<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p6c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p6c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>Good show and good showing (from left):
Gordon Snell; Jimmy and Anne Murphy; Maeve
Binchy; Michael and Gretchen Wayne.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p6d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="76" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p6d-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Director Pat O'Connor with Mary
Elizabeth
Mastroantonio.

