<P>


<H2>O'Reilly and Rooney honored for "Vision"; Neil Jordan wins Performing Arts
Award</H2>

<IMG WIDTH="214" HEIGHT="185" SRC="graphics/p7d.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">
A record attendance of more than 1,300 American Ireland Fund members and friends
celebrated the Fund's twentieth annual New York Dinner on May 11 at Tavern on the
Green.  Honorees at the gala event were Tony O'Reilly and Dan Rooney, the co-founders
of the Ireland Fund, who were feted for their daring and vision in 1976 and for their
unstinting service, support and encouragement in the ensuing years.<BR>
"Despite years of violence and death in Northern Ireland, we believed then that
individuals could help to build peace, brick by brick, day by day," AIF Chairman Tony
O'Reilly recalled. "Now, 20 years later, we have peace in all of Ireland for the first
time in a generation. But this is only a beginning."<BR>
As Dinner Co-Chairs Donald Patrick Brennan, Lewis L. Glucksman, Donald R. Keough,
Albert Lippert, Dean R. O'Hare, Michael J. Roarty and Daniel P. Tully pointed out in
their message, "It's no coincidence that, in troubled times, the Ireland Fund emerged.
The success we celebrate today originated when those two courageous men showed
extraordinary vision."
<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<IMG WIDTH="272" HEIGHT="192" SRC="graphics/p7a.gif" HSPACE="10" VSPACE="10"
ALIGN="LEFT"> Added Junior Co-Chair Claire Cronin, "My hope is that their leadership
will be our
inspiration, their unwavering commitment our example...It is our intention to pay Dan
and Tony the highest form of flattery-
imitation-and build upon the solid foundation that is the American Ireland Fund."<BR>
The Central Park event was also occasion for presentation by Gregory Peck of the
annual
Award for the Performing Arts to Neil Jordan, Oscar-winning screenwriter and film
director who scored the 1992 hit, "The Crying Game" and the 1994 hit "Interview With a
Vampire". Sligo-born Jordan is also author of an acclaimed short stories collection,
"Nights in Tunisia" (1978) and two novels, "The Past" (1980) and "Dream of a Beast"
(1983).<BR>
Jordan was honored for his extraordinary talent, artistry and achievement in world
cinema with a 
specially commissioned Waterford Crystal bowl. In addition, the AIF will make a
$10,000
grant in his name to the University College Dublin Film School.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">







<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p7b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="88" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p7b-sml.gif"
