<H2>A first Arizona gala</H2>

PHOENIX
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="279" HEIGHT="219" SRC="graphics/p8a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT">

For the premiere event benefiting the American Ireland Fund in the Southwest, Dinner
Chairman James P. Cunningham declared his hope that, "We are inaugurating not only an
activity for the evening but also a movement which hopefully takes root in Arizona and
has the effect of uniting Arizona's Irish."
Two awards highlighted the evening's activities. Fr. William McNamara, founder of
Spiritual Life Institute, a monastic community devoted to Christian humanism, received
the AIF Humanitarian Award. Fr. McNamara is currently establishing a second such
community in Co. Sligo.  Tony Award-winning actor, Charles Durning, received a special
AIF award for his acting.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">

<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>
<H2>Mercedes McCambridge stars at AIF benefit</H2>

SAN DIEGO
<P>
One of the world's most talented and admired actresses, Mercedes McCambridge, received
the AIF Heritage Award in San Diego on February 25.
Born on St. Patrick's Day, McCambridge moved from radio drama to the silver screen in
1950 and won an Oscar that year for her portrayal of feisty reporter Sadie Burke in
"All the King's Men," her first movie role. In 1964, she starred on Broadway in "Who's
Afraid of Virginia Woolf" and in 1991, she came out of retirement to star in "Lost in
Yonkers."
Another highlight for the San Diego gala was creation of the "Irish 50," a select
group
of individual contributors. Dinner co-chairs were Mike Neil and Leo Sullivan.
Ruth and Joe McInerney turned out for the celebration. So did Mary and Dan Mulvihill,
a
former dinner 
chairman, as well as Maureen O'Connor Peterson and Joan Kroc.





<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p8b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p8b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>In San Diego, Marianne McDonald presents
Mercedes McCambridge with AIF Heritage Award.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p8c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="77" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p8c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Joan Kroc of McDonald's fame with
Mercedes
McCambridge.


