<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 13)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page12.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/higryfw4.gif" ALT="Can't go forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>AIF grant brings tiny Cootehill alive with art, music in 
a summer festival</H2>

"The idea," Kay Phelan says, "is to introduce to people living in a rural area
events and arts which they wouldn't normally see. We bring those things here 
for them."<BR>
<IMG WIDTH="205" HEIGHT="336" SRC="graphics/p13a.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="10">
One way rural areas in Ireland choose to confront the challenges of de-population
and long-term economic decline is by developing significant local arts
initiatives.<BR>
The Cootehill Community Arts Festival, begun in 1988, brings theater, music and
literary readings to an isolated Cavan community. Last year, the project received
a $7,500 AIF grant.<BR>
Past festival programs have included an art workshop; a busking competition; a
performance of "Romeo and Juliet"; and a poetry reading by John Montague and
Nuala Ni Dhomhnaill, 1992 AIF Literary Award winner.<BR>
In addition, the festival joined with the Tyrone Guthrie Centre, located not far
from Cootehill, to present classic music recitals. For Irish and international
artists, composers and writers, the Guthrie Centre in Annaghmakerrig, Co.
Monaghan, is an isolated retreat. The Guthrie Centre is considered one of
Ireland's premier cultural treasures and has received more 
than $70,000 in AIF grants, including a 1989 $50,000 flagship grant.
"We availed of the natural talent that is at the Guthrie Centre," Phelan
explains. "We want [the festival] to give people a little bit of what they know
and to encourage new and innovative artists."
<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<P> 
<A HREF="graphics/p13b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="82" HEIGHT="62" SRC="graphics/p13b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Cootehill prepares. The local art
festival
runs August 10-20
<BR CLEAR="LEFT"> <P>
Certainly for any creative endeavor, work becomes especially worthwhile when
artists have the opportunity to come in direct contact with a community.
The 1995 Cootehill Arts Festival, scheduled for August 10-20, will feature
another classical music recital at Annaghmakerrig House as well as art
exhibitions, drama and literary workshops and street theatre.
<P>
In rural Co. Cavan, the quiet village of Cootehill "tends to get left out of
things," admits Kay Phelan. So she and other residents organized a summertime
Community Arts Festival, supported by an AIF grant.
<P>
A classic. 
Music recitals at the Tyrone Guthrie Centre are a Cootehill Arts Festival
highlight.

Cootehill prepares.
The local art festival runs August 10-20.







<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="62" SRC="graphics/grant.gif" ALIGN="LEFT"> HOLYWELL TRUST.<BR>
Developing cross-community education programs and leadership training sessions
for young people in Derry.<BR>
AIF grant: $10,000.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
</B>
