<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page
2)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0">

<A HREF="page1.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"></A><A
HREF="page3.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT"> <HR SIZE="4"> 
<B> 
<P>

<CENTER>
<H2>Clinton: Children of Northern Ireland Want a Better Future.</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>

Thursday, November 30, will long live in the minds of those who were privileged
to be in Derry, writes Kingsley Aikins.
<P>
On that day, President Bill Clinton won the hearts of the people of Northern
Ireland, before moving to Dublin the following day to repeat the exercise.
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="221" HEIGHT="250" SRC="graphics/p2a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=15 VSPACE=10>
Never in Derry's history can that wonderful, vibrant town have experienced
anything quite like it. That the President of the United States should be there
to inaugurate an American Ireland Fund project-the Thomas P. "Tip" O'Neill Chair
in Peace Studies at the University of Ulster-was an extraordinary tribute to the
work of the Fund and the effect the
Fund has had in Derry over the last 20 years. It was also a great tribute to the
former Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives and the entire O'Neill
family, 25 of whom made the journey to Derry for the event.
<P>
From early in the morning, the people of Derry streamed into the Guildhall
Square. Though it was cold, the sky was blue and there was brilliant winter
sunshine. By three in the afternoon, the atmosphere was electric.

<P>
Suddenly, President and Mrs. Clinton arrived, and the square reverberated with an
emotional welcome. The President chose his words carefully. He paid tribute to
the historic role of Derry as a departure port of so many emigrants to America,
and to the welcome Derry gave U.S. troops stationed there during World War II.
President Clinton also paid tribute to Derry's own John Hume, and made a special
reference to Paddy Doherty and the Inner City Trust with whom the AIF has been so
closely involved over the years. He clearly told the men of violence that their
days were over. As he succinctly put it, "Peace means peace."
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
At the University of Ulster in Derry, Northern Ireland, U.S. President Bill
Clinton and American Ireland Fund President Loretta Brennan Glucksman
unveil a stone from the Capitol Building in Washington, D.C. which former Speaker
Thomas Foley presented to the AIF. The stone will be displayed in the university
that houses the Thomas P. "Tip" O'Neill Visiting Chair in Peace Studies.
<P>
Then, it was into the Guildhall for the American Ireland Fund event. At a private
reception with President and Mrs. Clinton, nine-year-old Tom O'Neill IV presented
his grandfather's prized golf putter to President Clinton as the O'Neill family
and Directors and friends of the American
Ireland Fund looked on. President Clinton had a special word with AIF Regional
Director, Tom Kennedy of New York who accompanied President Kennedy to Ireland on
his famous trip in 1963.
<P>
In the main Guildhall, the ceremony was simple but emotional. With great style
and pride, Loretta Brennan Glucksman, AIF National President, spoke eloquently of
the Fund's involvement with Derry over the last 20 years. AIF Board Member Tom
O'Neill, III, invoked the memory of his late father, and his passion and concern
for a part of the world he had grown to love.
<P>

<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p2b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p2b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
Among the Congressmen to travel with President Clinton to Ireland were: (left to
right) Bart Stupak (D) Michigan, Victor Frazer (I) Virgin Islands Delegate,
James P. Moran (D) Virginia, Jerry F. Costello (D) Illinols, Robert A. Borski (D)
Pennsylvania, President and Mrs. Clinton, Michael R. McNulty (D) New York,
Peter T. King (R) New York, Maurice D. Hinchey (D) New York, and Thomas J. Manton
(D) New York
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p2c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p2c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Tom O'Neill pays tribute to his father Thomas P. "Tip" O'Neill's contribution to
the peace process and his love of Ireland and its people.

<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>
