ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>

<CENTER>
<H2>Reconciliation & Community:</H2>

<H3>A Conference On The Future Of Northern Ireland</H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="213" HEIGHT="220" SRC="graphics/p4a.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
<BR>
BELFAST - Even as the Ireland Funds announced grants totaling $450,000 as part of
a major Northern Ireland Initiative, an unusual conference on "Reconciliation and
Community," sponsored in part by the American Ireland Fund, discussed the future
of Northern Ireland in Newry.                              
<P>
During a meeting in Belfast of Ireland Funds' board members and grant recipients
representing Irish organizations, Worldwide Chairman Dr. Tony O'Reilly announced
a round of grants "to support those on both sides who are trying to stabilize the
situation and who are working to keep lines of communication open between the two
communities."                                   Among the 68 grants made in the
Northern Ireland Initiative were $12,000 to the Centre for the Study of  Conflict
at the University of Ulster in Coleraine; $15,000 to the West Belfast Festival;
$10,000 to the Shankill
Women's Centre; and $10,000 to the Derry-based Field Day Theatre Company. For the
conference on "Reconciliation and Community," the US-based Foundation for a Civil
Society received $20,000.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
As a contribution to the growing momentum of peace in Northern Ireland, the
conference was extraordinary.
Over 300 leaders from all sectors of Northern Ireland engaged in open dialogue on
the future. They were joined by political leaders, leading policymakers, and
other experts from Colombia, Costa Rica, the Czech Republic, El Salvador, Israel,
the Palestine Liberation Organization, Poland, South Africa, Spain, and the US.
Representatives from the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom also took
part.
<P>
As Ireland's Tanaiste and Minister for Foreign Affairs Dick Spring told the
conference, "The most important lesson is that this journey can be made." Oscar
Arias, Nobel laureate for peace and former President of Costa Rica, further
challenged the people of Northern Ireland to make peace real and lasting.
<P>
"It is not easy," said Arias. "But you will see that others have done it and are
doing it today, under the most difficult conditions. In the face of deep
differences and harsh memories, they have decided that they share one broad roof
and must learn to live under it together."
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="59" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
AIF Board members John Sharkey (left) and Robert
Dunfey at the Ireland Funds' Belfast meeting.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="58" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Addressing the Belfast meeting in June was Geraldine McAteer from Foundry
Regeneration Trust.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
