<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>KYLEMORE ABBEY SCHOOL BENEFITS FROM AIF GRANTS</H3>
</CENTER>

<IMG WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="188" SRC="graphics/p5a.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT>
GALWAY-Over $100,000 in grants have recently been made to the Kylemore Abbey
school and grounds in Connemara in order to further the
American Ireland Fund's efforts to address educational needs in Ireland. An
international boarding and day school for girls since 1920, the Kylemore Abbey
School seeks to achieve academic excellence in a friendly atmosphere; to provide
a rewarding and maturing experience for its students in a multi-national
environment; and to facilitate personality development in beautiful surroundings.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>ROONEY FELLOWSHIP AWARDED</H3>
</CENTER>

PITTSBURGH-A  second  year student at Newry College, Newry, Co. Down is the 1995
recipient of the Rooney Fellowship.
As Rooney Fellow, Brian Larkin will attend Duquesne University's School of
Business in Pittsburgh with Dean Thomas Murrin as his mentor. He will also serve
an internship in the marketing department at Heinz USA.
<P>
The Rooney Fellowship is named in honor of AIF Vice Chairman Dan
Rooney, who owns the NFL Pittsburgh Steelers. In Pittsburgh, the Rooney
Fellowship is administered by the Ireland Institute of Pittsburgh and the Newry
Pittsburgh Partnership.
<P>
"The Rooney Fellowship aims not only to provide education for students, but also
to improve business and cultural links between Northern Ireland and the US."
notes Sister Michele O'Leary, President of the Ireland Institute.
<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p5b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
Welcoming 1995 Rooney Fellowship winner Brian Larkin of Newry (second from left)
are Sr. Michele O'Leary (far left),
Dr. Raymond Mullen (second from right), and AIF Vice chairman Daniel Rooney
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>AIF LITERARY AWARD TO JOHN MONTAGUE</H3>
</CENTER>

BELFAST-In a ceremony at Queen's University, poet John Montague received the 1995
American
Ireland Fund Literary Award of $15,000. His selection was made by a
committee of Irish writers that was chaired by novelist Thomas Flanagan.
<P>
"It is, of course, in a special way appropriate that the award should be
given this year to a Northern writer as we find ourselves hoping for and praying
for a solution of the province's longstanding grievances and concerns," Flanagan
told the Cork Examiner newspaper.
<P>
"No voice has expressed those concerns with stronger emphasis than has
Montague and yet always with a sense of history's echoes, paradoxes and
ambiguities," he added.
<P>
In late 1995, Wake Forest Press published Montague's "Collected Poems"
Before beginning a career in teaching, Montague worked as Paris correspondent for
the Irish Times. He has taught at universities in France, Ireland, Canada, and
the US. Montague is currently Distinguished Professor of English in the New York
State writers program of the State University of New York, Albany.
<P>
The AIF Literary Award is funded by the Thomas F. O'Neill family of New York and
Florida. Past recipients include Seamus Heaney (see accompanying article), Brian
Friel, and Seamus Deane.
<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p5c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="41" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER></A>

In Belfast, 1995 AIF Literary Award winner John Montague.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>LORETTA BRENNAN GLUCKSMAN IS NEW AIF NATIONAL PRESIDENT</H3>
</CENTER>

NEW YORK-Loretta Brennan Glucksman, president of Westland
Kssociates, a public relations and governmental affairs consulting firm, was
appointed AIF National President by the AIF Board of Directors. Previously AIF
President-East Coast Region, Brennan Glucksman succeeds John F. O'Sullivan who
served in the office since 1990 and is now vice chairman.
<P>
"Loretta has given outstanding service in the development of American
philanthropy for Ireland," said Dr. Tony O'Reilly, AIF Chairman. "As AIF National
Ppresident, she will direct the American Ireland Fund's continued growth and
provide strong leadership."
<P>
In addition, O'Reilly praised John F. O'Sullivan as a "distinguished leader of
the American Ireland Fund who oversaw a period of unprecedented global growth in
the Ireland Funds organisation."
<P>
On a recent visit to Ireland, Brennan Glucksman attended an informal reception
for President of Ireland Mary Robinson held by Rural Resettlement Ireland (RRI).
<P>
RRI grew out of a voluntary rural resettlement program begun in 1990 by
Jim Connolly and has received AIF grant assistance. To date, RRI has assisted
nearly 200 families to move to 17 rural counties. Over 3,600 families are on the
waiting list.

<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p5d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p5d-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
AIF President Loretta Brennan Glucksman with (left) Hugh Finnegan, president of
Rural Resettlement Ireland, and Don Kelly, RRI.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>





