ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">

<B>
<P>

<CENTER>
<H2>A year of peace:what next?</H2>

<H3>An Essay By Maurice Hayes</H3>
</CENTER>

<IMG WIDTH="244" HEIGHT="266" SRC="graphics/p8a.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
<BR>
THE SUMMER OF 1995. The first summer of peace for 25 years in Northern Ireland
was also a summer of glorious sunshine, of good spirits and good weather, which
reflected the spirit of the community.
<P>
The most marked feature following the ceasefires has been the absence of fear. A
great weight has been lifted from people. Parents no longer worry that their
children might be victims of random violence and wives that their husbands will
not return from work. People living in isolated areas are free from the terror
that they will be victims of random sectarian shootings or tit-for-tat reprisals.
<P>
There is a changed atmosphere, too. People have embraced peace as an idea whose
time has come, and which must not be let go. Hopes are high, yet simple enough:
To enable people to live together in peace and harmony, and to provide them the
opportunity to find work. The precise political arrangements required to bring
this about are less important and are certain to be the subject of debate for
some time. It was a good summer, too, for tourism, for business, for people
enjoying the new-found freedom to move without fear. There is a new confidence in
the community, a willingness to move out from behind barricades and to talk and
listen. Most of all, there is a will for peace that makes a return to violence
unthinkable.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
Much of this improvement is due to the work of groups which have been assisted in
the past by the Ireland Funds. People like Jackie Redpath on the Shankhill Road
in West Belfast; Joyce McCartan in South Belfast; Paddy Doherty in Derry; the
Corrymeela Community; and various community and voluntary groups who have been
labouring for years in their own communities now see the task transformed. Most
of them are looking to embrace job creation, to work with prisoners and with
cross-community groups. Only for the support and help of the Funds in the past,
many of them would not have survived to play the important roles they
are taking today.

</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
 A <B><A HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. 
</BODY>
