<CENTER>
<H1>Year In Review<HR WIDTH=190></H1>
</CENTER>
<H3>HOUSTON</H3>
THE LONE STAR STATE WAS SHINING
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
When the AlF's first ever Houston Gala convened on April 6 at the Houstonian
Hotel to celebrate Ireland, a Houston resident and former U.S. President, George
Bush was the evening's honoree. Currently at work with Gen. Brent Scowcroft, his
former National Security Advisor, on a book about his Administration's foreign
policy achievements, Bush resides in Houston with his wife, Barbara Bush. They
have five children and 13 grandchildren.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>PITTSBURGH</H3>
WHOLEYS HONORED FOR "OUTSTANDING CONTRIBUTIONS"
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13b.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
On March 25, supporters gathered for the city's eleventh annual AIF dinner.
Robert and Lois Wholey received the 1995 Chairman's Award for Outstanding
Contributions to Irelandthe first such award ever to be bestowed on a couple.

The evening's special guest was actor and humanitarian Paul Newman who
founded Ireland's Barretstown Gang Camp for children with serious illnesses. I
AIF Chairman Tony O'Reilly presented Newman, who is also a professional racing
driver, with a Waterford Crystal car as screen colleague Melanie Griffith and
others cheered him on.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>NEW YORK 20TH ANNIVERSARY DINNER</H3>

NEIL JORDAN WINS PERFORMING ARTS AWARD
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13c.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
A record attendance of more than 1300 American Ireland Fund members and friends
celebrated the Fund's twentieth annual New York Dinner on May 11 at Tavern on the
Green. Honorees at the gala event were Tony O'Reilly and Dan Rooney, the
co-founders of the Ireland Fund, who were feted for their daring and vision in
1976 and for their unstinting service, support and encouragement in the ensuing
years.
<P>
The Central Park event was also occasion for presentation by Gregory Peck of the
annual Award for the Performing Arts to Neil Jordan, Oscar-
winning screenwriter and film director who scored the 1992 hit, "The Crying
Game." Sligo-born Jordan is also author of an acclaimed short stories collection,
"Nights in Tunisia" (1978) and two novels, "The Past" (1980) and "Dream of a
Beast" (1983). As part of the Award, Jordan designated a $10,000 grant to the
University College Dublin Film School.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>WASHINGTON</H3>
THE NATIONAL GALA
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13d.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
On St. Patrick's Eve, March 16, Vice President Al Gore joined An Taoiseach John
Bruton, Prime Minister of Ireland, and the Hon. John Hume, M.P for Derry, and
many others for the American Ireland Fund's annual National Gala in Washington,
D.C. Hume received the AIF's National Humanitarian Award.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>SAN FRANCISCO</H3>

"RED" FAY HONORED WITH DISTINGUISHED LEADERSHIP AWARD
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13e.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
In 1946, Navy mates Paul Burgess, "Red" Fay, Jr., and John E Kennedy
returned from war duty and shared a room in Boston where Fay helped his
friend win a seat in Congress. Years later, Fay served as Under Secretary of the
Navy in JFK's Administration and after the President's death wrote "The Pleasure
of His Company" about their friendship.
<P>
On March 10, "Red" Fay received the 1995 AIF Distinguished Leadership
award from a hometown San Francisco crowd led by Eamonn Keegan, AIF
President West Coast Region.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p13f.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
<BR>
John O'Sullivan receives an award from Sheila O'Malley and Loretta Brennan Glucksman in recognition of his 5 years as President of the AIF.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
</B>
<P>
