<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>GREAT BRITAIN</H2>
</CENTER>
<H3>Ireland Fund of Great Britain</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="206" HEIGHT="194" SRC="graphics/p18a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
LONDON-Guests at the eighth annual Midsummer Night's Magic Ball of the Ireland
Fund of Great Britain heard a message from Prime Minister John Major. "Much of
the credit," he said, for "the remarkable transformation that peace has brought
about to the lives of people in Northern Ireland, and throughout the United
Kingdom...(goes) to organisations like the Ireland Fund."
<P>
The evening's honoree was Josephine Hart, outgoing IFGB Chairman, who in her
eight years in office helped the Fund to raise almost $1.2 million. "It's been a
wonderful experience and I'm very grateful to have had the opportunity," Hart
told the Irish Times. Author of the best-selling novel "Damage" (1988), Josephine
Hart recently published her third novel, "Oblivion".
<P>
In June of 1995, Brian Hayes took over from Josephine B. Hart as Chairman of the
I.F.G.B. Brian has been involved with the Fund since its inception, and he brings
to the position an outstanding knowledge of the City of London and those who live
there. His expertise as a fundraiser will see the I.F.G.B. go from strength to
strength over the next few years.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="153" HEIGHT="173" SRC="graphics/p18c.gif" ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
Special guests at the Dorchester Hotel gala included Ms. Hart's husband, Maurice
Saatchi; Sir Andrew Lloyd Webber; film producer Sir David Putnam; and broadcaster
Terry Wogan.
<P>
Earlier this year, the Ireland Fund of Great Britain's fifth annual Greyhound
Racing Dinner on March 6 at Wembley Stadium attracted over 300 enthusiastic
"punters" who gathered to cheer on their favorites. The event was hosted by the
Hon. Kevin Pakenham.
<P>
The IFGB kept its fundraising calendar full with a St. Patrick's Night Party held
at the Porchester Hall, Bayswater, hosted by Hugo MacNeill and Rory Tobin. In
May, the Fund also sponsored an Ascot Racing Dinner
hosted by Stephen Quinn and David Reid Scott. In the past few months, the Ireland
Fund of Great Britain has held two extremely successful events. One was the
annual Christmas Craic Ball in London and the other was their first ever Ireland
Fund of Great Britain event in Birmingham, chaired by Tom Gallagher.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p18b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="66" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p18b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
