<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">



<B>
<P>
<H2>The Chief Executive's Message</H2>

<IMG WIDTH="147" HEIGHT="204" SRC="graphics/p1.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="10">

Welcome to our second issue of our revamped Connections which I hope you find
interesting and informative. Also, thank you to those of you who took the time
and the trouble to write with your reactions, criticisms, ideas and indeed the
odd smidgens of praise.
<P>
	Building on your feedback what we've tried to do in this issue is to continue
to cover all the various fundraising events which have been held so far this
year. In addition we've tried to tell you a little bit about some of the key
people involved in the Funds, not only here and overseas, but also in Ireland. A
further expansion has been to give you information about various projects we have
supported this year as well as a definitive listing of all the grants made in the
first half of 1996 with a few words on each. In addition we've put together a
"Tour of Ireland" featuring 17 projects which the Funds have grant aided. Perhaps
this might encourage you to make a visit.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
	I'm glad to say that coming off the back of a record breaking 1995 the
momentum has continued into 1996. San Francisco was a particular highlight and
Pittsburgh broke through the magic million dollar mark and was the most
successful dinner we've held in our 20 year history. The National Gala in
Washington, D.C. has become a very important event attracting significant
national and international media attention. Around the world all the various
Funds are midway through a busy year with exciting plans for the future.
<P>
	In Ireland the situation is tense and the role that the Funds can play at
this difficult time is critical. I would urge you to read the article in this
issue written by Hugh Frazier, a member of the Ireland Funds Advisory Board in
Ireland. He explains, very succinctly, why the work of the Ireland Funds is now
so important and how we can all make a difference.
<P>
	As we disperse for the next few months I wish you all a pleasant and
enjoyable summer and look forward to reporting back to you at the end of the year
with a full report on our 1996 activities.
<P>
Kingsley Aikins
<P>
<HR SIZE=3>
<H2>The Ireland Funds - Who We Are</H2>
<P>	
The Ireland Funds are the world's largest private sector organization raising
funds for projects of peace, culture, charity and education in Ireland, North and
South.  The Ireland Funds have raised more than $80 million for over 1,000
projects. Often working at the grassroots level the Funds promote programs of
self-help and local community action and operates in the areas of peace and
reconciliation, arts and culture, education and community development. Non-profit
and non-sectarian, the Ireland Funds are made up of chapters in Australia, Great
Britain, New Zealand, Germany, Japan, South Africa, France, Canada and the United
States translating Irish interest and ancestry into constructive change for
Ireland.


<P>




</B> <P> <CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR> A <B><A
