ALT="Forward"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT"> <HR SIZE="4"> <B> <P>


<H2>A Message From The Chairman - Dr. AJF O'Reilly</H2>

<P>
<IMG WIDTH="159" HEIGHT="253" SRC="graphics/p2.gif" HSPACE="10" VSPACE="10"
ALIGN="LEFT">

<BR>
The Ireland Funds have come of age. As we approach the millennium, we take stock,

look ahead and move to position the Funds to meet their objectives going into the

next century.
<P>
	What have The Ireland Funds done over the past 20 years? The Funds have a
proven 
record of achievement, an unrivaled record for raising money for the promotion of

peace, culture, charity and education in Ireland. We have effectively recruited 
support for, and generated interest in, constructive initiatives in Ireland and 
strategically created a "network of goodwill" for Ireland across the globe made
up of 
concerned and dynamic people. Most importantly we have established a reputation
in 
Ireland for integrity and sympathetic understanding of the problems facing local 
communities. With the help of the Irish Advisory Committee, we have managed to 
support people of goodwill in all parts of the island, north, south, catholic and

protestant.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
	How can The Ireland Funds sustain momentum? We need to redouble our efforts
to 
attract donations, to encourage donors to substantially increase their giving, we

need to broaden the donor base, to encourage more people to give. We must
constantly 
seek out ways to encourage the thousands whose only contact is an annual
fundraising 
dinner to deepen their involvement and continue to interact with the work of The 
Ireland Funds throughout the year.
<P>
	By focusing on engaging new and younger people in the affairs of The Funds we

ensure that the vital work continues, and, in that spirit, we of the founding 
generation ought not to forget how our wills will influence the way we are
remembered.
<P>
	We need to encourage donors to take an active interest in the projects in
Ireland 
which their contributions make possible, to visit them, to receive periodic
reports 
of progress and develop a constructive relationship with them.
<P>
	With a renewed focus and dynamic executive direction, both in Boston and
Dublin, 
I have no doubt that we can together generate both enthusiasm and money to rise
to 
the challenge of the new century and to enhance the promotion of peace, culture, 
charity and education in Ireland. The Ireland Funds have never been more prepared
to 
translate the ancestry of the diaspora and the interest of the world at large
into 
constructive commitment to the new and modern Ireland.


</B> 
<P> 
