<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 3)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page2.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page4.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>


<H2>From Coast to Coast, AIF Regional Presidents Support Peaceful, Constructive
Change</H2>

At a recent AIF Board Meeting, Patrick Purcell, owner and publisher of the Boston
Herald, was appointed PresidentÐEast Coast Region, succeeding Loretta Brennan
Glucksman, who now serves as AIF National President. In 1993, Purcell was Dinner
Chairman for the AIF's Boston gala and was appointed a member of the Fund's Board
of Directors.
<P>
	"The organizations the American Ireland Fund supports run the gamut from
education to the arts," says Purcell. "It's that sort of broad-based approach
that will lead to peaceful, constructive change in Ireland, North and South." 
<P>
	According to Dr. Anthony J.F. O'Reilly, AIF Chairman, "Pat Purcell has given
outstanding service in the development of American philanthropy for Ireland. As
the American Ireland Fund's President-East Coast Region, he will direct the
Fund's continued growth and provide strong regional leadership."
<P>
<H3>Patrick Purcell<BR>
A Classic Success Story</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="121" HEIGHT="160" SRC="graphics/p3a.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE=5
VSPACE=5>
Eldest son of an immigrant carpenter from Co. Waterford, Ireland, Patrick Joseph
Purcell was raised in Queens and went to nearby St. John's University. His first
job out of college was working in the advertising of the New York Daily News. In
1980, he became associate publisher of the Village Voice, owned by Rupert
Murdoch's News America Publishing.
<P>
	In 1984, when Purcell was just 36 years old, Murdoch appointed him president
and publisher of the Boston Herald. He later also served as publisher of the New
York Post, TV Guide, and other prominent publications. On Valentine's Day 1994,
Purcell purchased the Herald from News America.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<H3>Economic development his priority</H3>
Not long after he purchased the Boston Herald, Purcell visited Ireland and
Northern Ireland on a trade mission with Massachusetts Gov. William Weld. The
trip reinforced his conviction that economic development is the key to peaceful,
constructive change throughout the Ireland.
<P>
	"As a capitalist," Purcell says, "I believe that the most important thing we
can do for Ireland is encourage employment. "I look forward to strengthening my
commitment and involvement toward that end as AIF President-East Coast Region."
<P>

<H3>Eamonn Keegan:<BR> 
"A Need to Do Something Good"</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="123" HEIGHT="163" SRC="graphics/p3b.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" HSPACE=5
VSPACE=5>

As an AIF regional president, Pat Purcell joins Eamonn Keegan, who was appointed
AIF President-West Coast Region in 1994. Beginning in 1984, Keegan has served
annually as co-chairman of the Fund's San Francisco fundraising dinner.
<P>
	A native of Dublin, Keegan left Ireland in 1963 not long after President John
Kennedy's historic goodwill visit there and just weeks before the President's
tragic assassination.
<P>
	"I thought I'd like to have a look, but I didn't think I'd stay," he recalls.
Indeed, Keegan eventually found great business success in the United States as an
investment counsellor.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
	"My heart still says, 'Made in Ireland,' even if my mind thinks like a Yank,"
he says.  "I believe we all, as human beings, have a need to do something good.
<P>
	"My involvement with the American Ireland Fund gives me that opportunity,"
Keegan adds. "Anything we can do to foster peace and reconciliation has great
appeal to me."



<P>



<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
 A <B><A HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. 
