<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 4)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page3.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page5.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>


<H2>Seeing is Believing</H2>

<H3>See Ireland the Ireland Fund's Way.</H3>
For many years, the Ireland Funds have
sponsored numerous projects throughout Ireland and Northern Ireland that promote
tourism and related economic development. Increased tourism brings a wide range
of positive benefits, including the important human exchange among visitors and
residents. The next time you, a relative or friend visit Ireland and Northern
Ireland, see Ireland the Ireland Funds' way.  It's a great way to see your
investment at work.
<P>

<IMG WIDTH="209" HEIGHT="213" SRC="graphics/p4a.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT">
<BR>
1. Birr Castle * Birr, Co. Offaly<BR>
In 1845, the Earl of Rosse built at Birr Castle
what was then the world's largest telescope. The Birr Scientific and Heritage
Foundation is currently developing Ireland's Historic Science Centre at the site.
The gardens and domain of Birr Castle are open to the public. Information: (0509)
20056.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>

<A HREF="graphics/p4b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> <BR>2. Famine Museum/Strokestown Park
House * Strokestown, Co. Roscommon <BR>
A memorial
to the Great Potato Famine of the 1840s. Information: (078) 33013.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A> 3. Castletown House * Celbridge, Co.
Kildare<BR>Ê
The largest private house in
Ireland. Now operated by the Irish Georgian Society, Castletown was built in the
1720s for William Connolly, Speaker of the Irish House of Parliament. 
Information: (01) 628-8252. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4d-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
4. Cobh Heritage Center * Cobh, Co. Cork<BR>
From Cobh (pronounced like
"cove"), then known as Queenstown, Irish emigrants left for the U.S., Canada and
Australia throughout the 19th and early 20th century. Information: (021) 813591. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4e.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4e-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
5. Foxford Woolen Mills<BR>
A step back in to
time, the recreated 19th-century mills include many of the original mill machines
as well as life-size models and engaging multimedia presentations. Information:
(094) 56756. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4f.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4f-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
6. Ceide Fields * Ballycastle, Co. Mayo<BR>
The most
extensive Stone Age monument in the world-a nearly intact system of ancient
fields, monuments and tombs covering almost four square miles. Information: (096)
43325. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4g.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4g-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
7. Kylemore * Kylemore, Co. Galway<BR>
Overlooking a Connemara lake, Kylemore Abbey is
the home of Benedictine nuns, who run a boarding school for girls as well as a
visitor center and shop selling local crafts and Kylemore Abbey pottery. The
abbey's "Gothic Church" is an exquisite miniature cathedral.
Information: (095) 41146. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4h.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4h-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
8. Fota
Wildlife Park * Cobh, Co. Cork<BR>
Cheetah, giraffe, zebra, red panda, and lemur roam
freely in open, natural enclosures. FotaÕs cheetah breeding center is the largest
outside Africa. Information: (012) 812736.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4i.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4i-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
9. Derry City Centre * Derry<BR>
Numerous projects
undertaken by the Inner City Trust and other AIF-supported groups have restored
the historic city centre overlooking the River Foyle. Attractive restaurants,
shops, and a crafts village lie within Derry's medieval walls. Information:
contact the Northern Ireland Tourist Board, toll-free 800-326-0036.  
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4j.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4j-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
10. Linen Hall Library * 17 Donegal Square North,Belfast<BR>
Established 1788 "to improve the mind and excite a spirit of
general enquiry, Linen Hall Library is the city's oldest, with reading room,
caf, and specialty books and prints on sale. Information:
(01232) 321707.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4k.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4k-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
 11. Macnas * Galway<BR>
 One of Ireland's most innovative theatre troupes. Upcoming
Performances include the Galway Arts Festival, Wed., July 17 and Sun., July 21;
and Dublin Theatre Festival, Olympia Theatre, beginning Oct. 8. Information:
Contact Irish Tourist Board (address, toll-free telephone below)
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4l.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4l-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
12. Marsh's library * Dublin<BR>
In the shadow of St. Patrick's
Cathedral, Dublin's oldest public library was founded by Archbishop Narcissus
Marsh in 1701. Scholars formerly studied rare books while locked in
"cages"-alcoves enclosed by wire grilles. Information: (01) 543511. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4m.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4m-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
13. Muckross House * Killarney, Co.Kerry<BR>
At the heart of Killarney National Park on the shores
of Lower Lake, Muckross House includes the Kerry Folklife Center, where
traditional crafts are demonstrated. Information: (064) 31440. 
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4n.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4n-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
14. Ulster American Folk Park * Campbill (3 miles north of Omagh on A5), Co.
Tyrone<BR>
Recreates a traditional Tyrone village and includes the ancestral home of
millionaire
 Andrew Mellon. In 1996, the Park marks its 20th anniversary year with a series
of special
 events including the Frontier Festival, Aug. 3-5 and Aug. 24-26 and an
Appalachian 
& Bluegrass Music Festival, Sept. 6-7. Information: (01662) 243292.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p4o.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p4o-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A>
15. Wexford Opera Festival * Wexford<BR>
One of the
most prestigious and celebrated Irish cultural festivals, the Wexford Opera
Festival attracts a host of performing artists as well as local and international
audiences. The 1996 festival runs Oct. 17 through
Nov. 3. Information: Box Office, Theatre Royal, High St., Wexford, tel. (053)
22144.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>

 For more travel information: Irish Tourist Board, 345 Park Ave., New York, NY
10154. Toll-free: 800-223-6470. Northern Ireland Tourist Board, 551 Fifth Ave.,
Suite 701, New York, NY 10176. Toll-free: 800-326-0036.


</B>
