<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 6)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page5.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page7.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>


<H2>Prominence in Pittsburgh</H2>

At the American Ireland Fund Pittsburgh dinner on April 2, 1993, John Connelly
announced that he was pledging $1 million to the American Ireland Fund with a
further $9 million to follow in a special ten-year bequest program.
<P>

<IMG WIDTH="146" HEIGHT="204" SRC="graphics/p6.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">



"People ask me why," Connelly said at the time. "I'd like to say that more is
expected from a man to whom much has been given. The Lord has blessed me
tremendously. When you leave this world, you leave everything-unless you make
plans that your legacy, your heritage, what you stand for, can go on."

<H3>An Impressive Business Career</H3>
One of Pittsburgh's most successful citizens, John Connelly has enjoyed a career
of remarkable business achievements since the late 1940s. At 16, Connelly
graduated from high school, but he was unable to continue his education due to
the death of his parents. "Fate had other plans," he told Pittsburgh Magazine, in
a recent profile honoring him as "Pittsburgher of the Year."
<P>
	As treasurer of the Allegheny County Sanitary Authority, Connelly guided the
$100 million clean-up of Pittsburgh's Three Rivers, paving the way for the city's
revitalization. In 1958, he established the Gateway Clipper excursion boat fleet,
now the nation's largest fleet of excursion and fine dining boats with operations
in Pittsburgh, New York City, Davenport, Iowa, and St. Louis, MO.
<P>
	John Connelly, according to Pittsburgh Magazine, "watched the rivers
gradually change from fetid sewers into lively playgrounds for boaters and
anglers. River sightseeing cruises spawned dinner cruises and party cruises,
which began the Three Rivers Regatta, and, down the line, opened hotels and
riverboat casinos."
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<H3>Apples for Students</H3>
	Connelly also developed a financial incentive marketing system that has done
business with 4000 banks nationwide and led to Fortune naming him, the "Father of
Incentive Bank Marketing." He later introduced modern riverboat gambling in
America, first with the President Casino in Davenport, IA, then with
establishment of casinos in Biloxi, Mississippi and St. Louis.
<P>
	In addition, Connelly started the "Apples for Students" program, in which
schools save supermarket register tapes and exchange them for free Apple
computers that Connelly buys wholesale and then sell to the stores. So far, the
program has placed $250 million of Apple computer products in schools in all 50
states.
<P>
<H3>A Legacy for Ireland</H3>
When the AIF honored him at its Pittsburgh dinner as "Man of the Year" in 1989,
John Connelly "became immersed in Ireland from then on." Every year since, he has
traveled to Ireland as a prominent AIF supporter.
<P>
	"I have a sense of well-being when I'm in Ireland," Connelly says. "The
fields, the churches, the Cliffs of Moher give me a sense of my heritage."
<P>
	His special bequest program on behalf of the American Ireland Fund, he adds,
owes its inspiration to Tony O'Reilly, AIF Chairman and fellow Pittsburgher.
<P>
	"Never in my life have I met a man with such fire in his belly, and such
eloquent speeches for reconciliation rather than confrontation," says Connelly.

</B>
<P>
