<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 12)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page11.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A
HREF="page13.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>AIF/Trinity Scholarships in Genetics</H2>
<H3>Your Money at Work in Education</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="161" HEIGHT="247" SRC="graphics/p12a.gif" HSPACE="10"
ALIGN="RIGHT"><BR>
Once again this summer, Irish students who are majoring in genetics at Dublin's 
Trinity College will perform research at leading laboratories across the United 
States, thanks in large part to a scholarship established over 20 years ago by
The 
American Ireland Fund. "I regard this scholarship program as perhaps the most 
significant undertaking by the {Trinity College} Genetics Department," says
Professor 
David McConnell, the department head. "We can teach them, but this program gives
the 
student a great boost, and they return to Ireland full of enthusiasm."
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<P>
<H3>U.S. Reasearch whets their appetites</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="190" HEIGHT="275" SRC="graphics/p12b.gif" HSPACE="15" VSPACE="15"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
Trinity College sends six students each year to the U.S. on this special AIF 
scholarship, program. An unusually high number of Trinity's Department of
Genetics 
undergraduates eventually go on to pursue doctorate degrees, reports Prof.
McConnell 
a Cal Tech graduate himself, with about one third of them studying at American 
universities.
<P>
	"The research they do in the summer whets their appetite and the students get

infected by the American 'can-do' spirit," he reports.
<P> 
	"The experience really builds their self-confidence," he adds. "The students
also 
discover that their own educational system has done them a good turn."
<P>
	Altogether, more than 100 Trinity students have received AIF scholarships. 
Prominent among former recipients are Prof. Maurice Kernan at SUNY-Stony Brook,
whom 
Prof. McConnell calls, "one of the best young behavioral geneticists," and Dr.
Jane 
Robinson, a niece of President Mary Robinson and a leading yeast geneticist on
the 
University of Arizona faculty.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
	"It's an absolutely first-class program," observes Bill Vincent, AIF Vice 
Chairman, who has maintained a special interest in the Trinity Genetics
scholarship 
program. The Genetics Department of Trinity College Dublin is the only such 
University department in Ireland. The government has allocated £4m towards the 
construction of a new building for the Genetics Department which will include
major 
teaching facilities for the Science Faculty. This development will allow the 
Department of Genetics to enhance its teaching and research programs.

<H3>A Valuable and Rewarding Experience</H3>

In her research paper, 1995 scholarship recipient Louise Campbell described work
she 
performed at Long Island's Brookhaven National Laboratory.
<P>
	"I worked in Dr. John Dunn's lab, which, along with three other labs, forms
the 
Human Genome Group at Brookhaven," Campbell writes. "Dr. Dunn's lab is currently 
sequencing the genome of the spirochete Borrelia Burgdorferi, the causative agent
of 
Lyme disease. In conjunction with Dr. Ben Luft's lab at SUNY Stony Brook, work is

being done to develop a vaccine against this disease."
<P>
	"I would like to thank John Dunn for his enthusiastic encouragement in the
lab, 
and for making me feel so at home during my stay in the States," she continues.
"I 
am indebted to Prof. McConnell for arranging the position on my behalf and to Dr.

Vincent and The American Ireland Fund for providing much appreciated funding"
<P>
	In Indianapolis at the Department of Medical and Molecular Genetics, Indiana 
University Medical Center, Andrew Lindsay's research under Dr. Jay Tischfield 
included a "micro-satellite analysis of breast cancer."
<P>
	Says Lindsay: "It is due to Dr. Tischfield that I now know that I want to 
continue in research when I graduate. "I would also like to thank The American 
Ireland Fund for giving me the opportunity to go America in the first place," the

Trinity student adds. "It was a very valuable and rewarding experience which I
will 
look back on for the rest of my life."




</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
