<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>The Texas Award Fund</H2>

The Board of The American Ireland Fund recently approved three projects to
receive 
grants from The Texas Award Fund. This award fund, which is part of the permanent

endowment fund of the AIF was originally set up by the American Irish Foundation
at a 
meeting in Houston in 1979 and owes much to the drive, vision and generosity of
Board 
member Connie Ryan of Houston. Connie and others, including Bill Vincent and
Brian 
Burns, made the original contributions to the Fund and the Burkitt Foundation
made a 
$75,000 matching grant. George William Burkitt, a native of County Down, came to
the 
U.S. in the 1800Õs and settled in Texas.
<P>

<H3>Glenstal Abbey</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="236" HEIGHT="149" SRC="graphics/p13a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">
Glenstal Abbey, founded in 1927, is a high school for two hundred and ten
students, 
which enjoys a distinguished reputation in Ireland. It is home to forty nine
monks who 
are at the service of the Church and society in Ireland. However, it is also home
to a 
rare book collection; among the twenty-five thousand volumes in the library,
there are 
over one hundred books dating from the early seventeenth century. A $50,000 grant
from 
the Texas Award Fund of the AIF is being used to help catalogue, computerize and 
conserve its rare book collection, as part of a comprehensive development plan
which 
facilitates access to the library for scholars and other visitors.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<H3>University of Limerick American Studies Program</H3>
The University of Limerick has received a grant of $50,000 for a program of
American 
Studies at the University which will assist international understanding of the
U.S. 
and its role in the emerging global society. It was proposed to establish an
American 
Resource and Research Centre which will provide a focal point on the campus for
those 
engaged in American Studies and will support planned academic programs in the
field of 
American Studies.

<H3>Magdalene College Charles Stuart Parnell Fellowship</H3>
The object of this senior research FellowshipÐin effect a visiting
ProfessorshipÐis to 
promote the highest level of active study in Irish history, language, culture and

institutions, and to bring the fruits of that study before the wider academic 
community, and beyond. Such study is vital if the populations of Ireland and
Britain 
are to understand each other and the past and present which binds the two
together. 
This is an ongoing project in Cambridge University which has received substantial

support from the AIF to date, including this  $50,000 grant. The Fellowship has 
attracted world renown academics such as Prof. Joe Lee and Prof. McDonagh.





<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p13b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63"
SRC="graphics/p13b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> University of Limerick

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p13c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63"
SRC="graphics/p13c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Magalene College




