ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>1996 Literary Award Winner</H2>

When the Swedish Academy of Letters awarded Seamus Heaney the 1995 Nobel Prize for 
literature, the Derry-born poet was cited for "works of lyrical beauty and ethical 
depth, which exalt everyday miracles and the living past." The Nobel Prize brings with 
it international acclaim and a $1 million award.
<P>
	Like so many creative artists, however, Seamus Heaney struggled early in his career
 to support his labors with pen and paper. In 1975, when he published "North," Heaney 
generously thanked the 1973 American Ireland Fund Literary Award for allowing him to 
work on that important bookÕs composition with less than the usual financial worry.
<P>
	Throughout the last quarter century, the Thomas F. O'Neill family of New York and 
Florida has funded the Award's $15,000 prize. The Award was first given in 1972 by the 
American Irish Foundation to Austin Clarke; when the Foundation merged with the 
Ireland Fund in 1987, it became known as The American Ireland Fund Literary Award.
<P>
<H2>Michael Longley</H2>

Over the last 25 years, the American Ireland Fund Literary Award has established 
itself as one of the most important prizes  given to Irish writers of poetry, prose 
and plays. The honorees have been men and women of great artistry and creative skill 
whose work has given voice to Ireland's past and present, its delights and its sorrows.
<P>
For 1996, the AIF Literary Award winner is poet Michael Longley of Belfast, whose work 
includes No Continuing City (1969), Man Lying on a Wall (1976), and Gorse Fires (1991),
 which received the Whitbread Prize for Poetry. His most recent book, The Ghost Orchid,
 was published in the U.S. in February by Wake Forest University Press.
 <P>
	"Longley's compassionate perception of his modern world is deftly embodied in a 
lucid, restrained elegance," one critic has written, while the Times Literary 
Supplement has praised "Longley's poetry [as] impressive for its skill, its cadences, 
and the naturalness of the voice speaking within it."
<P>
	Michael Longley was born in Belfast in 1939. For a number of years, he served as 
Director for Literature and the Traditional Arts on the Arts Council of Northern 
Ireland. He is married to the critic Edna Longley and has three children.
<P>
<H3>Evidence Is On The World's Bookshelves</H3>
Now in its 25th year, the American Ireland Fund Literary Award has consistently 
honored the very best of Irish writers. The honor roll of AIF Literary Award winners 
reads like the table of contents for an anthology of contemporary Irish poetry, prose, 
and playwriting.
<P>
	The Irish Times praised the Literary Award as "evidence that the Irish in the 
United States are doing something to help the culture of the mother-country." Each 
year, that evidence accumulates on bookshelves and stages around the world.
<P>
	Indeed, the Award's silver anniversary will be marked in Ireland by publication of 
The Flight Path, a limited edition collection of works especially contributed by 
previous winners.
<P>
<H3>Breathing and Creative Space</H3>
According to Thomas Flanagan in his forward to The Flight Path, the intention of the 
Award, as envisioned in 1971 by Thomas Jordan, formally the AIF's San Francisco-based 
Associate Director, "was to give young writers a breathing and creative space." 
William Shannon, then an editorial writer for the New York Times and later U.S. 
Ambassador to Ireland, agreed to chair the Selection Committee.
<P>
	Under Shannon's direction, the Award's purview grew to include writers whose 
lifetime contribution have enriched Ireland's cultural heritage.
<P>
	In 1988, Flanagan, author of "The Year of the French," took up the committee's 
reins following Shannon's death. Other committee members have included many respected 
Irish-based poets and novelists.
<P>
	Through the Award, the American Ireland Fund has established a strong and enduring 
link between Ireland through the men and women who give voice to Ireland's past and 
presents, its delights and its sorrows.




</B>
<P>
