<B>
<P>


<H2>Indomitable, Courageous Joyce McCartan</H2>

<IMG WIDTH="125" HEIGHT="129" SRC="graphics/p18a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">
The old Pensions Building in Washington was filled with the buzz and excitement of the 
National Gala as the packed audience, including some of the most powerful and 
influential men and women in the nations capital settled themselves for the after 
dinner speeches. Suddenly, in a vivid moment, a familiar craggy face filled the 
screens and the hard vowels of Belfast in a rasping, gravely voice cut through the 
noise and demanded attention. It was back to reality with a bump.
<P>
	The face, and the voice, belonged to Joyce McCartan, an old friend of the Ireland 
Funds. There she was, standing in the middle of the Lower Ormeau Road in Belfast, near 
the old markets area, a sectarian interface, a flashpoint for riot and trouble, the 
scene of bombs, attacks and murders, an expanse of inner-city dereliction and ruin.
<P>
	And there was Joyce, in command, indomitable, courageous and outgoing - pointing 
to all the developments she had brought about: a cafe here to from a focus for women 
and a community centre, a training unit there to provide computer skills and jobs for 
local kids and to lead them into employment, a family centre, a hostel, a future hotel,
 work, work, work, improvement, community building, pointing a better way, to politics 
and constructive effort as an alternative to violence.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
	As the cameras panned round both her achievements, she said public tribute to the 
help and encouragement she had received from the American Ireland Fund.
		For Joyce, indomitable, indestructable, courageous, hopeful succumbed to 
ill-health and died a month after the President's visit, after a very short period in 
hospital, battling and fighting to the end, interested in people, selfless, unselfish 
and committed.
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="260" HEIGHT="180" SRC="graphics/p18b.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT">
	Joyce McCartan was well to know the Ireland Funds and had many friends there. She 
spoke passionately about her work at the Dublin Conference in 1994 and the next year 
in Belfast. Her message was always the same: help us to help ourselves. We can do it 
our own way. We can beat the bomb and the bullet, poverty and injustice. We can do it 
by crossing sectarian barriers, by building trust, by getting together on the issues 
which matter to us as wives, as mothers, as ordinary people, and fighting for them.
<P>
		Three of her sons were murdered. No fewer than twenty one members of her 
extended family were killed in the troubles - some by the IRA, some by the British 
Army and the Police, some by sectarian assassins, some by chance. This litany would 
have crushed most people, but not Joyce McCartan. Every time, she came back with 
renewed effort, more determined than ever to find an alternative to violence, more 
determined too to build bridges across sectarian divisions which would lessen the 
chance of conflict in the future.
<P>
	It was Joyce's great strength that she derived the potential of women to bring 
about change. She began bringing them together, first in the Womens Circle and then 
with the help and advise of Advisory Committee member Kate Kelly, reaching out to 
women in all areas of Belfast and further afield.
<P>
		Fund members and donors will remember with affection Joyce's parting words to 
the Washington gala: "Only for the American Ireland Fund I could not have done a thing.
 They stood by me at the beginning when nobody else did."
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>



</B>
<P>
