<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 21)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page20.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A>
<A
HREF="page22.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>The Famine Museum</H2>

Has received a $41,000 grant from The American Ireland Fund. Between 1845 and 1850 in 
Ireland, one million people died of starvation and disease and another 1.8 million 
fled to the United States and Canada. The Great Famine was a watershed in Irish 
history with cultural and social implications for Europe and North America. "The 
centrality of the Great Famine in Irish history has had a major impact on the 
development of Ireland and on Irish communities overseas," says Luke Dodd, 
administrator of the Famine Museum at Strokestown Park, Co. Roscommon. "It is 
fundamental to the Irish sense of heritage and identity."
<P>
<H3>Respect and Honor for "Ordinary Suffering"</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="156" HEIGHT="213" SRC="graphics/p21.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">


On May 14, 1994, the Famine Museum was opened by President of Ireland Mary Robinson. 
This project has recently received a substantial grant from The American Ireland Fund 
which is helping Strokestown and the National Library of Ireland to undertake 
cataloging the approximately 50,000 materials related to the Strokestown Estate in 
order to preserve them for study by students and scholars.
<P>
	"Here in the Famine Museum, at the very center of our history, we have the chance 
to claim the ordinary suffering, the anguish of a past in which men and women who 
were our ancestors did no more than barely survive," President Robinson said. 
<P>
From photographs, letters, official documents and 19th-century satirical cartoons to 
farm implements and a huge iron cauldron from which soup was distributed in a famine 
relief program, the museum's exhibits are organized around such related themes as 
emigration, eviction, resistance and starvation and disease.
<P>
	"This is probably the most unusual heritage project in this country," observes 
Luke Dodd, who was the creative force behind the project.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<H3>"Meaning" Restored</H3>

For a number of important reasons, Strokestown Park is an especially appropriate 
location for the Famine Museum. Strokestown Park House was built during the 1730s for 
Thomas Mahon, a member of Parliament. The architect was Richard Castle, a German 
recently settled in Ireland, and one of the best exponents of then-fashionable 
neo-Palladian architectural principles. When constructed, Strokestown Park House 
operated as the nucleus of a 30,000-acre estate.
<P>
	According to agricultural experts, what caused the Famine was the over-reliance 
in Ireland on a single kind of potato, known as "the lumper," which was vulnerable to 
the particular blight fungus that struck in the 1840s. In 1845, when the blight 
became especially severe, Strokestown Park passed to Major Denis Mahon, who knew 
little about the business of estate management.
<P>
	Like many other landlords, the arrival of the potato blight left Major Mahon 
faced with bankruptcy, as most of his over-populated estate was producing no income. 
Under the direction of his land agent, Mahon initiated schemes to get the estate back 
into order, which included organized emigration and eviction. Thousands perished, 
either on the estate or making the trans-Atlantic journey. Such was the outrage felt 
by locals that Major Mahon was shot dead in 1847 not far from town.
<P>
	"The setting gives the museum its great power," notes Dodd. "We have sought to 
make a restoration of the meaning of the place. The estate no longer exists only as a 
monument to the family who lived there, but also to commemorate the tens of thousands 
of tenants whose lives were inextricably bound up with the 'Big House,' but who were 
seldom, if ever, acknowledged."

<H3>Education is the Real Test</H3>
Central to the museum's purpose is educating not only visitors, but also 
schoolchildren in all of Ireland. A full-time education officer at the museum worked 
closely with curriculum development people in the Department of Education to 
construct appropriate instruction programs.
<P>
	"Ensuring the success of the educational portion of the museum has been a real 
test," Dodd says. "The Famine Museum is about lots of different voices and about the 
difficulty of taking a 19th-century object and displaying it to a 20th-century 
audience."





</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
