<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 32)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page31.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A>
<A
HREF="page33.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>Celebrating The Year of the Irish in France</H2>
<IMG WIDTH="177" HEIGHT="243" SRC="graphics/p32a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">


Throughout 1996, France marks the "Year of the Irish" with over 1,000 special events 
including film screenings, authors' readings, and music performances. For Pierre 
Joannon, Chairman of the Ireland Fund of France and Honorary Consul General of 
Ireland in Antibes, the "Year of the Irish" presents an opportunity to acquaint the 
French people with the achievements of contemporary Ireland. "There's an immense 
goodwill in France toward Ireland, but itÕs not always founded on a deep knowledge of 
what Ireland is really like today," he says."Certainly, Ireland is no longer the 
quaint country of 'The Quiet Man.'"
<P>

<H3>An Irish Honeymoon</H3>
Few Frenchmen know Ireland as well or love its people as deeply as Pierre Joannon. In 
1964, newlyweds Pierre and Annick Joannon cancelled a honeymoon trip to Scotland 
because of a typhoid scare there. Instead, they went to Ireland on a month-long tour 
that eventually took them from the Glens of Antrim in the North to Kerry at the 
island's southern tip.
<P>
	Their unexpected exploration left the Joannons with a lasting love for the island 
of Ireland, and they now have a house in Clonbur, Co. Galway, overlooking Lough Corrib.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<H3>Cannes With an Irish Accent</H3>
Scholar, writer, and lawyer, Joannon became Honorary Consul General of Ireland in 1973.
 His elegant home, a 19th-century villa known as "Les Chnes Verts" ("the green oaks"),
 lies appropriately on Boulevard John F. Kennedy. Among many other events he holds 
there to promote Irish culture and industry, Joannon hosts a glamorous party each May 
for Irish actors, producers, and filmmakers attending the nearby Cannes Film Festival.
<P>
	Joannon's work on behalf of broadening French understanding of Ireland sees him 
move effortlessly from the glitterati to the literati. Among other works, he is 
author of a critically-acclaimed "History of Ireland"; a biography of Michael Collins;
 as well as authoritative essays on James Joyce and William Butler Yeats.
 <P>
	In addition, Joannon launched with Professor Patrick Rafroidi, president of 
University of Lille, the bilingual publication, Etudes Irlandaises, considered the 
most serious journal of Irish studies published in France over the last two decades.
<P>
<H3>At the Wild Geese Ball</H3>
The inaugural event of the "Year of the Irish" in France, Joannon reports, was the 
1996 Ireland Fund of France benefit dinner in Paris at the at the elegant Pre Catelan 
restaurant in the Bois de Boulogne. The gala fundraiser took place on the eve of the 
annual France-Ireland rugby game.
<P>
	The dinner's guest of honor was Dr. Michael Smurfit, who received the first "Wild 
Geese Award," a bronze sculpture by Tanya Nyegaard of Dublin. As owner of Cellulose 
du Pin, based in Bordeaux, the Smurfit group is now the biggest employer in France's 
southwest region of Aquitaine.
<P>
	The term "Wild Geese" stems from the annual migration of young Irishmen in the 
17th and 18th centuries, to join the armies of the European powers, or to seek an 
education and a livelihood. Many Irish names still survive in France, Spain, and 
Austria.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3>"France owes much to Ireland"</H3>
In June 1969, President Charles de Gaulle of France toured Dublin Castle, where he 
spoke warmly of French-Irish relations. Pierre Joannon detailed the General's deep 
affection for the Emerald Isle in his book, "De Gaulle and Ireland". "Ireland...has 
always held, and still holds today, a special place in the hearts of Frenchmen," de 
Gaulle noted to his hosts who included Taoiseach Jack Lynch, Ireland's Prime Minister. "You have just said, Mr. Prime Minister, what Ireland owes to France," de Gaulle continued, "but France owes much to Ireland. There are imperishable links... There is the example which you have always given and which your people, so courageous, so noble and so generous have always given...".
<P>
<HR>
<P>


Paris: From all over France, as well as from Ireland, the U.S. and elsewhere, the 
Irish flocked to the fifth annual Galas of The Ireland Fund of France, held in Paris 
on the eve of the France-Ireland rugby game. Held in the salons of the Pr Catelan, 
one of the most elegant and prestigious restaurants in the French capital, attendance 
surpassed normal capacity.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Renamed this year the "Wild Geese Ball", the event was dedicated to the Irish in 
France and their achievements down the centuries. Hosts of the evening were the Duke 
and Duchess of Magenta, whose family, the MacMahons, trace their desent from Brian 
Boru, King of Ireland, and who gave to the French Republic one of its most famous 
Presidents, Marshal MacMahon. Many of those present at the Ball were distinguished 
descendants of the Wild Geese - those Irish who fought under the French flag in past 
centuries.
<P>
	The proceeds of the Wild Geese Ball  will support the Chryss O'Reilly Scholarship 
Program, which helps young Irish people to undertake French and European studies. The 
generosity of the Fund's patrons also enables The Ireland Fund of France to finance 
the travel and treatment of French children with serious blood diseases at Paul 
Newman's "Hole in the Wall Gang Camp" at Barretstown, County Kildare, as well as 
other charitable and cultural projects in the Franco-Irish context.
<P>
	Organizers of the work of The Ireland Fund of France are Pierre Joannon, the 
writer and historian, and Tadgh F. O'Sullivan, a former Irish Ambassador to 
Washington, Moscow and Paris.
	





<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p32b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p32b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT"></A><BR> Amelie, Duchess of Magenta with Irish 
Minister of State Avril Doyle.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
