<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 37)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page36.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A>
<A
HREF="page38.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>


<H2>Why There is Still a Need for The Ireland Funds</H2>


<H3>Advisory Board</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="142" HEIGHT="188" SRC="graphics/p37a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">

Over the past year I have occasionally heard people ask the question "Is there still 
a need for The Ireland Funds?" In asking this question they point to the peace process
 in Northern Ireland. They highlight the booming Irish economy with its record levels 
of growth backed by massive subventions from the European Union. With the advent of 
such positive development they quite reasonably wonder if there is any need for the 
Ireland Funds to continue to pursue their triple goals of promoting peace, culture 
and charity in both parts of the island. My answer to such doubts is "Yes, there is 
still a very important role for the Funds to play. Indeed in many ways the need is 
greater than ever before."
<P>
	There are many reasons why this is the case. In this short article I will just 
highlight three of them. First, the peace process still needs all the support it can 
get. Secondly, there is a critical task to assist groups in Ireland to cope with the 
effects of very rapid economic, social and cultural transition. Thirdly, the Funds 
have a unique role to play in giving moral support and encouragement to groups and 
individuals struggling to build a better future.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>

<H3>Promoting Peace</H3>
The experience of the past eighteen months has brought home to everyone that the 
cessation of violence is only the beginning and not the end of a long and difficult 
process of peace is to be firmly embedded in both communities. Hopefully the current 
breakdown in the ceasefire will be overcome and all the political parties will shortly 
enter into meaningful talks. It is further to be hoped that these talks will 
eventually lead to some political compromise, though there can be no certainty about 
this. However, even when and if they do, that will only be another stage of the 
process completed.
	What has become very apparent over the recent months is the depth and extent of 
polarization that exists between the two communities. There is a serious lack of 
trust between the various players. Fear, hatred and sectarianism are still very real 
factors. Many people still feel alienated and excluded from the mainstream of society 
in Northern Ireland. There are deeply sensitive and difficult issues like traditional 
marches and policing to be tackled.
	If these issues are to be addressed there will need to be continuing support for
community relations and reconciliation initiatives. The work of local community groups,
 voluntary organizations and women's groups in building peace from the bottom up in 
some of the most disadvantages and divided communities will continue to be vital. 
This is the type of work that the Ireland Funds have supported over the past two 
decades and which has been so important in creating the climate that has made the 
peace process possible. It is essential that such work not only continue but is 
further intensified. Thus, the Ireland Funds need to continue to give a lead to 
others in supporting such work. It is uniquely well placed to do so given its 
long-established reputation for fair and impartial support to projects from both main 
traditions and in all parts of the island.
<P>
<H3>Supporting Transition</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="261" HEIGHT="197" SRC="graphics/p37b.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="LEFT">

Ireland is a country undergoing very rapid economic, social and cultural transition. 
The process of very rapid change and development has many positive features. However, 
it is also a cause of much uncertainty and insecurity. Significant numbers of people 
have not benefited from the recent very rapid economic progress. There are very 
serious problems of unemployment and especially longterm unemployment. Some 
traditional communities, especially in rural areas, have experienced serious decline 
and decay. In the major urban areas there are growing problems of ghetto areas with 
high concentrations of disadvantage. Many of the traditional leadership figures and 
many of the values that Irish society has built around are being increasingly 
challenged.
<P>
	Coping with this rapid change in a positive and constructive manner represents an 
enormous challenge. I believe that the Ireland Funds have a key role to play in 
assisting both parts of the island to meet this challenge. In this regard there is an 
urgent need to support creative and imaginative projects that will help to build an 
inclusive society by promoting constructive community development initiatives that 
will help rebuild flourishing local communities. There is also a need to support 
projects which will help preserve the best of Irish culture and society and to define 
a new and distinctive Irish identity and value system within the context of a modern 
economy and society. These again are exactly the sorts of projects that the Ireland 
Funds have in the past given a lead in supporting and which the Funds are so well 
placed to identify and support in the future.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<H3>Moral Support And Leadership</H3>
When I first became involved in advising the Ireland Funds on projects to support in 
Northern Ireland back in the late 1970s I very quickly discovered that one of the 
really important things about the Funds was that they brought much more than money to 
the projects. Their support gave to groups and individuals struggling to build a 
better future and to promote reconciliation a real sense of their efforts being 
valued and endorsed. In many cases these were projects that up to then not many people 
had appreciated the importance of. That sense of moral support continues to be true 
both for project in the Republic as much as in Northern Ireland. A cheque from the 
Ireland Funds means for recipients not only much needed money but also that a major 
network involving many eminent and successful people is saying that their efforts to 
build a better future or to work for peace and reconciliation really matter.
<P>
	This sense of endorsement has been further enhanced over the years with the 
growing recognition of the Ireland Funds as a worldwide confederation of people 
concerned about Ireland. I think that many projects supported by the Funds have a real 
sense that they have become a part of a great network of people concerned to encourage 
positive progress and development on the island. There is no other foundation or 
organization concerned with Ireland that I know of that can play quite this role.
<P>
<H3>In Conclusion</H3>
These then are just three reasons why the Ireland Funds are needed as much now as in 
the past. It is also important to recognize how well placed the Funds are to meet 
this challenge. They combine several elements in a way that make them a distinctive 
leading force in philanthropy in Ireland. They operate on all island basis. They have 
a well-established track record for enlightening grant-making. They have a 
well-merited reputation in both Unionist and Nationalist communities for being fair 
and even-handed. They have a proven ability to identify and support new and 
imaginative projects. They have significant status as a result of having a worldwide 
network of eminent and distinguished supporters. All of these factors combined mean 
that the Funds are uniquely well-qualified to continue to play a leading and much 
needed role in promoting peace, culture and charity in Ireland.
<P>

<H3>Biographical Note:</H3> 
Hugh Frazer is a member of the Irish Executive and Advisory 
Committees of the Ireland Funds and he has been involved in advising the Funds since 
the late 1970s. He comes from Cullybackey in Co. Antrim. He is former director of the 
Northern Ireland Voluntary Trust and is currently director of the Combat Poverty 
Agency in Dublin. He has written and lectured extensively on issues of community 
relations and community development. He is also an artist who specializes in painting 
the urban landscape.
<P>
A cheque from the Ireland Funds means for recipients not only much needed money but 
also that a major network involving many eminent and successful people is saying that 
their efforts to build a better future or to work for peace and reconciliation really 
matter.
<P>
The Funds are uniquely well-qualified to continue to play a leading and much needed 
role in promoting peace, culture and charity in Ireland.








</B>
<P>
