<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 11)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page10.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A
HREF="page12.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>

<H2>Globetrotting with the Confederation of Concern</H2>

<H3>Ireland Fund of Great Britain</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="279" HEIGHT="200" SRC="graphics/p11a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">
At the Ireland Fund of Great Britain's fifth annual greyhound racing dinner on March 6
at Wembley Stadium, over 300 enthusiastic "punters" gathered to cheer on their
favorites. The event was hosted by the Hon. Kevin Pakenham.<BR>
Those attending included Richard Willis, who heads up the Mulligan's chain and Sarah
Willis; radio and TV personality Fred Housego; as well as Brendan Darby and Julie
Rumble of the Bank of Ireland. Among the race sponsors were Kelly Communications,
represented by Fiona and Declan Kelly.<BR>
The IFGB kept its fundraising calendar full with a St. Patrick's Night Party held at
the Porchester Hall, Bayswater, and hosted by Hugo MacNeill and Rory Tobin. In May,
the
Fund also sponsored an Ascot Racing Dinner hosted by Stephen Quinn and David Reid
Scott.
<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>

<H3>Ireland Fund of Canada</H3>

On the occasion of their joint visit to Toronto, the Lord Mayors of Dublin and Belfast
were guests for an Ireland Fund of Canada fundraiser hosted with Co-
operation North and Toronto's Mayor Barbara Hall. The special evening preceeded a
series of St. Patrick's Day events on behalf of the IFC held across Canada.
In Toronto on March 17, the Fund's twelfth annual St. Patrick's Luncheon at the Metro
Toronto Convention Centre attracted more than 1,100 leading business people,
politicians and professionals including Catherine Graham, IFC chair and Peggy Delaney,
one of the luncheon's founding members. Businessman Jim Keating said, "This is a day
when everyone can get together and toast Ireland."<BR>
Elsewhere, the St. Patrick's Society of Montreal joined the IFC for a March 17 benefit
dinner. At the Westin Hotel, Edmonton area supporters attended a St. Patrick's Emerald
Ball hosted by Doodie Cahill, Edmonton Chapter Chairman, and Colm O'Carroll, Vice
Chairman.<BR>
On May 5, the IFC's Ottawa Chapter held its fifth annual Emerald Ball at the Chteau
Laurier Hotel with entertainment by the local branch of Comhaltas Ceoltoiri Eireann.
Dinner chairmen for the festive evening were Pat Whelan and Chris Murray.

 


<P>
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="50%">
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="97" HEIGHT="62" SRC="graphics/grant.gif" ALIGN="LEFT"> ULSTER AMERICAN
FOLK
PARK.<BR>
Ireland's largest museum on emigration to the US 
will commemorate the 150th anniversary of the Great Famine (1845-1849) with special
events and exhibits.<BR>
AIF grant: $5,000.
<BR CLEAR="LEFT">
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p11b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="82" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p11b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A> Ulster American Folk Park.
</B>
<P>
