<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 3)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page2.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page4.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>

<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>

<IMG WIDTH=213 HEIGHT=213 SRC="graphics/p3a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=15 VSPACE=10>
<BR>
The President's response was sincere, heartfelt, and poignant. He paid special
tribute to the Fund and Speaker O'Neill, whom he hailed as a man of the people, a
bricklayer's son who became the most powerful man in Congress and the nation's
most prominent champion of
working people.
<P>
"Speaker O'Neill loved politics because he knew it could make a difference in
people's lives," President Clinton said. "The O'Neill Chair in Peace Studies at
the University of Ulster sponsored by the American Ireland Fund will be a fitting
tribute to his long life and legacy, for Tip O'Neill knew that peace must be
nurtured by a deeper understanding among people and greater economic opportunity
for all.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
"Of all the voices I've heard along this trip," he continued, "the most inspiring
were those of two children I met this morning at the Mackie Plant in Belfast, and
all those children, including some from Derry, who wrote to me in recent weeks
about their aspirations for peace in heartfelt
terms. I know they don't want to go back to the way things used to be. They want
a better future. They deserve it. And I know you, in the American Ireland Fund,
can help make it happen."
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p3b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p3b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Eileen and Brian Burns with U.S. President Bill Clinton and his wife Hillary.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p3c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p3c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>

Attending the ceremony to dedicate the O'Neill Chair were (left to right) John P.
Mackey, counsel, House Committee on International Relations, President and Mrs.
Clinton, Paul Quinn and Pat and John Hume from Derry.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<CENTER>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>
BE A PART OF THE 1996 NATIONAL GALA
</CENTER>
<P>
Once again in 1996, the American Ireland Fund's National Gala takes place on
Thursday, March 14, in the National Building Museum in Washington, DC.
<P>
The success of the last several "National Galas" made funding possible for the
O'Neill Chair in Peace Studies at the University of Ulster as well as other
important AlF initiatives to promote peace, reconciliation and renewal across
Ireland, North and South.
<P>
The 1996 Dinner will honor two great friends of Ireland, the Honorable Benjamin
A. Gilman, Chairman, International Operations and Human Rights Committee and Mr
John Sweeney, President, AFL-CIO. The President of the United States, Mr Bill
Clinton and the Prime Minister of Ireland, Mr. John Bruton are also invited
guests.
<P>
<CENTER>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>
AIF ESTABLISHES "TIP" O'NEILL CHAIR IN PEACE STUDIES
</CENTER>
<P>
In 1979, US Speaker Thomas P "Tip" O'Neill, Jr., went to Belfast as the first
American politician to promote dialogues with parties in Northern Ireland. He
believed that no matter the difference in race, religion, and ideology, with
honest debate and open dialogue the peace was there to be grasped.
<P>
The O'Neill Chair in Peace Studies at the University of Ulster in Derry will be
part of INCORE, which is a joint international program between the United Nations
University and the University of Ulster in the field of
conflict resolution and ethnicity. It will be a visiting chair and the holder
will develop non-violent approaches to conflict resolution and management,
particularly in the field of ethnic conflict. He/she will also examine the
American experience of pluralism for its lessons, positive and negative, and its
relevance to Ireland and other societies.

<P>
