<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<P>

<CENTER>
<H3>PEACE THROUGH TRADE IS TOPIC AT WHITE HOUSE CONFERENCE</H3>
</CENTER>

WASHINGTON-In May, the White House Conference for Trade and
Investment in Ireland gathered together hundreds of major political and business
figures from throughout the US, Ireland, Northern Ireland, and Great Britain. In
the first morning alone, the line-up of speakers included President Bill Clinton;
Secretary of State Warren Christopher; Secretary of Commerce Ron Brown; and
former US Sen. George Mitchell. The American Ireland Fund was among a list of
corporate sponsors that also included Mutual of America Life Insurance Company;
Charles Schwab & Co.; and H.J. Heinz, co.
<P>
"Above all else, it was the atmosphere, a really tangible sense that not
only was the violent phase of the conflict over, but also that everybody was
determined to preserve the sanctity of the peace process, and collectively, move
it to the next stage," noted Kingsley Aikins, Ireland Funds Chief Executive, in a
post-conference newspaper column.
<P>
"It was, without a doubt, a huge US triumph and a considerable feather in
the cap of the Clinton Administration who, a long time ago, was both willing to
put Ireland at the top of their foreign affairs agenda and also take risks to
push the peace process.
<P>
"That the conference was going to be something special could be felt on the eve
of its opening when the American Ireland Fund hosted a reception for visitors
from Ireland, mostly Northern Ireland. Nothing remarkable in that, except that
rarely could there have been such an extraordinary cross-section of political
parties in the one room. Totally impossible, even six months ago, the evening was
nearly surreal in the mix of attendance by former opponents.
<P>
"Only in America" is a phrase we often hear-that certainly applied to this
conference. It quite simply couldn't have happened anywhere else."

<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p6a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="53" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p6a-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
In Washington, Secretary Ron Brown addresses
the White House Conferenee for Trade and Investment in Ireland.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>MUCKROSS COMMUNITY CENTRE OPENS</H3>
</CENTER>

<IMG WIDTH="222" HEIGHT="230" SRC="graphics/p6b.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
KILLARNEY-Following a year of construction, which was partially underwritten with
a $25,000 AIF grant, the Muckross Community Centre opened in July with President
of Ireland Mary Robinson on hand for the dedication ceremonies.
<P>
In June 1994, AIF Vice Chairman Bill Vincent laid the cornerstone for the
community center building. In 1932, Senator Arthur Vincent, Bill's father,
presented Muckross House and 11,000 acres to the people of Ireland, and it is
today one of Ireland's most popular tourist attractions.
<P>
Groups planning to use facilities at the Muckross Community Centre include a
local Boy Scout troop, sports clubs and the Muckross Youth Club. "It is our
intention that the center will be available to all sectors of the community, and
that it will help develop social, cultural, civic and economic activities in the
area," said Jerry O'Grady, Muckross Community Association chairman.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>GOLF TOURNAMENT GIVES ST. JAMES HOSPITAL BOOST</H3>
</CENTER>

DUBLIN-In november, committee members of the American Ireland Fund Golf Toumament
presented a check for $45,000 to St. James Hospital. With the AIF grant to the
Leukemia and Bone Marrow Transplant Accommodation Trust, the hospital will pay
off the mortgage on
a second apartment for the families of sick children built with AIF support.
<P>
"It's very satisfying," says Jack Kennedy, committee chairman for the
seventh annual AIF Golf Tournament at the Ocean Edge resort on Cape Cod, MA. "The
first apartment has been full every night since it was opened. We are pleased to
help ease the transition for Irish families who must bring their critically ill
children to Dublin for treatment."
<P>
Altogether, Kennedy estimated, AIF grants to St. James Hospital raised at the
annual Cape Cod golf tournament currently total over $120,000. MetLife was once
again the major corporate sponsor. 
<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p6c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p6c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>

Golf committee members (left to right) Paul McNealy, Dan Conley, Special Events
Golf Director Jack Kennedy, Bill Roche and Ken Phillips.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>





