<B>
<P>


<CENTER>
<H3>NOBEL LAUREATE HEANEY HAS AIF PEDIGREE</H3>
</CENTER>

DERRY-Born poet Seamus Heaney winner of the 1995 Nobel Prize for Literature, has
maintained a warm relationship with the Ireland Funds since he received the
American Ireland Fund Literary Award in 1973.
<P>
In awarding the $1 million Nobel Prize, the Swedish Academy of Letters
cited Heaney for "works of lyrical beauty and ethical depth, which exalt everyday
miracles and the living past." Born into a farming family near Derry, Heaney, 56,
teaches at Harvard University and also has a home in Dublin.
<P>
In 1989, at the Ireland Funds Conference in Cork, Heaney delivered the keynote
address on "Varieties of Irishness."
<P>
"The more varieties there are in Ireland, the better and the healthier they
will turn out," he told a rapt audience. He compared the work of a writerin
which the impulse to write discovers direction in the poem as it is writtento
the work of the Ireland Funds, where the impulse to contribute to Ireland's
development finds fulfilment in the projects eventually chosen for support.
<P>
Throughout the years, Heaney has attended numerous functions of the
Ireland Funds, in particular the annual ceremonies for the AIF Literary Award.
<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p7a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="69" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p7a-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
In 1991, Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney (second from left) Joined AIF Literary
Award winner Nuala Nl Dhomhnall, AIF vice chairman Bill Vincent (far left) and
Shane O Nell, whose family has funded the Award.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>GLUCKSMANS GIVE AIF $3 MILLION FOR EDUCATION</H3>
</CENTER>

<IMG WIDTH="309" HEIGHT="172" SRC="graphics/p7b.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
AIF National President Loretta Brennan Glucksman and her husband, Lewis Glucksman
have given a $3 million gift to the Amencan Ireland Fund for the promotion of
higher education in Ireland. The gift was formally announced at the Fund's Boston
dinner in November.
<P>
Beginning in 1993, the American Ireland Fund identified the specific area
of education as one where it would seek supplemental funding from its many
friends and supporters to address particularly pressing problems and exciting
opportunities which had been identified.
<P>
For many years the AIF has supported numerous Irish educational institutions.
This important education initiative recognizes that Ireland has a large
population of children to educate; Ireland's schools have extensive needs for
capital plant and equipment; and that there is a lack of any endowment to support
educational institutions.
<P>
As solutions, the AIF education initiative will promote and develop centers of
excellence at Ireland's universities; support rural education and development;
and otherwise seek support for various educational institutions including
libraries and museums.
<P>
In addition to serving as AIF National President, Loretta Brennan Glucksman is
president of Westland Associates. Lewis Glucksman is vice chairman of Smith
Barney, Inc. In 1993, the couple were honored at the AlF's New York dinner for
their long-term love of Ireland and its people.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<CENTER>
<H3>ALL ABOARD FOR PEACE, CULTURE AND CHARITY</H3>
</CENTER>

The party of the summer was held aboard a 105 foot yacht docked in Nantucket
Harbor, and owned by real
state developer Patrick Carney, and his wife Lillian.
<P>
Welcomed aboard the Kaleen III for an evening to benefit the American
Ireland Fund were newlyweds Sen. John Kerry and his wife Teresa Heinz; US
Ambassador to Portugal Elizabeth Frawley Bagley, and her husband, Smith Bagley;
Pierre Salinger, journalist and press secretary to President John F. Kennedy, and
his wife, Nicole; Edmund and Doris Reggie (parents of Sen. Edward Kennedy's wife,
Victoria Reggie); NBC-TV Chairman and CEO Robert Wright, and his wife, Suzanne;
and Thomas P. O'Neill, III, his wife, Jackie, and their son, Thomas IV.

<P>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<A HREF="graphics/p7d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p7d-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>

U.S. Senator John Kerry, U.S. Ambassador to Portugal, Elizabeth Frawley Bagley
and NBC chairman Robert Wright in Nantucket at the AIF
Summer celebration.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>





<P>
