<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 9)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page8.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page10.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">
<B>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH="336" HEIGHT="253" SRC="graphics/p9a.gif" VSPACE=10>
</CENTER>



The great strength of the Ireland Funds is that they represent voluntary effort
and that they reach throughout the world. The money invested in voluntary and
charitable activity in Ireland is, of course, both impressive in amount and
important in effect, but just as important in sustaining hope. That people with a
benign interest in Ireland from around the world were working on their behalf and
wanted to help was a significant factor in giving people courage.
<P>

The American Ireland Fund led the way and remains the biggest donor, but each of
the Ireland Funds brings its own distinct contribution. Canada has taken a
particular interest in Northern Ireland and Australia in integrated
education; France has developed links with Ireland through a special scholarship
program. The Ireland Fund of Great Britain divides its support between Ireland
and Great Britain.
<P>
The peace process falters at times, but hopefully keeps its sense of direction.
The task now is to begin to rebuild in Northern Ireland a society that has been
sundered by violence. The immediate need is for employment, the encouragement of
enterprise, and development of community self-help projects. It is important that peace should be seen to make a
difference in a real as well as an atmospheric way. For a young man or woman in
an area which has been riven with violence, the biggest difference would be work,
education and training-together, allowing him or her a chance to contribute to
society.
<P>
The ending of violence produces new sets of problems and new calls for support
from the Ireland Funds. The configuration of the Ireland Funds as an
international Confederation of Concern for Ireland broadens its sphere of
influence and projects a positive image of the new Ireland, North and South,
young, dynamic, committed to growth, edging towards a settlement which will
accommodate difference in Northern Ireland and secure peace
on the island.
<P>
In that tremendous endeavor, Ireland's people need, more than anything, the help,
support, and encouragement of their friends around the world. It is the genius of
the Ireland Funds that they provide just such a network, and a reservoir of
goodwill, guidance, assistance and practical encouragement.

</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
 A <B><A HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. 
</BODY>
