<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<P>

<CENTER>
<H1>Year In Review<HR WIDTH=190></H1>
</CENTER>

<H3>PALM BEACH</H3>
FABULOUS FEMMES OF PHILANTHROPY
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
At the Breakers, Tina Harvey Flaherty, Felice Mark Lippert, and Chryss
Goulandris O'Reilly, were event co-chairs for a very special AIF evening
honoring Carolyn Buckley Dreyfoos, Gay Hart Gaines, Elesabeth Ingalls
Gillet, and Rosemarie Stack, the Fabulous Femmes of Philanthropy. The
AIF dinner and several related events attracted what Palm Beach Today called, "a
small army of noteworthy guests." On that list were former Presidential Chief of
Staff John Sununu as well as brothers Jim and Pat Rooney and Eileen and Brian
Burns.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>LOS ANGELES</H3>

A NIGHT FOR A "CIRCLE OF FRIENDS"
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14b.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
The reviews were enthusiastic following a major film premiere at Jimmy's
Restaurant to benefit the AIF. On the screen and in the audience were Minnie
Driver and Chris O'Donnell, who co-starred in "Circle of Friends," based on the
novel by Maeve Binchy who was guest of honor. Also there to applaud Peace,
Culture and Charity were Michael and Gretchen Wayne.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>PHOENIX</H3>

THE FIRST ARIZONA GALA
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14c.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
For the inaugural event benefiting the American Ireland Fund in the
Southwest, dinner chairman James P. Cunningham declared his hope that, "We are
inaugurating not only an activity for the evening but also a movement which
hopefully takes root in Arizona and has the effect of uniting Arizona's Irish."
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>HARTFORD</H3>

THANKS, BRUCE
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14d.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
Officers and directors of the John F. Kennedy Trust joined with AIF supporters to
present former Congressman Bruce Morrison with the "Spirit of Ireland" Award at
the AIF's inaugural event in Hartford on May 6. Morrison is remembered for his
efforts to help secure visas to the U.S. for young Irish people and his
involvement in the peace process.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>DENVER</H3>

DANIEL RITCHIE IS HERITAGE HONOREE
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14e.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10>
Once again, Patrick Broe, Edward Timmins and James Whyte were the
evening's co-chairmen for the AIF's Rocky Mountain Chapter annual gala on March
2. Denver supporters honored Chancellor Daniel Ritchie of the
University of Denver with the Rocky Mountain Heritage Award.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=70%>

<H3>SAN DIEGO</H3>

MERCEDES MCCAMBRIDGE STARS AT AIF BENEFIT.
<P>
<IMG WIDTH="166" HEIGHT="115" SRC="graphics/p14f.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10>
Mercedes McCambridge received the AIF Heritage Award in San Diego on
February 25. Born on St. Patrick's Day, McCambridge moved from radio drama to the
silver screen in 1950 and won an Oscar that year for her portrayal of feisty
reporter Sadie Burke in "All the King's Men," her first movie role. In 1964, she
starred on Broadway in "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf."

Another highlight for the San Diego gala was the creation of the "Irish 50," a
select group of individual contributors. Dinner co-chairs were Mike Neil and Leo
Sullivan.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
</B>
<P>
