<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>CHICAGO</H2>
</CENTER>

<H3>A second decade and other "beginnings"</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="337" HEIGHT="187" SRC="graphics/p16a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
ON OCTOBER 5. 1995, THE ELEVENTH ANNUAL "Night of Awakening Dreams" brought
together Chicagoans of Irish background, along with their Colleagues and friends,
who share a deep and lasting concern for all the people of Ireland.
<P>
The fundraising gala honored Edward A. Brennan, who recently retired as Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer of Sears, Roebuck and co. He started his career with
Sears in 1956 selling men's furnishings in Madison,
Wisconsin, and rose through the ranks to become the giant merchandiser's eleventh
Chairman in 1986. Brennan is the third generation of his family to work for the
company.
<P>
Dinner Chairman Patrick G. Ryan noted that the evening marked the beginning of
the American Ireland Fund's second decade in Chicago. "It also marks a beginning
for Ireland, too, and for all its people in the North
and in the South," he said. "With every passing day, the Irish people come
another step closer to peace and reconciliation."
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
Honoree Edward Brennan said, "The American Ireland Fund Dinner was one of the
nicest and most memorable events of my life. The presence of so many good friends
and the many expressions of good will meant a great deal to Lois and me."

<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p16b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p16b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER></A>

Patrick and Shirley Ryan at the Chicago Dinner.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>


<P>
