<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 17)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page16.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A
HREF="page18.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>BOSTON</H2>
</CENTER>

<H3>Peter Lynch Chairs Million Dollar Gala</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="274" HEIGHT="207" SRC="graphics/p17a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
"As I'm sure it does for all of you, Ireland holds a very special place in my
heart," Peter Lynch, Boston dinner chairman and AIF Treasurer, told a gathering
of 1300 guests at the Fund's annual Hub gala. "We gather tonight as witnesses to
the progress the American Ireland Fund has brought to the island of Ireland over
the past 20 years."
<P>
Guest speaker for the 1995 Boston dinnerthe fourteenth annual such eventwas AIF
Chairman Tony O'Reilly. Advertising Co-Chairmen were Jack Connors, CEO of Hill
Holliday Connors Cosmopulos, and Edmund Kelly, President and COO of Liberty
Mutual.
<P>
In addition, Louise Doherty and Thomas Lee, students at Oakgrove College, a Derry
integrated high school, spoke about how support from the American Ireland Fund
for integrated education in Northern Ireland, had positively changed their lives
and their communities. (see below)
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
Irish folksinger Frances Black performed for guests who included Loretta Brennan
Glucksman, the new AIF National President. At the dinner, Loretta and Lew
Glucksman announced a $3 million AIF gift to build
a library at the University of Limerick (see article, p. 9).
<P>
For 1995, 120 business leaders and philanthropists were honored as "Founders" for
individual donations of $5,000. In addition, 25 "Underwriters" donated $10,000
each.

<H3>OAKGROVE COLLEGE STUDENTS BRING THANKS</H3>

<A HREF="graphics/p17f.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p17f-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10></A>
Taking risks for the cause of peace and reconciliation, the AIF sent its first
grant for integrated education to Lagan College in Belfast when the high school
opened in 1981. In nearly 15 years, Lagan's enrollment has ballooned from 30
pupils to over 700 and more than 20 such schools now operate across Northern
Ireland. AIF grants to support integrated education have continued throughout
that time, and have been joined by grants from other Ireland Funds, induding the
Australian Ireland Fund and the Ireland Fund of Canada.
<P>
The first children who attended integrated schools were part of a daring
experiment," noted the AlF's Kingsley Aikins, "but its been an experiment that
has worked, in large part because of the support from Ireland Funds around the
world."
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p17b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p17b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
AIF board members (left to right), Peter Lynch, Treasurer, Dr. A.J.F O'Reilly,
Chairman, Loretta Brennan Glucksman, President, Governor William Weld and Ireland
Funds Chief Executive, Kingsley Aitkins.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p17c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p17c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER></A>

Arvam and Carol Goldgerg stop to chat with Chryss O'Reilly.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p17d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p17d-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER></A>

AIF treasurer Peter Lynch stops to chat with Joe O'Donnell.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p17e.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p17e-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft and his wife Myrna taking part in the
evening's festivities.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>



