<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 7)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page6.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif"
ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A HREF="page8.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51"
HEIGHT="41" SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif" ALT="Forward" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4">

<B>
<P>


<H2Prominence in Pittsburgh</H2>

"Jobs are the foundation of peace," explains Rooney. "A person with a job is
contributing to his or her community. Without a job, there's a loss of dignity
that can lead to despair and violence."
<P>

<H3>Dan Rooney:
A Fighter Who Loves Peace</H3>
<IMG WIDTH="184" HEIGHT="222" SRC="graphics/p7.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">

In over forty years working for one of the National Football League's premier
teams, Dan Rooney has consistently enjoyed success on and off the field. The
eldest son of Art "The Chief" Rooney, he became the Steelers' president in 1975.
The Pittsburgh native was born on the city's North Side, where he still lives
today.
<P>
	Last season, the hard-charging Pittsburgh Steelers won yet another NFC
Championship, earning them the right to face off against the Dallas Cowboys in
Super Bowl XXX (that match ended with Dallas on top). The men in black and gold
first went to the Super Bowl in 1974, when they beat the Minnesota Vikings.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
<H3>Peace Means So Much</H3>
"This is a time again for us to show support and hope," Rooney says, but he's not
referring to the Steelers upcoming 1996 season.
	Instead, RooneyÑwho with Tony O'Reilly was a co-founder of the American
Ireland Fund in 1976 and currently serves as its Vice ChairmanÑis speaking about
his concern for the peace process in Northern Ireland.
	"Peace means so much to the people of Northern Ireland, and it covers so many
things, including jobs," he says.
<P>
		The American Ireland Fund, in Rooney's eyes, makes a difference through
its ongoing support of grass-roots social and economic development projects.
	"I really believe we have given people hope, particularly in the smaller
organizations," he says. "They know that there are people in America who care
about them in the right way."
<P>
<H3>Little Ireland, Big Support</H3>
	At the AIF's 20th anniversary New York City gala last year, Rooney was
honored along with Dr. O'Reilly for what Claire Cronin, the event's Junior Chair,
called, "the vision to foresee that little Ireland had big supporters around the
world."
<P>
	In Ireland, the entire Rooney family is well-regarded for its various
charities, including the Rooney Prize for Literature and Dan's own active
membership on the board of Flax Trust, a cross-community jobs creation project
based in Belfast.
<P>
	The AIF's annual Rooney Fellowship, named for Dan Rooney and administered by
the Ireland Institute of Pittsburgh, sponsors a student from Northern Ireland to
study at the Duquesne University School of Business and serve an internship in
the marketing department at Heinz.
<P>
	"The Rooney Fellowship aims not only to provide education for students, but
also to improve business and cultural links between Northern Ireland and the US,"
notes Sister Michele O'Leary, the Ireland Institute's president.
<P>
	"It's a great pleasure to work with Dan," she adds. "He cuts through the
nonsense and gets to the core of an issue, but he does so quietly and
efficiently. He's a man of integrity."
<P>
	The Roony relationship with Ireland also encompasses Dan's two brothers, Pat
and Tim, who are both National Board Directors of the AIF. In addition, Pat's son
Joe runs the highly successful American College in Dublin.
	


</B>
<P>
