<P>


<H2>AIF Literary Award Winners - Celebrating 25 Years</H2>

<IMG WIDTH="232" HEIGHT="163" SRC="graphics/p16a.gif" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="RIGHT">

"I look back with joy at the
25 presentations of The American Ireland Fund Literary Award
starting in 1972, nearly all of which I have attended! It is
particularly gratifying that
we have been able to reward older writers such as Sean O'Faolain and Herbert Butler 
and also to have
spotted younger talent who have since developed their skills and become known such as 
Seamus Heaney
and John Banville."
A.W.B. Vincent
<P>
"The financial rewards for the
kind of books I write are less than princely, and while one
doesn't write for money, it is nice once in a while to receive
'a few bob', as we say."<BR>
John Banville
<P>

"(This award) means that
for a year one can pursue,
in Wordsworth's phrase, "a wise
passiveness" and recollect emotion, or in my case commotiom, in
tranquility."
Seamus Heaney<BR>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
"Think what $7,000 would have meant to the course of Irish literature
if Joyce had got such encouragement when he was straining to move
on from the Dubliners
to the Portrait while in
penury in Trieste...the Award can give talent its best chance."
Sean O'Faolain<BR>
<P>

"The leisure that the AIF has
afforded me has given me the
opportunity to put the finishing touches on a number of projects
Ð a play, poems, memoirs."<BR>
Austin Clarke
<P>
"The considerable contribution
the AIF has made to my career
as a writer came at a particularly difficult phase of my life.
They made it possible for me
to complete and stage a play and
make preparations for a new novel."<BR>
Thomas Kilroy
<P>

"Now I can look forward to a couple of years without financial worry
during which I can write not only to boil the pot.(The Award) will keep me in my idea 
of luxury for at least
2 years if not threeÉ"<BR>
Dervla Murphy
<P>



<IMG WIDTH="472" HEIGHT="160" SRC="graphics/p16b.gif" HSPACE="10">

From Left to Right: Austin Clarke, 1972; Seamus Heaney, 1973; Thomas Kilroy, 1974; 
John Banville, 1975; Dervla Murphy, 1976; Aidan Higgins, 1977; Mary Lavin, 1979; 
Benedict Kiely, 1980; Brian Friel, 1981; 

Richard Murphy, 1983; Thomas McCarthy, 1984; John McGahern, 1985; Hubert Butler, 
1986; Seamus Deane, 1989; Nuala Ni Dhomhnaill, 1991; Frank McGuinness, 1992; Eavan 
Boland, 1994; John Montague, 1995

</B>
<P>
