<HR SIZE="4"> 

<P>


<H2>Review of Grants</H2>


<B>O'Casey Theatre Company, Derry</B><BR>
The O'Casey Theatre Company provides theatre training to young people and contributes 
to the urban re-generation of Newry. Funding has made theatre accessible to both 
urban and rural audiences.
<P>
<B>Co-Operation North, Belfast</B><BR>
Funding promotes practical cooperation between the people of Northern Ireland and the 
Republic of Ireland and goes to support  the Cultures of Ireland conference.
<P>
<B>Alert, Dublin.</B><BR>
Alert is a drug awareness and drug prevention organization formed in 1991. Funding 
will allow them to develop and operate programs based on education, sport and 
entertainment.  It will also allow them to publish a newsletter.
<P>
<B>Committee for Ballinsloe Community Information Centre, Galway</B><BR>
Ballinsloe is a disadvantaged area with about 1600 unemployed people.  Funding 
provides training courses for local leaders and the unemployed. This is an important 
local initiative and will help develop self reliance in a rural community.
<P>
<B>Ferns Diocesan Youth Service, Wexford</B><BR>
For 25 years the service has been working with young people and local communities 
throughout Wexford. Funding is for a horizon program focused on women and will 
release matching funds from European Union schemes.
<P>
<B>The Think Tank, Belfast</B><BR>
In February, 1994 a "think tank" was initiated on Belfast's Shankill Road involving 
community activists representing Ulster's protestant working class for the purpose of 
stimulating purposeful debate, not just within communities but between communities. 
This grant will help them to produce a publication "A New Beginning".
<P>
<B>Threshold, Dublin</B><BR>
Threshhold specializes in helping the homeless.  Funding will help establish an 
action reserach project on housing dispute resolution in an area of high unemployment 
and social deprivation in the Dublin Inner City.
<P>
<B>Habitat For Humanity, Belfast</B><BR>
This organization empowers individuals both socially and economically by building 
homes with low-income families.  They will build 22 homes in the next 18 months, 10 
in catholic areas and 12 in protestant areas of Belfast.  This grant will release 7 
times the amount in public funds.
<P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="graphics/p20a.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20a-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
<A HREF="graphics/p20b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20b-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
<A HREF="graphics/p20c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20c-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
<A HREF="graphics/p20d.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20d-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
<A HREF="graphics/p20e.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20e-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
<A HREF="graphics/p20f.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p20f-sml.gif"
BORDER="0" HSPACE="10" ALIGN="ABSMIDDLE"></A>
</CENTER>

<P>
<HR>
<P>
In the first 5 months of 1996, The American Ireland Fund has supported
82 projects throughout
the island of Ireland with grants totalling
$1.1 Million.
here is a representative
sampling of projects
in the areas of education, employment, community development, youth, sport, peace and reconciliation and culture.



</B>
