ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>AUSTRALIA</H2>
</CENTER>
<H3>Australian Ireland Fund</H3>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH="403" HEIGHT="194" SRC="graphics/p20a.gif" VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
</CENTER>
<BR>
SYDNEY-Tara Hill was one of the most venerated spots in early Ireland. From
before the time of the legendary King Cormac Mac Airt in the third century, Tara
Hill was the seat of Ireland's priest-kings. Tara's atmosphere of power and myth
was recently recreated here at a "Banquet of Tara" to benefit the Australian
Ireland Fund, according to Teresa Keating, the Fund's executive secretary. 
<P>
Recent major corporate sponsors of Australian Ireland Fund events at cities across the
island continent have included Qantas Airlines; Aer Lingus; Ashford &
Dromoland Castles; Guinness Australasia; Sydney Convention and Exhibition Centre;
and Waterford Wedgwood.
<P>
 Important individual supporters include Peter and Jane Cosgrove; Cameron
O'Reilly; and Patrick Lynham.
 Over one-third of Australians have some Irish ancestory. Currently, the
Australian Ireland Fund Chairman is John O'Neill. Formerly CEO of the State Bank
of New South Wales, O'Neill is now CEO of the Australian
Rugby Football Union. His Irish roots can be traced to the early days of
Australian colonization. William Charles O'Neill, John's great-grandfather was
born in Kerry in 1835. His great-great-great-grandfather,
Thomas Galvin, came to Australia in 1798. In addition to fundraising dinners,
garden parties, a concert at Sydney Opera House and film festivals have been
organized across the nation-continent. The Australian
Ireland Fund has primarily supported projects of reconciliation and those aimed
specifically at assisting youth. Grant recipients include Lough View Integrated
Primary School, Castlereagh, and All Saints Youth Club, Co.
Antrim.

<P>
The Fund has also benefitted from a close relationship with The Lansdowne Club, a
group of over 350 Irish born business people who are based in Sydney. Chaired by
Peter Brennan, the Club made a donor designated grant of $5,000 to the Australian
Ireland Fund for the Central Remedial Clinic in Dublin.
<P>
The Australian Ireland Fund's grants total over $500,000. Recent grants to
Ireland, North and South, made by the Australian Ireland Fund include:
Committee on the Admin. of Justice, Londonderry YMCA, Phoenix Trust, Macnas,
Craic Na Coillte Community Arts, Drugs Awareness Programme,
Dungannon Bereavement Community, Dockward Community, Holywell Trust, Parents
Alone Resource Centre, Tallaght Arts Forum, Women Together and Windsor Women's
Centre.

</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
 A <B><A HREF="http://www.visunet.ie/visunet/">VISUnet</A></B> created site. 
