<HEAD><TITLE>The Ireland Funds - Connections (Page 21)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../gfx/pattern.gif" link="#0000ff"
vlink="#ff0000">

<A HREF="../connect.htm"><IMG WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="57" SRC="../conn-sml.gif"
ALIGN="RIGHT" BORDER="0"></A>

<A HREF="page20.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hibk4.gif" ALT="Back" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A> <A
HREF="index.htm"><IMG WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="54" SRC="../index.gif"
ALIGN="MIDDLE"
BORDER="0"></A><A
HREF="page22.htm"><IMG WIDTH="51" HEIGHT="41"
SRC="../../gfx/hifw4.gif"
ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>NEW ZEALAND</H2>
</CENTER>
<H3>Ireland Fund of New Zealand</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="307" HEIGHT="246" SRC="graphics/p21a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
AUCKLAND-Set up in 1992, The Ireland Fund of New Zealand is steadily growing in a
country where many claim a connection with Ireland. About 600,000 of the nation's
3.5 million inhabitants are of Irish background, with about 10,000 to 15,000 of
those Irish born. The current Prime Minister, Jim Bolger, has very strong Irish
links. Both his parents emigrated to New Zealand from Wexford in the 1930s.
Bolger is one of a leading group of successful Irish-New Zealanders who have made
it to the top of the political and business ladder over the last 30 to 40 years.
<P>
An Auckland merchant banker, Sir Michael Fay, serves as Chairman of the Board of
Directors of the Ireland Fund of New Zealand. Fay is one of New Zealand's most
successful businesspeople and was a driving force in introducing merchant banking
to the country.
<P>
Americans know Fay for his battles with Dennis Connoron and off the waterin the
America's Cup. In 1995, a successful Kiwi challenge brought the "Auld Mug" to New
Zealand for the first time.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
Other driving forces behind the Fund are Oliver Lee, Rodney Walshe and Patrick
Hogan. Lee presents a weekly Irish radio program heard throughout New Zealand.
"I'm very passionate about Ireland and also for the work the Ireland Funds do in
Ireland," says Oliver Lee. Rodney
Walshe, originally from Dublin, is Ireland's Honorary Consul based in Auckland.
<P>
Like the other eight countries where Ireland Funds exist, the Ireland Fund of New
Zealand relies on the generous support of the Irish community and friends of
Ireland to attend various functions. To date, these have included black tie
dinners for the President of Ireland Mary Robinson, and Dr. Tony O'Reilly, as
well as a premiere of Brian Friel's acclaimed play, "Dancing at Lughnasa." Plans
are well under way to organize a "Guinness and Oyster" garden party in March,
which hopefully will become an annual
fundraising event. Their most recent grant was to the Phoenix Trust in Belfast, a
community based employment and training centre.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p21b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p21b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
At an Ireland Fund of New Zealand fundraiser, Sir Michael Fay confers with fellow
Board Member Patrick Hogan.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p21c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="73" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p21c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
President of Ireland Mary Robinson addresses the Ireland Fund of New Zealand.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
</B>
