ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>
<H2>FRANCE</H2>
</CENTER>

<H3>France and Ireland: A Sustained Friendship</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="248" HEIGHT="228" SRC="graphics/p22a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
ANTIBES, FRANCE-In 1973, Ireland joined France as a member of the European
Economic Community (now the European Union), notes Pierre Joannon, Consul General
of Ireland in this splendid Riviera town on the Mediterranean coast. Today,
France is Ireland's third largest export market and more than 30 French factories
operate on Irish soil. Tourism is booming, too; more than 200,000 French
travelers visit Ireland every year.
<P>
 Close relations between France and Ireland, however, are nothing new. Links
between the two nations, Joannon adds, go back at least to the seventh century
A.D., when Irish missionaries including St. Columbanus ventured across the sea to
establish monasteries and centers of learning in Brittany and elsewhere.
<P>
 "The Ireland Fund of France was launched in Paris in 1990 to raise the level of
French understanding and concern about Ireland in every field," says Joannon, who
serves as Fund Chairman. Gala dinners and other
fundraising events have regularly been held both in Paris and Dublin.
<P>
 In 1993, the Ireland Fund of France established the Chryss O'Reilly Scholarships
through a personal grant by Chryss O'Reilly. The scholarship program allows young
Irish people, from North and South, to improve their language skills or pursue
studies abroad. O'Reilly Scholarship winners have included students from Queen's
University, Belfast; University College Cork; Trinity College, Dublin; and
University College Galway.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
In June 1969, President Charles de Gaulle of France paid an historic five-week
visit to Ireland following his defeat in a referendum that spelled the end of his
long political career. The General was descended on his maternal side from a
"Wild Geese" exile of the McCartan family and had always shown a keen interest in
his Irish roots. "We always come back to our origins," said de Gaulle.
<P>
In May 1994, the people of Sneem, co. Kerry where de Gaulle had stayed
twenty-five years before marked the anniversary by erecting a memorial stone in
the village. They also reenacted the General's famous
walk on Derrynane Strand. The event, organized by Sneem Development Association,
attracted considerable French interest and was grant-aided by the Ireland Fund of
France.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p22b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p22b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Members of the Board of Directors of the Ireland Fund of France (from left to
right) are Paula O'Rorke, Phillppe O'Rorke, Pierre Joannon, Tadhg O'Sullivan, and
Brid O'Sullivan.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>

</B>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH="532" HEIGHT="8" SRC="../../gfx/lnbreak2.gif"
ALT="____________________"></CENTER><BR>
