ALT="Forward" BORDER="0" ALIGN="MIDDLE"></A><BR>


<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>

<H2>JAPAN</H2>
</CENTER>
<H3>"Emerald Ball" heads list of Ireland Fund of Japan activities</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="240" HEIGHT="218" SRC="graphics/p23a.gif" ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>
TOKYO-The highlight of St. Patrick's Day 1995 was the third annual Emerald Ball,
sponsored by the Ireland Fund of Japan, reports Majella Murphy Altschuler, the
Fund President. Celebrating the day were over 500 guests and a host of individual
and corporate sponsors who made the event the most profitable fundraiser to date
for the Ireland Fund of Japan.
<P>
"Help from the philanthropic among the Japanese and international business
communities did wonders to ensure an exciting evening," said Maeve Gallagher,
chairperson.
<P>
 The Emerald Ball's many sponsors included Virgin Atlantic Airlines; Rover Japan;
and Apple Japan.
Special guests included the U.S. Ambassador to Japan Walter Mondale and Joan, his
wife; Irish Ambassador James Sharkey and Sattie, his wife.
Traditional and modern Irish music was provided by musicians Nick Kelly and James
McNally, who traveled from Ireland while the locally-based talent of Irish dancer
Yukiko Iwama and violinist Yuka Matsunuma kept
spirits high.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<P>
 IFJ members also participated in Tokyo's increasingly popular St. Patrick's Day
parade. Established in 1992 by the Irish Network Japan, the 1995 parade boasted
700 participants with over 30 organizations, and attracted over 3,000 spectators.
<P>
The Ireland Fund of Japan was officially launched on September 21, 1994. In
February 1995, President of Ireland Mary Robinson met with the Board and was
presented with a parchment copy of the Fund's constitution.
<P>
According to Majella Murphy Altschuler, the objectives of the Ireland Fund of
Japan include promotion of cultural exchanges between Ireland and Japan; support
for the activities of the Irish community and Irish friendship and cultural
organisations in Japan; and support for charitable
causes in Ireland and Japan.
<P>
"We plan to make grants annually to environmentally-friendly projects in both
Ireland and Japan," says Murphy Altschuler. For example, the IFJ will support
re-construction of a Kobe Community Center destroyed in the city's devastating
1995 earthquake, the Conservation Volunteers in Down, and the Oidhreacht Chorca
Dhuibhne (OCD) in Kerry. OCD is a cooperative in the Dingle Peninsula which has
been set up to promote community development and conserve the unique cultural,
historical and environmental features of the Irish speaking area.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p23b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p23b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Emerald Ball special guests Included (from left) Sattle Sharkey, Irish Ambassador
James Sharkey, Yuka Matsunuma, St. Patrick, Joan Mondale
and U.S. Ambassador Walter Mondale.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p23c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p23c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Kobe's Community Renter, recipient of an Ireland Fund of Japan grant.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
