<BR CLEAR="RIGHT">
<HR SIZE="4"> 
<B>
<CENTER>

<H2>SOUTH AFRICA</H2>
</CENTER>
<H3>Ireland Fund of South Africa</H3>

<IMG WIDTH="238" HEIGHT="250" SRC="graphics/p24a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10>
<BR>

JOHANNESBURG-The special goal of the Ireland Fund of South Africa is to raise
money in South Africa to fund projects within the country in the general areas of
education and training that involve Irish
organizations and individuals.
<P>
"The overall objective is to build closer links between Ireland and South Africa
and help build on the two countries' growing commercial relationship," notes Ivan
Fallon, Honorary Chairman for the inaugural dinner of the Ireland Fund of South
Africa in June, 1995.
<P>
"This fund will be driven by Irish money, using Irish teachers, nurses and
developers to help with skills training and educaion," Fallon adds. By raising
well over R200,000 (nearly $60,000), he adds, "we couldn't have
hoped for a better start."
<P>
South African Water Affairs Minister Kadar Asmal received the Fund's Bird and
Bell award at the dinner. Asmal spent 27 years in exile in Ireland during the
apartheid regime and was a law lecturer at Trinity College. "We need the skills
of Irish people to realize the dream of economic growth and re-distribution," he
said.
<P>
Among the 500 guests who attended the dinner was David Dinkins, former New York
City Mayor.
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<P>
Though never great in number, the Irish have had a marked impact on South Africa.
Most were independent adventurous young men and women who concentrated on
specific occupations, such as missionaries, retailers,
and mine laborers. Prominent South African-lrish of the past included premiers
Sir Thomas Upton and Sir Albert Hime; William Porter, author of the Cape's famous
color-blind franchise; and Solomon Gillingham, close
adviser to Paul Kruger.
<P>
<HR SIZE=3 WIDTH=80%>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p24b.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p24b-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
South Africa's Water Affairs Minister Kadar Asmal received the Bird and Bell
award.
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P>
<A HREF="graphics/p24c.gif"><IMG WIDTH="78" HEIGHT="63" SRC="graphics/p24c-sml.gif"
BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<BR>
Chryss O'Reilly and friends celebrate the Inaugural South African Dinner
<BR CLEAR=LEFT>

</B>
