<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Degrees in Computing Science at Newcastle</TITLE>
<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:Lindsay.Marshall@newcastle.ac.uk">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">Computing Science and Software Engineering at
<A HREF="http://www.ncl.ac.uk/">Newcastle</A></H1>

The last 30 years have seen startling advances in computer technology and
important developments in computer software.  Change is so rapid that it is
difficult to forecast even a few years ahead how the subject will progress and
what 'state-of-the-art' technology will be like.  Despite this, there are basic
principles in computing science which can be mastered, and in our degree
programmes at Newcastle we aim to enable you to understand these principles as
well as to appreciate the most recent advances.
<P>
We offer two BSc Single Honours degrees - in Computing Science and in Software
Engineering - which, through a range of  third-year options, allow you to
specialize in various topics in computing science including the development of
large-scale software systems. Our courses emphasize the techniques required to
develop systems and applications software, and provide an understanding of the
architecture of the systems on which the software runs. We encourage a
systematic approach to problem-solving and an analytical approach to the
evaluation of solutions - rather than, for example, concentrating on
present-day commercial applications of the software. In this way we equip you
with skills which you will be able to apply throughout your career. 
<P>
We are fortunate in having a large number of
<A HREF="http://www.cs.ncl.ac.uk/people/staff.html">staff</A>
with a wide range of
interests in computing.  We participate in major national and international
<A HREF="http://www.cs.ncl.ac.uk/research/">research</A>
projects and are one of only six universities to have consistently
received the highest possible research rating. Our research strengths in areas
such as safety critical systems, distributed systems and parallel computation
feed through to our undergraduate courses, and are reflected particularly in
the final-year options offered.

<H2>The Degree Programmes in Computing Science and Software Engineering</H2>

These two degrees, like all the others at Newcastle, are modular. This enables
us to cater for a range of qualifications and experience on entry; it also
offers flexibility in the degree to which you may concentrate on computing in
the first year and permits a high level of specialization in the final year.
The diagram shows the structure of the degree programmes:  in each year you
take 12 modules, since a module is one twelfth of a year's study time. The
modules are taught in two semesters, one running from October to February, the
other from February to July. There is a wide choice of final-year options.
<P>
Both degrees share the same first- and second-year courses, so transfer from
one to the other is straightforward up to the end of the second year.  This
means that you may apply for either degree and wait to see how your interests
develop during the first two years. You do not need to apply for both degrees.

<H3>First Year</H3>

Everyone takes modules in programming, software engineering, data structures
and algorithms plus maths at a level suitable for your previous experience
(GCSE, BTEC or A level). You may take further modules covering logic and
computer architecture, or a third subject (eg physics, economics, psychology)
or (for those without A level maths) an additional computing science course. As
the diagram shows, which first-year courses you take makes a slight difference
to your choice of second-year modules.

<H4>Programming and Software Engineering (2 modules)</H4>

This course introduces
and develops programming concepts, taking an approach based on object-oriented
design and abstract data types, and using the programming language C++.

<H4>Data Structures and Algorithms (2 modules)</H4>
This covers some of the
fundamental data structures and algorithms for organizing collections of data,
together with their efficiency, implementation and application to a variety of
practical problems.

<H4>Logic and Computer Architecture (2 or 4 modules)</H4>
You explore the ideas
which underpin the development of both software and hardware systems, including
the appropriate mathematics.  The computer architecture course covers the
operation of the components of a typical computing system and study of a
low-level programming language.  In the logic design course you look at ways of
combining elementary logic components to perform more complex operations such
as arithmetic.

<H3>Second Year</H3>

Together with the modules taken in the first year, the 12 second-year modules
form a compulsory 'core' of material in Computing Science. (If you did not take
the Logic and Computer Architecture modules in the first year, you take them
now and defer some of the core modules to the final year - see diagram.) All
modules include practical work which contributes to your final assessment.
<P>
The modules relate to four themes:

<H4>Programming Techniques </H4>
<DL>
<DT>3 modules:
<DD>Programming Language Principles
<DD>Concurrent Programming
<DD>File Systems and Data Bases
</DL>
You study a wide range of programming languages, gaining practical experience
of their different applications and a theoretical grasp of the relationships
between the languages, file structures and the management of information.

<H4>Software Engineering</H4>

<DL>
<DT>3 modules:
<DD>Software Engineering 1
<DD>Software Engineering 2
<DD>Group Project and Professional Issues
</DL>
In this course you examine each stage in the development of a software system -
analysis of the requirements it is to meet; development of a specification;
design and implementation of the software; testing, evaluation, maintenance and
documentation of the system. 
<P>
The group project gives you experience of collaborative work and of project
planning and management. Topics are divided between the various groups of
students, so that each has to combine its own work with that of another group.
This involves each group in planning sales and purchase strategies and in
coordinating the integration of the software. The assessment of the projects
includes an element of  self-assessment by members of the group.

<H4>Systems</H4>
<DL>
<DT>3 modules:
<DD>Computer Networks
<DD>Advanced Computer Architecture
<DD>Compilers and Operating Systems
</DL>
This covers computer architecture - the structure rather than the detailed
electronics of hardware systems - examines both hardware and software aspects
of communications systems and introduces the main topics concerning the
implementation of operating systems and compilers.

<H4>Algorithms</H4>
<DL>
<DT>3 modules:
<DD>Algorithms 1
<DD>Algorithms 2
<DD>Numerical Algorithms
</DL>
These are systematic methods for constructing solutions to problems.  You
examine a range of them considering their design, implementation, efficiency
and application.

<H3>Third Year</H3>

The range of options for the Advanced Topics changes constantly to keep pace
with rapid developments in the subject, and in recent years more than 20 have
been offered. Typical choices have included:
<UL>
<LI>Applications in Artificial Intelligence
<LI>Operating Systems
<LI>Distributed Computer Systems
<LI>Parallel Computation
<LI>Reliability and Fault Tolerance
<LI>VLSI Design
<LI>Real Time Systems
<LI>Human-Computer Interaction
<LI>Computer Graphics
</UL>
An individual third-year project represents one quarter of your final year's
work. These projects vary widely but have recently included:
<UL>
<LI>Air Traffic Control Simulator
<LI>A Computing Adventure
<LI>Metro Map
<LI>An Electronic Campus Walk
<LI>Interactive Video
</UL>

<H2>Computing Science - a flexible approach</H2>

<H3>Should I have any previous experience of computing?</H3>

Obviously, many applicants do have experience of computing, but a real interest
in the subject (both its practical and intellectual aspects) is more important
than specific experience.  You do not need to have taken computing science at
GCSE or A level, but we do not limit the opportunities available to more
experienced students.

<H3>What maths do I need?</H3>

Our Computing Science and Software Engineering degree programmes are open to
students with Maths GCSE (Grade B or better) or an equivalent qualifacation
such as a Merit in BTEC Quantitative Methods, as well as to those with A level
or equivalent.  We achieve this by offering a range of first-year maths courses
at different levels: you take the one which best suits your previous
experience.  The diagram shows where this fits into the first-year programme.

<H2>Industrial Experience</H2>

Some of our students have sponsorship from leading companies which offers them
vacation work in industry, and British Telecom offers sponsorship on a
competitive basis for our Computing Science and Software Engineering degrees.
Our degree programmes are not sandwich courses but if you wish to spend a year
in industry between the second and third years of your degree, you may do so if
you can make suitable arrangements.  One of our students recently won a place
to spend an industrial year with British Airways .

<H2>Study Abroad</H2>

We have links with European universities through the ERASMUS scheme, which
enables some of our students to study for a year in another EC country.
Exchanges have been made with the Universities of Rennes, Vienna and Munich and
visiting students from these universities provide an international perspective
even for students who remain in Newcastle.

<H2>Computing Combined with Other Subjects</H2>

Computing Science may be taken as an option in Joint Honours Science with any
of the following: economics, mathematics, physics, psychology, statistics or
surveying and mapping science.  Half your time is spent on computing science
and the other half on the other subject. Computing Science is also available
within the Combined Studies BA Honours degree, enabling you to combine it with
up to four other subjects, mostly from the arts and social sciences.
Major-Minor degrees consisting of one third computing and two thirds French or
German or Spanish are offered by the School of Modern Languages. In all these
degree programmes, the computing science courses are taken from those available
within Single Honours Computing Science. Further details of all these
programmes are given in the Prospectus and in various brochures available from
the Admissions Office. 

<H2>Computing in the Faculty of Engineering</H2>

There is now a rapidly-growing need for engineers who can understand the full
range of design problems, from specifying a VLSI chip to building sophisticated
software to make use of it, and it is essential that these experts understand
both the hardware and the software of the systems.  To meet this demand we have
established two degree programmes in conjunction with the Department of
Electrical and Electronic Engineering: the BEng (a three-year degree) and the
MEng (four years) in Microelectronics and Software Engineering.  A brochure
giving further details is available from the Admissions Office or the
Department of Electrical and Electronic Engineering.

<H2>Transfer to and from other degree programmes</H2>

Most of our students are committed to their choice of computing science or
software engineering and follow that degree programme through the three years.
However, each year some choose to transfer to related programmes at the end of
the first year.  While such transfers cannot be guaranteed and are subject to
various restrictions, typical moves include transfer to Joint Honours in
Computing Science plus another subject which you have already taken in the
first year (eg maths, statistics or your third subject); transfer to Combined
Studies or to Single Honours Maths or to Single Honours in your third
first-year subject. Of course some students who start in these subjects
transfer to Computing Science!

<H2>Entrance Requirements</H2>

We take applicants with a wide range of qualifications - A level, BTEC and
Scottish Highers and CSYS. You should have at least grade B in maths at GCSE or
equivalent,  or a pass in BTEC Quantitative Methods if you do not have it at A
level. Candidates who are uncertain about the level of their qualifications
should contact us before applying to discuss their individual circumstances.
<P>
Grades required can vary from year to year so you should check the current
estimates in this year's Prospectus.  The Prospectus also gives details of
entrance requirements for Joint Honours, Combined Studies, Major-Minor and
other degrees.
<P>
We welcome applications from mature students, with or without traditional
qualifications. Newcastle College runs an access course which equips successful
candidates for entry to our degree programmes. For further details about this,
please contact the Admissions Tutor, <A HREF="#info">Dr Lindsay Marshall</A>.
<P>
Overseas students are also very welcome; those with sufficient experience in
maths and computing may, in exceptional circumstances, be eligible for entry
direct into the second year. A Bridging Course for overseas students, run in
conjunction with Newcastle College, is available for those without the
necessary background in maths and computing; it also provides English language
tuition. Please contact <A HREF="#info">Dr Marshall</A> for further details. 
<P>
We invite candidates to whom we are going to make an offer to visit the
Department for an open day to meet current students and staff, to find out more
about the courses and to see our computing facilities.  This is intended to
help you to make your final choice of university.

<H2>The Resources of the Department</H2>

We have an extensive computer network which links a wide range of computers,
from large powerful systems down to the smallest microprocessor system.  A
considerable number of workstations available to undergraduates provides access
to the systems attached to this network, and powerful special-purpose equipment
is available for research projects.  These systems are also connected to
national and international computer networks, which give staff and students
access to electronic media, keeping them in touch with computing colleagues
around the world.  Our computer systems are continually updated to take
advantage of the latest technological developments. Students who already own a
Macintosh or PC system can make use of it, but this is by no means essential.
<P>
<IMG SRC="apple.gif" ALT="" WIDTH="360" HEIGHT="232">
<H2>Life in the Department</H2>

The Department has a lively, friendly atmosphere and first-year undergraduates
quickly get to know other students and members of staff. The Computing Society,
run by the students, organizes other social events throughout the year, as well
as lectures from visiting speakers.  Departmental common rooms act as a focus
for social life for second- and third-year undergraduates.  More seriously, the
Staff-Student Committee and student representation on other departmental
committees give you the chance to contribute to discussions and influence
decisions about courses and other aspects of departmental life.

<H2>Careers</H2>

In the present job market computing science graduates are better placed than
many others to obtain employment in a challenging and fulfilling career.
Specialists are recruited by computing manufacturers and software houses (who
write programs for customers), and all graduates with good knowledge of
computing may be employed by any organization which uses computers on a large
scale - banks, insurance companies, the electronics industry, central and local
government, and management in all areas of business.
<P>
A significant number of our undergraduates continue with their studies as MSc
or PhD students. Follow <A HREF="profiles.html">this link</A> to find
some profiles of past and present students.

<A NAME=info><H2>Further Information</H2></A>

If you have any further questions about the Computing Science or Software
Engineering degree programmes, please write to: 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<ADDRESS>
